WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
[Amit Varma]: One of my favorite quotes about writing comes from the great Susan Sontag, who said,

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:14.960
[Amit Varma]: quote, a writer is someone who pays attention to the world, stop quote.

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, that might seem banal, don't we all pay attention to the world?

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:23.320
[Amit Varma]: The truth is that we don't, all of us tend to get drawn into a comfort zone, not just

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:28.240
[Amit Varma]: in terms of physical spaces, but also the mental maps we draw of the world, the frames

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:32.480
[Amit Varma]: of reference with which we see everything around us, even the universe of acceptable

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:35.620
[Amit Varma]: facts outside of which no facts matter.

00:00:35.620 --> 00:00:37.520
[Amit Varma]: This is why art is so important.

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:42.320
[Amit Varma]: It can take us outside of ourselves, even into someone else's head in someone else's

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:43.320
[Amit Varma]: life.

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:47.480
[Amit Varma]: This is also why journalism and narrative nonfiction are so important.

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:52.240
[Amit Varma]: They can reveal a part of the world in such vivid detail that we come alive for a moment

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:54.120
[Amit Varma]: and see everything differently.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:59.400
[Amit Varma]: This is why Tom Wolfe once said, quote, nonfiction is the most important literature to come out

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:02.920
[Amit Varma]: of the second half of the 20th century, stop quote.

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:07.840
[Amit Varma]: And in times which are so complex, when we are surrounded by such simplistic narratives,

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:12.720
[Amit Varma]: I would argue that we need nonfiction more than ever before to make sense of this world

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:29.200
[Unknown]: we live in.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:30.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:35.600
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Saman Subramanian, a journalist whose narrative nonfiction has appeared in

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:40.320
[Amit Varma]: publications like the New Yorker, the New York Times, the Guardian, Wired, Harper's,

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:41.320
[Amit Varma]: and many, many more.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:47.320
[Amit Varma]: He is also the author of three acclaimed books, the most recent of which is a dominant character,

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:50.560
[Amit Varma]: the Radical Science and Restless Politics of J.B.S.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:51.560
[Amit Varma]: Haldane.

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:55.440
[Amit Varma]: Samanth is also a legendary Indian quizzer, and he used to be my colleague at Crickin

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:00.760
[Amit Varma]: for around 17 years ago, which is so far back that if you wrote a book about it today, it

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:03.160
[Amit Varma]: would qualify as a book of history.

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:07.000
[Amit Varma]: I was eager to get him on the scene and the unseen to talk about his new book, and I also

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.640
[Amit Varma]: wanted to chat with him about an art he has mastered, the art of narrative nonfiction.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:15.880
[Amit Varma]: So this episode is therefore an episode of two halves.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:20.560
[Amit Varma]: The first is about writing, and the second is about Saman's book on J.B.S.

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:26.560
[Amit Varma]: Haldane, which is a fascinating study of a great scientist and a flawed human being.

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:32.760
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to a conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:36.320
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to the scene and the unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:37.600
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

