[Amit Varma]: Scene unseen.in slash support.

00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:53.080
[Amit Varma]: Samanth, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:54.080
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Samanth.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.360
[Guest]: It's a pleasure to be here.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:59.800
[Amit Varma]: Samanth, you know, before we get started and get to this book, let's talk a bit about sort

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:02.760
[Amit Varma]: of your personal life and your personal journey.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:06.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, I've known you for a long time, we were, of course, colleagues at Quickenpho.

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:11.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so I've known you as a quizzer, as a writer, and as someone who's always also

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:16.760
[Amit Varma]: very interestingly thinking at a meta level about these things, and writing about them

00:04:16.760 --> 00:04:17.760
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.840
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about, you know, how you grew up, how did you become a quizzer?

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:23.280
[Amit Varma]: Were you a voracious reader?

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:24.920
[Guest]: What were your early influences like?

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:26.480
[Guest]: I think I was always a reader.

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:30.640
[Guest]: I mean, I started, I remember the first sort of book of quote, unquote, serious literature

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:33.680
[Guest]: that I read was Smith's Journalist by P.G.

00:04:33.680 --> 00:04:39.040
[Guest]: Woodhouse, which somebody gave me back in the day, very sort of prophetically, I guess.

00:04:39.040 --> 00:04:42.680
[Guest]: And I was, you know, until then, I'd been reading comic books and adventure novels like

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:47.080
[Guest]: the Hardy Boys, and this gave me a taste of what a real book could do and what real language

00:04:47.080 --> 00:04:48.080
[Guest]: could do.

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:49.080
[Guest]: And I think that sort of hooked me.

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.720
[Guest]: And so throughout my childhood, that was what I did.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:54.040
[Guest]: You know, I was not a very sporty kid.

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:55.040
[Guest]: I was asthmatic.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:58.140
[Guest]: And so there was not a lot of activities I could pursue outside.

00:04:58.140 --> 00:05:00.480
[Guest]: And so I would stay indoors and read.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:04.840
[Guest]: And I think my quizzing sort of came out of that, because when I read, I found that I

00:05:04.840 --> 00:05:09.880
[Guest]: was reasonably good at retaining what I read, but more importantly, I used to like to read

00:05:09.880 --> 00:05:15.440
[Guest]: across genres, across topics, you know, not just fiction at the time, but, you know, nonfiction

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:16.880
[Guest]: of all kinds.

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:22.440
[Guest]: And I would even sort of, as the cliche goes, read the newspaper packets in which the roasted

00:05:22.440 --> 00:05:25.040
[Guest]: peanuts were sold, when they were sold to you.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:28.640
[Guest]: So, you know, I mean, I was that kind of reader.

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:32.680
[Guest]: And the quizzing, I think, started when I was in school, and I've just sort of never

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:33.680
[Guest]: given it up.

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:38.120
[Guest]: I think I started around the ninth grade in Chennai, where I was living at the time.

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:43.760
[Guest]: And it was just, it was such a sort of good community of people and such an interactive

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:48.160
[Guest]: activity at the time that I just, I decided I just wanted to do this all the time.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:49.920
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of talk a bit about quizzing.

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:52.880
[Amit Varma]: You wrote the superb piece on quizzing for the Guardian, which of course I link from

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.480
[Amit Varma]: the show notes, where at one point, you said, quote, whatever I'm doing at any point of

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.020
[Amit Varma]: the day, it's probably safe to assume that I would rather be quizzing, stop quote.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:04.720
[Amit Varma]: And at another point, you say you drink to forget, you quiz to remember.

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:09.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the things I was struck by was how you referred to a friend of yours

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:13.440
[Amit Varma]: calling quizzing an act of bricolage, you know, a term that Levi Strauss used to talk

00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:17.720
[Amit Varma]: about how, you know, different small ideas can be mixed and, you know, bring about something

00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:22.680
[Amit Varma]: new, which seems to me to be both sort of a theme of, you know, a guiding philosophy

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:27.520
[Amit Varma]: of Haldane himself, and we'll get to the book shortly, but also something that also seems

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:32.480
[Amit Varma]: to drive you in the sense that the subjects that you've written on are very eclectic and

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:33.760
[Amit Varma]: varied.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And it seems that even when you wrote about cricket, for example, you brought a lens to

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.160
[Amit Varma]: it, which was not necessarily off cricket, you've spoken about how, you know, when you

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:47.720
[Amit Varma]: wrote about cricket, you looked at it as a metaphor for bigger things.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:51.780
[Amit Varma]: So it's almost, you know, as I said earlier, that you're kind of stepping back from every

00:06:51.780 --> 00:06:55.860
[Amit Varma]: subject you're writing about, and you're applying all of these different things.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:58.080
[Amit Varma]: Is that how you see yourself as well?

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:01.080
[Amit Varma]: And is that part of you know, what makes you a very good quizzer?

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And then what drives your writing that it's not just a subject you're writing about, you're

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:06.160
[Guest]: bringing everything to the table?

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:07.160
[Guest]: That's an interesting question.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.160
[Guest]: Okay.

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:09.160
[Guest]: So there's two things here.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:14.920
[Guest]: One is just what you might call in whatever limited form it is, my philosophy of writing

00:07:14.920 --> 00:07:15.920
[Guest]: or of journalism.

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.480
[Guest]: And we can come to that later, because maybe there's more to be said about that.

00:07:18.480 --> 00:07:25.000
[Guest]: But the second is just, as you put it, is this kind of magpie-like obsession and fascination

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.940
[Guest]: with small, interesting things.

00:07:27.940 --> 00:07:32.360
[Guest]: And then also sort of a curiosity to see what all those things build into.

00:07:32.360 --> 00:07:36.520
[Guest]: You know, I think a lot of this comes from people that you and I would both have read

00:07:36.520 --> 00:07:37.520
[Guest]: when we were growing up.

00:07:37.520 --> 00:07:42.280
[Guest]: You know, for example, in the 90s, still, for a lot of people, the archetypal cricket

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:43.520
[Guest]: writer was Cardus.

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:48.120
[Guest]: And Cardus famously was a music critic for the Manchester Guardian, even as he was a

00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:49.440
[Guest]: cricket writer.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:52.760
[Guest]: And he brought that same approach to his cricket writing, in my opinion.

00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:57.680
[Guest]: He brought a knowledge of the world with him when he went into the stadium to watch.

00:07:57.680 --> 00:08:02.460
[Guest]: And it was not just a question of analyzing the game for its own sake, but a question

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:04.720
[Guest]: of drawing bigger themes out of it.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:09.720
[Guest]: I think that is interesting to me, because once you have perfected is too strong a word,

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:13.480
[Guest]: but once you become addicted to that approach, you can then apply it to anything.

00:08:13.480 --> 00:08:17.240
[Guest]: You can kind of read and write about science, and you can draw these themes out.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:20.800
[Guest]: You can look at sport, you can look at art and culture.

00:08:20.800 --> 00:08:26.600
[Guest]: It's all in the process itself, the process of viewing, of regarding these subjects as

00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:27.840
[Guest]: an outsider.

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.320
[Guest]: And the thing is that we will always be an outsider.

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:35.600
[Guest]: I mean, in cricket writing, for example, there is always the eternal conundrum of why people

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:40.120
[Guest]: who are not able to play a James Anderson delivery should be writing about how this

00:08:40.120 --> 00:08:43.400
[Guest]: batsman out in the cricket field should be doing that.

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:46.320
[Guest]: We are not able to do it, why should we comment on it?

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.320
[Guest]: And I know a number of cricketers who have held this view in the past.

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:55.400
[Guest]: But I think to bring this particular philosophy of viewing and regarding and analyzing to

00:08:55.400 --> 00:09:00.960
[Guest]: bear is to privilege that outsider-ness to a certain extent, and to privilege what the

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:04.440
[Guest]: outsider brings by way of insight and perception.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:06.360
[Guest]: So I think that's where all of this comes from.

00:09:06.360 --> 00:09:07.600
[Guest]: And bricolage is a part of that.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:11.960
[Guest]: I mean, the quizzing is a part of that in the sense that you are reading about and learning

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:15.320
[Guest]: about secondhand or even thirdhand a lot of these topics.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:19.680
[Guest]: But in your own particular way, they somehow add up into something, you know, a larger

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:24.000
[Guest]: answer, or if you're setting a question, a larger question, which is interesting in its

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.800
[Amit Varma]: own right in that particular moment.

00:09:25.800 --> 00:09:29.560
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of larger questions relating to what you just said.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:34.600
[Amit Varma]: But a couple of mundane things that I'm genuinely curious about that, you know, for the benefit

00:09:34.600 --> 00:09:38.520
[Amit Varma]: of my listeners, I tell them that, you know, when Samant and I were colleagues at Cricken

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:43.440
[Amit Varma]: for long ago, and I hadn't heard of his quizzing prowess at the time, to me, he was just another

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:44.440
[Amit Varma]: young colleague.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:47.260
[Amit Varma]: And there was a quiz we heard about in Mulund of all places.

00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:48.480
[Amit Varma]: And our office was in Andheri.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:50.440
[Amit Varma]: And we said, let's go and take part.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:54.200
[Amit Varma]: So we went as a team in this rickety auto all the way to Mulund.

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:58.280
[Amit Varma]: And basically, what happened in the quiz was Samant answered every single question and

00:09:58.280 --> 00:09:59.860
[Amit Varma]: just won it on his own.

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:03.760
[Amit Varma]: And everybody else, including me was kind of like a spectator after which, you know,

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:07.600
[Amit Varma]: I think one gentleman in the audience came to you and said, Are you that guy from Chennai,

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:10.440
[Amit Varma]: who wears a cap backwards?

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:12.840
[Amit Varma]: And it then turned out that you were a legend.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And that was like an iconic image of you with that cap backwards and all that.

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:21.400
[Amit Varma]: So the mundane questions I sort of want to get out is regarding A, your reading habits

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:25.960
[Amit Varma]: and B, then your attention habits, because obviously, you know, all regular quizzers

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:30.680
[Amit Varma]: in the circuit that you are part of, and I was very briefly part of, not good enough

00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:35.560
[Amit Varma]: to stay there for a while, all of us, you know, look askance at the notion that quizzers

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:38.120
[Amit Varma]: are just memorizing stuff and memorizing facts.

00:10:38.120 --> 00:10:42.280
[Amit Varma]: So there is an element of that you've wrote in your Guardian piece about how Pat Gibson

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:47.080
[Amit Varma]: keeps Excel files, and you know, he'll have across categories, he'll give different files

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:49.440
[Amit Varma]: and note down up to 100 facts a day.

00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:53.440
[Amit Varma]: But you know, most quizzers when they quiz, it's like a deductive process, you're bringing

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:57.920
[Amit Varma]: all your knowledge to bear and you're really working out problems as such.

00:10:57.920 --> 00:11:02.900
[Amit Varma]: So my sort of two part question is that, what was the process of retention like barring

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:07.800
[Amit Varma]: the fact that you read very widely, did you also have to take specific efforts to make

00:11:07.800 --> 00:11:10.600
[Amit Varma]: sure you remembered or categorized information?

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:12.440
[Amit Varma]: And apart from that, what was your reading like?

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:13.440
[Amit Varma]: And what is your reading like?

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:14.440
[Amit Varma]: How much would you read?

00:11:14.440 --> 00:11:15.440
[Amit Varma]: How would you pick what you read?

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:18.480
[Guest]: There's a cultural difference here, actually, which is quite interesting.

00:11:18.480 --> 00:11:21.800
[Guest]: And my, you know, I didn't have time to get into in my Guardian piece.

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:26.160
[Guest]: But it's it might be interesting for our listeners here, which is that in the US and in the UK,

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:31.720
[Guest]: quizzing is is about memorization and memory and retention to a far greater extent than

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:32.720
[Guest]: it is in India.

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:36.040
[Guest]: So you know, the Pat Gibsons of the world when they compete to compete in something

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:41.360
[Guest]: like the World Quizzing Championship, a lot of their prowess comes from having, you know,

00:11:41.360 --> 00:11:46.040
[Guest]: created these databases and these lists of facts, which they then sort of revise almost,

00:11:46.040 --> 00:11:49.240
[Guest]: it's very much a student like activity over here.

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:53.320
[Guest]: It's not like that in India, I feel I mean, India is my big theory about this is that

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:57.440
[Guest]: Indian quizzing has grown up as a reaction to Indian education, because Indian education

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:04.320
[Guest]: is already so steep in rote learning and memorization that Indian quizzing is like some form of

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:07.960
[Guest]: lateral thinking exercise that has grown up as a reaction to that.

00:12:07.960 --> 00:12:12.720
[Guest]: And so in India, the quizzing revolves largely around what you might call the interesting

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:17.240
[Guest]: bit of trivia, the piece of information that sits at slightly odd angles to the rest of

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:18.240
[Guest]: the world.

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:21.280
[Guest]: And just because of that oddity, you remember it as soon as you read it.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:25.800
[Guest]: I mean, it's just, it's not an effort to memorize it in any particular way.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:30.540
[Guest]: And so I think I have never and I know a number of my friends and colleagues in the quizzing

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:35.680
[Guest]: world have never gone in for the pure retention exercise, I mean, the truth is definitely

00:12:35.680 --> 00:12:40.160
[Guest]: that we all have possibly quite good memories, and we will remember a lot of what we read

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:43.400
[Guest]: because we read widely, we tend to just remember a lot of those things.

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:47.000
[Guest]: But that's never the it is the basis, but that is never the key.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.560
[Guest]: The key to unlock a lot of these Baroque Indian quiz questions is a particular kind of lateral

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:56.160
[Guest]: thinking that kicks in, depending on the framing of the question.

00:12:56.160 --> 00:13:01.720
[Guest]: And these facts that as I said, slip sit at slightly odd angles to the rest of the world.

00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:05.080
[Guest]: So that is the charm of Indian quizzing, I feel.

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:09.960
[Guest]: And so retention is important, but secondary, in my opinion, in terms of importance.

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:14.720
[Guest]: My reading itself has tended to I mean, vary over the years, as all of us have experienced,

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:19.600
[Guest]: you know, I used to read a lot more fiction than I do now, to my regret, I went through

00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:24.120
[Guest]: a phase, I think about five or six years ago, when I realized, you know, I kind of looked

00:13:24.120 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: back upon my calendar year, and I realized I had just not read that many books.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.040
[Guest]: And this was, of course, again, something we've all experienced the profusion of the

00:13:32.040 --> 00:13:33.840
[Guest]: internet and various other things.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.280
[Guest]: And I was reading and I continue to read a lot of magazine pieces because of my own work.

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:41.120
[Guest]: And so that takes out a lot of my reading time.

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:45.720
[Guest]: And so I decided I would make a conscious effort to read more books.

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.560
[Guest]: For one year, I set a target of a book a week at least to read more challenging books, I

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:54.800
[Guest]: felt that habit had gone out of the window to sort of read books that maybe you have

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:59.260
[Guest]: to read passages two or three times to get the import of that.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:00.400
[Guest]: So I started doing that.

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:02.240
[Guest]: And it's gone reasonably well.

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:05.520
[Guest]: Some months are better than others, you read a lot for work anyway.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:09.120
[Guest]: So sometimes at the end of the day, the last thing you want to do is pick up yet another

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:10.120
[Guest]: book.

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:13.960
[Guest]: But the range is there, fortunately, and partly that this is because of the eclectic range

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:16.600
[Guest]: of topics that I work on for my journalism.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:21.200
[Guest]: So you tend to read across subjects anyway, but then also, my own interests just lie in

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:22.200
[Guest]: different fields.

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:26.360
[Guest]: So I will look at book reviews and try to figure out what is new and interesting that

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:27.800
[Guest]: I might pick up.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:32.160
[Guest]: So right now, for example, I'm reading this book by the philosopher Daniel Dennett called

00:14:32.160 --> 00:14:37.520
[Guest]: Darwin's Dangerous Idea, which is an extremely dense and very, very rigorously thought out

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:42.880
[Guest]: piece of writing about how the idea of natural selection Darwin's idea of natural selection,

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:47.920
[Guest]: the world, but also sort of why it was dangerous in the sense of how it upset a lot of preconceived

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:52.740
[Guest]: notions about the world, and how those preconceived notions were put in place by the power structures

00:14:52.740 --> 00:14:55.600
[Guest]: that were around in the 19th century.

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:59.360
[Guest]: And so how it was, quote, unquote, dangerous to all of these power structures, but it goes

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:00.360
[Guest]: far beyond that.

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:04.800
[Guest]: I mean, he goes into computer science and algorithms, and he goes into systems and how

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:06.620
[Guest]: systems and processes work.

00:15:06.620 --> 00:15:11.880
[Guest]: It's very much a magpie like approach to evolution and natural selection, which is why I was

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:14.760
[Guest]: attracted to the book when I first read about it.

00:15:14.760 --> 00:15:18.120
[Guest]: And it's definitely one of those extremely difficult books, because you have to kind

00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:22.000
[Guest]: of immerse yourself in it for a month at least to get a sense of it.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.160
[Guest]: And so obviously, in the middle of all of that, I will sometimes read as I did this

00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:27.160
[Guest]: time, detective stories.

00:15:27.160 --> 00:15:31.120
[Guest]: So I read A Perfect Murder by HRF Pete Keating, which I've been meaning to get to for a long

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:32.120
[Guest]: time.

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:36.160
[Guest]: So it's, it's, as I said, it's, it's varied and weird and quite whimsical sometimes.

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:40.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I read Darwin's Dangerous Idea a few years ago and love as well as Consciousness

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:44.920
[Amit Varma]: Evolved, which is another book by him, which is sort of sitting right here, very rewarding,

00:15:44.920 --> 00:15:45.920
[Amit Varma]: right?

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:50.040
[Amit Varma]: I just realized that, you know, one thing that kind of resuscitated my own reading habit

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:54.840
[Amit Varma]: was that when I started doing the podcast, I had to read a lot for research, often multiple

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:56.840
[Amit Varma]: books for a particular episode.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:16:01.720
[Amit Varma]: And then just the practice of reading so many books for work also makes it easier to read

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:02.720
[Amit Varma]: it for leisure.

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:06.280
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that's the case with you also, as you said, but thought that strikes me.

00:16:06.280 --> 00:16:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And this is something that came up in the last episode I recorded with Russ Roberts

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:12.520
[Amit Varma]: of Econ Talk fame as well.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:17.680
[Amit Varma]: You know, is that how much the technology around us and the gadgets around us can change

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:23.800
[Amit Varma]: who we are as a people by changing our experience of how we imbibe knowledge.

00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:26.140
[Amit Varma]: Like back in the day, if you're reading a book, you're taking a book, you're sitting

00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:27.280
[Amit Varma]: down with it.

00:16:27.280 --> 00:16:29.880
[Amit Varma]: And there isn't that much distracting you relatively.

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:33.740
[Amit Varma]: I mean, those lack of distractions also indicate why for so many decades test cricket was so

00:16:33.740 --> 00:16:34.920
[Amit Varma]: popular in India.

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:40.360
[Amit Varma]: But today we are sort of surrounded by distractions and what these distractions inevitably mean

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:46.480
[Amit Varma]: is that we are constantly in a state of shallow skimming that we rarely have the time and

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:50.760
[Amit Varma]: the attentional bandwidth to be able to immerse ourselves in something.

00:16:50.760 --> 00:16:55.120
[Amit Varma]: So a lot of people like I find that when I'm not actually sitting and reading a book, I'm

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:59.480
[Amit Varma]: not reading anything, you know, longest stuff on the internet or whatever, you know, it's

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:04.480
[Amit Varma]: just you're on social media, you're chasing different dopamine rushes, Twitter notifications

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:09.360
[Amit Varma]: or Facebook likes, and how you discover content is you're following links from here and there.

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:12.680
[Amit Varma]: And if you want to know something about a subject, you'll do a quick Google search and

00:17:12.680 --> 00:17:17.520
[Amit Varma]: you might read a couple of articles in the Wikipedia page, but it's all incredibly shallow.

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:22.440
[Amit Varma]: And because the knowledge that we consume and which is our learning, therefore, is what

00:17:22.440 --> 00:17:27.880
[Amit Varma]: shapes us as people, you know, would say either of us have been grown up to be different people

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:28.880
[Amit Varma]: if we were kids.

00:17:28.880 --> 00:17:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Today, I don't know.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I'm just kind of thinking aloud.

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:35.520
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I always say the guy who has a lot to answer for in the history of technology

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:40.280
[Guest]: is a guy who invented the alt tab shortcut has basically kind of completely destroyed

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: us in that single stroke.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.840
[Guest]: I mean, it's interesting, because, you know, 20 years down, we look at kids who grew up

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:48.040
[Guest]: today, we'll see the kind of work that they do.

00:17:48.040 --> 00:17:51.560
[Guest]: I mean, in the sense of both creative work, because creative work, I think requires some

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:56.280
[Guest]: sort of sustained attention to what you're doing, but also other forms of work.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:00.680
[Guest]: And maybe there's a, you know, you, for example, have been writing and thinking about TikTok

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:01.680
[Guest]: a lot.

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:04.800
[Guest]: And TikTok as a form of creativity is quite ripe for our age, right?

00:18:04.800 --> 00:18:06.920
[Guest]: I mean, it's that short attention span.

00:18:06.920 --> 00:18:10.820
[Guest]: But how creative you can be within those confines is something that I guess we will only find

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:14.720
[Guest]: out once all of this has reached a certain kind of fruition and maturity.

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:17.800
[Guest]: And we can look back upon it and assess it on its own terms.

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:23.480
[Guest]: I mean, right now, TikTok is mostly a diversion, sometimes a Chinese security threat, but not

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:27.800
[Guest]: yet kind of full fledged, creative form in its own right.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:31.480
[Guest]: I mean, and we'll have to see what kind of creative fruit this bears.

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:35.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I'm a big fan of TikTok, because what all of this shallow surfing could also

00:18:35.640 --> 00:18:40.300
[Amit Varma]: indicate is, it would enable a different kind of bricolage.

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:47.200
[Amit Varma]: But to sort of get back to the couple of questions I had, from what you said earlier, one is,

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:49.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, you often looked at cricket as a metaphor for other things.

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:54.760
[Amit Varma]: If you're writing about subject X, you'll also bring to bear upon it, a larger view

00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:57.880
[Amit Varma]: of the world and of society and all of those things.

00:18:57.880 --> 00:19:03.240
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that there is also a danger in that, for example, you've also spoken about

00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:07.960
[Amit Varma]: how, I mean, all writers will speak about how you want to avoid cliched language.

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:11.320
[Amit Varma]: You've also said you want to avoid cliched ideas.

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:12.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's also important.

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:14.340
[Amit Varma]: And that's something that you're conscious of.

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that the danger of sort of, you know, having these different lenses

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:23.380
[Amit Varma]: through which you look at the world, and applying it to different things, the danger can also

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:27.920
[Amit Varma]: be that, you know, you have a bunch of hammers, and you apply one of them to every nail.

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:29.400
[Amit Varma]: And you're not kind of going beyond that.

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:32.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just as an example, thinking aloud, you know, if you look at something like the

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:37.840
[Amit Varma]: IPL, for example, depending on your ideology, you can come at the IPL either from a point

00:19:37.840 --> 00:19:42.320
[Amit Varma]: of view of, oh, this is capitalist greed, and this is a corruption of what the spirit

00:19:42.320 --> 00:19:43.840
[Amit Varma]: of the game is all about.

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, longer cricket reveals character and blah, blah, blah.

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:49.480
[Amit Varma]: And you can bemoan the commercialization.

00:19:49.480 --> 00:19:53.640
[Amit Varma]: If you come from another ideological lens, and you can talk about that, no, it empowers

00:19:53.640 --> 00:19:56.520
[Amit Varma]: so many people and expands the reach of the game.

00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:58.320
[Amit Varma]: And look, it's got women viewing the game.

00:19:58.320 --> 00:20:02.560
[Amit Varma]: And so many more cricketers make money from the game and the incentives for kids coming

00:20:02.560 --> 00:20:06.200
[Amit Varma]: into the game have changed for the better, and all of those things.

00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:12.240
[Amit Varma]: And danger there is that, you know, whatever lens you bring to bear, it expands your view,

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:16.100
[Amit Varma]: because you're obviously not just looking at, you know, the sport alone or IPL alone,

00:20:16.100 --> 00:20:17.920
[Amit Varma]: you're bringing other things to bear on it.

00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:21.760
[Amit Varma]: But it can also constrict your view because it is a particular lens.

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:27.040
[Amit Varma]: And I'm assuming that as someone who's sort of taken a meta approach where you, you know,

00:20:27.040 --> 00:20:30.240
[Amit Varma]: you don't just write, but you think about writing at a broader level, is this something

00:20:30.240 --> 00:20:31.320
[Amit Varma]: that you've thought about?

00:20:31.320 --> 00:20:35.320
[Amit Varma]: And is this something that you have to watch out for in yourself that, am I going in there

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:38.040
[Amit Varma]: with a particular lens or a preconceived narrative?

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And to what extent is it necessary?

00:20:39.960 --> 00:20:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And to what extent would you need to watch out for it?

00:20:42.600 --> 00:20:46.280
[Guest]: The fundamental truth is that I think everybody goes into everything with a preconceived lens.

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:47.440
[Guest]: We all know this already.

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:52.880
[Guest]: And so there is no such, the myth of the objective journalist has long been shattered and replaced

00:20:52.880 --> 00:20:55.900
[Guest]: by hopefully the myth of the fair and at least balanced journalist.

00:20:55.900 --> 00:21:00.640
[Guest]: But this would be a problem, I think, if I was an opinion writer.

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:05.560
[Guest]: I think if I was commenting on things and doing nothing but that, it would be a very

00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:09.600
[Guest]: difficult thing because you would, as you say, only have a limited set of hammers that

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.760
[Guest]: you would bring to bear on everything that came before you.

00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:17.520
[Guest]: As a journalist, I feel there is a deeper rigor, which is quite enjoyable, which is

00:21:17.520 --> 00:21:21.320
[Guest]: that whatever lens or ideology it is that you bring to bear on something, it is then

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:26.040
[Guest]: your responsibility to go out and find quote-unquote proof of that.

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:30.600
[Guest]: You have to illustrate, you have to show, for example, how the IPL has empowered people,

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:34.120
[Guest]: who it has empowered, what their stories are, what are these stories of empowerment, where

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:36.380
[Guest]: did they come from and where have they come to?

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:41.560
[Guest]: If you think the IPL is a machine for corruption, you have to show how it is a machine for corruption,

00:21:41.560 --> 00:21:46.720
[Guest]: what kind of hyper-capitalist excesses it indulges in and how it's distorting the game.

00:21:46.720 --> 00:21:52.280
[Guest]: I find that there is where the power lies in the kind of work that I and many others

00:21:52.280 --> 00:21:58.240
[Guest]: like to do, which is that it is not only a question of telling, it is a question of showing.

00:21:58.240 --> 00:22:01.980
[Guest]: And it is not only a question of postulating, it is a question of then going out in some

00:22:01.980 --> 00:22:03.680
[Guest]: limited way and proving.

00:22:03.680 --> 00:22:08.440
[Guest]: And that is also where I can indulge my absolute love for narrative.

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:13.240
[Guest]: I mean just the fact that you can tell a story and through that story, these themes can sometimes

00:22:13.240 --> 00:22:14.240
[Guest]: even be implicit.

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:18.000
[Guest]: You don't even need to sort of explicitly make them clear the way an opinion writer

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.400
[Guest]: might do.

00:22:19.400 --> 00:22:24.160
[Guest]: This is also, by the way, why I have a huge amount of respect for people who write opinions

00:22:24.160 --> 00:22:29.520
[Guest]: on a daily or a weekly basis, people like you and Mehr Sharma and many others, people

00:22:29.520 --> 00:22:36.160
[Guest]: who are able to somehow sort of bring a certain freshness to each column and not make it seem

00:22:36.160 --> 00:22:39.880
[Guest]: as if it is all a question of just looking at the world through these set of lenses.

00:22:39.880 --> 00:22:42.040
[Guest]: I'm unable to do that for some reason.

00:22:42.040 --> 00:22:46.400
[Guest]: And I think it's because perhaps I don't have as many opinions as I would like.

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:48.400
[Guest]: They are not as fleshed out as I would like.

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:56.400
[Guest]: But fortunately, my job gives me the liberty to feed my opinions and nurture them and nourish

00:22:56.400 --> 00:22:59.280
[Guest]: them by going out and doing this kind of reporting.

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:03.160
[Guest]: And that is something that I think then I sort of transmit to the reader.

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:07.640
[Guest]: So there are a few cases in which I've gone into a story, not at least in my view, not

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:11.960
[Guest]: having a particularly strong opinion on it and coming out of it with a particularly strong

00:23:11.960 --> 00:23:12.960
[Guest]: view.

00:23:12.960 --> 00:23:16.320
[Guest]: There are many other instances where, as you say, I've gone in knowing what I think and

00:23:16.320 --> 00:23:20.760
[Guest]: kind of looking at narratives that I think tell that larger truth.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:21.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no.

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:24.920
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, I must at this point say that I found all your journalism and your book

00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:28.920
[Amit Varma]: on Haldane and all that extremely fair and balanced and a model of how journalism should

00:23:28.920 --> 00:23:29.920
[Amit Varma]: be done.

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:33.880
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me, you know, like you illustrated with the kind of questions that

00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:38.240
[Amit Varma]: you brought up that different people chasing that IPL story from different angles might

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:42.600
[Amit Varma]: ask that, you know, the fact is that you can actually write that story from both points

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:43.600
[Amit Varma]: of view.

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:46.960
[Amit Varma]: You can find evidence of the grand corruption, you know, the degrading of the skills in the

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:51.400
[Amit Varma]: game, all of which will be true, but you can also find evidence of the empowerment and

00:23:51.400 --> 00:23:52.400
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:56.880
[Amit Varma]: And to some extent, the choice of what material you gather, what angle you take, what questions

00:23:56.880 --> 00:24:02.400
[Amit Varma]: you ask and who you ask those questions to also kind of shapes a piece.

00:24:02.400 --> 00:24:05.000
[Amit Varma]: But I guess you've sort of already answered that.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.160
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, for those of my listeners who might wonder, like, of course, no one is subjective.

00:24:09.160 --> 00:24:14.080
[Amit Varma]: We all bring our own bags of biases to bear on anything that we do.

00:24:14.080 --> 00:24:18.360
[Amit Varma]: But given that you made a distinction between objective on the one hand and fair and balanced

00:24:18.360 --> 00:24:19.560
[Amit Varma]: on the other hand.

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:21.960
[Amit Varma]: So can you define fair and balanced a little bit?

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:22.960
[Guest]: You know?

00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:23.960
[Guest]: Yeah, that's a good question.

00:24:23.960 --> 00:24:27.480
[Guest]: And given that is actually, there's a lot of talk about what it means to balance a story

00:24:27.480 --> 00:24:28.480
[Guest]: these days.

00:24:28.480 --> 00:24:32.960
[Guest]: So in my view, fair and balanced is not so much a question of what the output looks like

00:24:32.960 --> 00:24:36.560
[Guest]: as what the procedural aspect of journalism is.

00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:42.800
[Guest]: So for example, if X has said something about Y, it is my responsibility as far as it is

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest]: possible to go to Y and ask him or her what they think about this and whether they would

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:50.120
[Guest]: like to say something in return.

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:55.680
[Guest]: Now, this, you know, this applies very much in the case of these cases where, you know,

00:24:55.680 --> 00:24:59.920
[Guest]: it is about people talking about each other, which happens quite often in journalism.

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:05.240
[Guest]: The bigger debate in journalism that has come up now about balance is when you are tackling

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:06.880
[Guest]: things like climate change.

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:13.400
[Guest]: There is a huge resistance now to the fact that you have to be balanced when you're presenting

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:16.040
[Guest]: a new set of climate change data.

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:21.440
[Guest]: You have to also necessarily include on your panel of experts on TV or in your story as

00:25:21.440 --> 00:25:26.520
[Guest]: a talking head, somebody who is a climate change denier.

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:29.880
[Guest]: That kind of balance, I think, is not what I'm talking about.

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:34.400
[Guest]: And it's something that we have increasingly come to learn is fruitless.

00:25:34.400 --> 00:25:40.920
[Guest]: I mean, if there are 99.5% of scientists out there who think that climate change is real,

00:25:40.920 --> 00:25:45.520
[Guest]: it is not incumbent upon you to seek out the other 0.5% and ask them and include their

00:25:45.520 --> 00:25:47.800
[Guest]: views just for the sake of quote-unquote balance.

00:25:47.800 --> 00:25:51.280
[Guest]: I don't think that's the kind of balance we're talking about here.

00:25:51.280 --> 00:25:55.760
[Guest]: Fairness is probably a better word for it because then there is a responsibility that

00:25:55.760 --> 00:25:59.160
[Guest]: comes upon the journalist to decide what is fair.

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.320
[Guest]: You know, fairness is subjective.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:01.640
[Guest]: Again, everything is subjective.

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:02.880
[Guest]: Fairness also is.

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:07.560
[Guest]: And you have to decide whether if somebody has said something about a topic, whether

00:26:07.560 --> 00:26:13.480
[Guest]: there is a value to be added to the story or a truth to be gained about the story by

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:15.880
[Guest]: talking to people from quote-unquote the other side.

00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:20.480
[Guest]: I think that is, so it's a procedural thing that you wrestle with on a day-to-day basis

00:26:20.480 --> 00:26:23.040
[Guest]: as you're reporting the story itself.

00:26:23.040 --> 00:26:25.280
[Guest]: The output may or may not reflect it.

00:26:25.280 --> 00:26:30.800
[Guest]: And this is where this whole notion of journalists being gatekeepers of these kind of narratives

00:26:30.800 --> 00:26:31.800
[Guest]: comes into play.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:35.280
[Guest]: Because as a journalist, you are actually deciding well before the story is out, what

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:40.240
[Guest]: is important and what is not, what truth is better reflected by what kind of writing and

00:26:40.240 --> 00:26:42.520
[Guest]: what kind of quotes that you include.

00:26:42.520 --> 00:26:43.800
[Guest]: But that is the job.

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:49.400
[Guest]: I mean, you know, and so you have to unfortunately hope that readers repose a certain amount

00:26:49.400 --> 00:26:54.760
[Guest]: of trust in you and in the institution to be able to discern all these various aspects

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:57.400
[Guest]: of truth and fairness and objectivity and balance.

00:26:57.400 --> 00:26:58.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, fair point.

00:26:58.400 --> 00:27:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another example of, for example, the quest for balance used to be, you know,

00:27:01.960 --> 00:27:05.560
[Amit Varma]: in a subject that you've written about is when people used to insist that if you're

00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:09.280
[Amit Varma]: talking to, you know, someone who believes in natural selection, you also must have an

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:14.280
[Amit Varma]: intelligent design guy out there, thereby implying an equivalence and that kind of balances,

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:20.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just nonsensical, you know, tell me a little bit about your process of writing

00:27:20.720 --> 00:27:21.720
[Amit Varma]: nonfiction.

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And even before that, like, you know, of course, you went to the US in the late 90s to study

00:27:25.600 --> 00:27:26.600
[Amit Varma]: journalism.

00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And then you went again to Columbia to study IR after your crick and four stint.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:35.480
[Amit Varma]: But before that, what shaped your ideas of what, you know, narrative nonfiction were

00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:39.800
[Amit Varma]: because I remember, you know, growing up in India, as I did in the 80s and the 90s.

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:44.760
[Amit Varma]: You didn't really unless you were very privileged, which I have to accept I was, you didn't really

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:50.040
[Amit Varma]: get to read much great writing of this sort, you had access to a whole bunch of great books,

00:27:50.040 --> 00:27:55.080
[Amit Varma]: but pre internet, you didn't really have access to great, long form journalism, you know,

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:58.240
[Amit Varma]: what was that process like of discovering what journalism can do?

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:03.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, is your you know, desire to be a writer of narrative nonfiction, something

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.720
[Amit Varma]: that happened gradually, or did you know early on that that's the kind of writing you want

00:28:06.720 --> 00:28:07.720
[Guest]: to know,

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:10.680
[Guest]: I had no idea, you know, like many other people, I think growing up in India in the 90s, I

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:16.720
[Guest]: had no exposure to any of these great writers and magazines that published narrative journalism.

00:28:16.720 --> 00:28:20.920
[Guest]: I think, you know, when I went to study journalism, and after I came back for a long time, my

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:26.080
[Guest]: idea of what I wanted to do, what kind of journalism I wanted to was driven very much

00:28:26.080 --> 00:28:27.960
[Guest]: by language.

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:32.800
[Guest]: And we go back again to, you know, the books that maybe all of us read in the 80s and 90s.

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:37.120
[Guest]: Growing up, you know, books where we came to admire literary style, a certain kind of

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:38.120
[Guest]: literary style.

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:42.440
[Guest]: For me, that was sort of the driver of, of good writing itself.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:44.640
[Guest]: And that was the pillar of it.

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:48.080
[Guest]: And so this was one of the reasons why I got into cricket writing, for example, because

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:54.600
[Guest]: I thought cricket was the kind of arena that would allow a certain literariness to flourish.

00:28:54.600 --> 00:28:58.120
[Guest]: I didn't realize at the time that the, you know, the era when you could be literally

00:28:58.120 --> 00:29:02.080
[Guest]: in your cricket writing at long past for the most part, and that, you know, there was a

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:08.360
[Guest]: lot more sort of day to day journalistic rigor and stripped away language that went into

00:29:08.360 --> 00:29:10.280
[Guest]: cricket writing in the early 2000s.

00:29:10.280 --> 00:29:12.520
[Guest]: But I thought at the time that that is what I wanted to do.

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:15.960
[Guest]: And then I, you know, beyond, I tried a number of other things, you know, I, after I quit

00:29:15.960 --> 00:29:19.320
[Guest]: Crick Info, I was a film critic for a little while.

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:22.880
[Guest]: And again, I thought that that was a way in which I could indulge my love of the language

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:23.880
[Guest]: itself.

00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:26.840
[Guest]: I would write features for newspapers, I would write travel pieces.

00:29:26.840 --> 00:29:31.440
[Guest]: But all of these were still sort of what you might call, you know, medium form journalism,

00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:32.440
[Guest]: right?

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:34.960
[Guest]: Maybe 1000, 1500 words at the most.

00:29:34.960 --> 00:29:40.600
[Guest]: And then I think in, this must have been around 2003 or 2004, which is when, you must also

00:29:40.600 --> 00:29:45.120
[Guest]: remember this, the New Yorker famously decided that they would sell 80 years of archival

00:29:45.120 --> 00:29:48.000
[Guest]: issues on a set of DVDs.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:49.840
[Guest]: And I splashed out for one of those DVDs.

00:29:49.840 --> 00:29:53.360
[Guest]: And they arrived by courier to my house in Chennai.

00:29:53.360 --> 00:29:58.240
[Guest]: And I would, I just started sort of picking articles and writers at random and reading

00:29:58.240 --> 00:30:03.360
[Guest]: off those DVDs, and I would simultaneously also read on these new websites that were

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:08.760
[Guest]: springing up Slate and Salon, all of these websites that were doing longer journalism.

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:11.840
[Guest]: I think even the New Yorker at the time had started to have a website where they put the

00:30:11.840 --> 00:30:12.840
[Guest]: entire issue online.

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:14.560
[Guest]: So anyway, so I would read all of this stuff.

00:30:14.560 --> 00:30:19.880
[Guest]: And I was entranced by this, because I think I felt here was a perfect marriage of all

00:30:19.880 --> 00:30:24.520
[Guest]: of these things that I love, which is that a writer was not necessarily wedded to one

00:30:24.520 --> 00:30:26.920
[Guest]: beat story after story.

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:32.600
[Guest]: There was a certain flexibility of structure, stories serve different functions, they went

00:30:32.600 --> 00:30:36.440
[Guest]: into elements like character and plot and scene.

00:30:36.440 --> 00:30:42.120
[Guest]: And importantly, for me, at least, is that there was a certain encouragement of imaginative

00:30:42.120 --> 00:30:43.840
[Guest]: language, literary language.

00:30:43.840 --> 00:30:48.200
[Guest]: When I read those stories, I think I felt as if I'd finally found a form in which I

00:30:48.200 --> 00:30:50.160
[Guest]: could, which I wanted to occupy.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:54.160
[Guest]: Now, from doing that to actually occupying it, it was like a completely different ball

00:30:54.160 --> 00:30:56.560
[Guest]: game altogether involving a lot of luck.

00:30:56.560 --> 00:31:00.080
[Guest]: But I think that was when, I think it was around 2004-2005, when I read these articles

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:06.600
[Guest]: on these DVDs, that I decided that if I wanted, for me at least, the ideal kind of journalistic

00:31:06.600 --> 00:31:09.080
[Guest]: work that I wanted to pursue was that kind.

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:13.800
[Guest]: And it also, I think, suited, and this is a huge confession, but it also just suited

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:15.640
[Guest]: my own metabolism of work.

00:31:15.640 --> 00:31:22.960
[Guest]: I had tried and completely failed at doing big journalism that requires you to pursue

00:31:22.960 --> 00:31:27.160
[Guest]: the same topic day after day and write stories almost day after day, each story sort of an

00:31:27.160 --> 00:31:31.360
[Guest]: expansion on the previous one, each story running at around 500 or 600 words.

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:34.560
[Guest]: I found I didn't enjoy it, I wasn't cut out for it.

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:37.000
[Guest]: The inherent problem is laziness, as it always is with me.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:42.560
[Guest]: And so therefore, with this piece, or these kind of pieces, I felt that I had time, sometimes

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:48.640
[Guest]: months, to think and to read, and maybe sometimes not to think about it, to put it away for

00:31:48.640 --> 00:31:51.400
[Guest]: a while and come back before I started writing it.

00:31:51.400 --> 00:31:55.400
[Guest]: So when I realized all of these things, I think maybe that is around the time that I

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:58.720
[Amit Varma]: decided this is the kind of work I wanted to do.

00:31:58.720 --> 00:32:02.880
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we continue with the process, a brief digression, something I wonder what

00:32:02.880 --> 00:32:03.880
[Amit Varma]: your thoughts are.

00:32:03.880 --> 00:32:06.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you're a little younger than me, but we grew up around the same time, I think you're

00:32:06.840 --> 00:32:11.520
[Amit Varma]: four or five years younger than me, perhaps, you know, so I teach this writing course online.

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the sort of bad habits I warn my students again, which is something

00:32:15.840 --> 00:32:21.360
[Amit Varma]: that Indians especially seem to have internalized in their writing, is the use of these pompous

00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:26.200
[Amit Varma]: phrases like instead of stop, they'll be like, put an end to and instead of now they'll be

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:28.280
[Amit Varma]: like at this moment in time.

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And always a use of, you know, bigger Latinate words with shorter Anglo Saxon words will

00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:38.920
[Amit Varma]: do so, you know, like enable or fructify or even, you know, technical language like that.

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:43.720
[Amit Varma]: And one thought that struck me as I was saying that one, I have a feeling that this is more

00:32:43.720 --> 00:32:46.320
[Amit Varma]: commonplace in India than elsewhere.

00:32:46.320 --> 00:32:50.960
[Amit Varma]: But two, I think one reason for that, that I have speculated, and I wonder what your

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:55.840
[Amit Varma]: views are, is that part of it is because we carry this postcolonial baggage that English

00:32:55.840 --> 00:32:57.560
[Amit Varma]: is a marker of class.

00:32:57.560 --> 00:33:02.760
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, one way of signaling how sophisticated you are, or where you stand in society is

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:08.080
[Amit Varma]: somehow showing, you know, quote, unquote, good English, and that includes showing bigger

00:33:08.080 --> 00:33:13.040
[Amit Varma]: words and, you know, the mastery of phrases like this, a mastery of cliches, like I don't,

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:16.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, when we were both cricket writers in the early 2000s, one of the things that

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:20.720
[Amit Varma]: struck me was that a lot of the older cricket writers wore their mastery of cliches as a

00:33:20.720 --> 00:33:21.720
[Amit Varma]: badge of pride.

00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:23.080
[Amit Varma]: It was a feature, not a bug.

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:26.760
[Amit Varma]: It was a good thing to have a cliche for every occasion.

00:33:26.760 --> 00:33:30.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so question number one, do you think that's kind of true?

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:34.920
[Amit Varma]: And question number two, is that something that in your own writing, did you see an evolution

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:38.840
[Amit Varma]: of the sort of writing which was I mean, on the one hand, of course, we were reading great

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:40.800
[Amit Varma]: books and reading great writers from abroad.

00:33:40.800 --> 00:33:44.720
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, we were surrounded by this sort of language around us and in

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:45.720
[Amit Varma]: our newspapers.

00:33:45.720 --> 00:33:49.360
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you have to consciously think about and fight against?

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:54.280
[Amit Varma]: Did your style evolve, you know, in a mindful way or did it sort of organically just to

00:33:54.280 --> 00:33:56.440
[Amit Varma]: reading good writing become what it is?

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:57.880
[Guest]: No, I think you're definitely right.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:02.280
[Guest]: In addition to the marker of class aspect that you mentioned, I think there is also

00:34:02.280 --> 00:34:07.000
[Guest]: the question of, you know, the sort of lag with which we in India received a lot of what

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:08.440
[Guest]: you might call literature.

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:13.480
[Guest]: And so I think in the 80s and 90s, we were not yet at least I mean, not a lot of us at

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:18.720
[Guest]: any rate, we were not reading the kind of stripped away new journalism kind of thing.

00:34:18.720 --> 00:34:22.440
[Guest]: I mean, you would read some Hemingway, but you would also often read a lot of 19th century

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:27.320
[Guest]: British literature and British literature was for it and it was ornate and you know,

00:34:27.320 --> 00:34:30.880
[Guest]: so you would read that and you would kind of internalize those words and think that

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:36.160
[Guest]: they were just to be used in everyday writing, not realizing that time had in a sense passed

00:34:36.160 --> 00:34:38.360
[Guest]: even in Britain.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:43.400
[Guest]: And so I think that was, you know, one of the key drivers of this, the kind of literature

00:34:43.400 --> 00:34:48.160
[Guest]: you read growing up in school as part of your non-detail exercises or whatever, was all

00:34:48.160 --> 00:34:52.240
[Guest]: sort of from a particular era, it was set in stone, it was frozen in time.

00:34:52.240 --> 00:34:55.600
[Guest]: And you internalize that in your classroom, and then you move out and you just continue

00:34:55.600 --> 00:34:58.480
[Guest]: to think that that is a marker of good writing.

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:04.000
[Guest]: And of course, we all know that Indian bureaucrats, for example, still use a lot of pompous obfuscatory

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:05.000
[Guest]: jargon.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.280
[Guest]: So you see that kind of stuff in government documents and releases, and that then makes

00:35:09.280 --> 00:35:15.800
[Guest]: its way into the newspapers and Indian newspapers were for a long time notorious for the usage

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:17.640
[Guest]: of governmentese as well.

00:35:17.640 --> 00:35:20.360
[Guest]: And so it was just all around you at that time, I felt.

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:24.400
[Guest]: And there was no internet to update you on how people were writing at this particular

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:25.760
[Guest]: moment in time in the 90s.

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:29.840
[Guest]: So that was, and it definitely, again, this is a question purely of privilege and nothing

00:35:29.840 --> 00:35:30.840
[Guest]: else.

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:34.480
[Guest]: The fact that I was able to go away just after school for university to study journalism

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:41.240
[Guest]: and be exposed at what was still quite a formative age to people consider good writing.

00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:44.840
[Guest]: And what is actually, I think, in my view, good writing, which is to strip away a lot

00:35:44.840 --> 00:35:47.920
[Guest]: of the pomp around language.

00:35:47.920 --> 00:35:52.320
[Guest]: I still haven't done it to the extent that I think a lot of my colleagues do.

00:35:52.320 --> 00:35:57.600
[Guest]: I still do like a certain element of play in language, a certain inventiveness.

00:35:57.600 --> 00:36:02.600
[Guest]: I will sometimes sort of use uncommon synonym for a common word, if I think it fits into

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:06.240
[Guest]: the rhythm of a sentence or if it fits into the context.

00:36:06.240 --> 00:36:11.200
[Guest]: But what a lot of this did and what reading a lot of this did forced me to actively, consciously,

00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:13.960
[Guest]: as you say, question how language works.

00:36:13.960 --> 00:36:20.600
[Guest]: And when it is permissible or even desirable to use an uncommon synonym for a common word,

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:21.600
[Guest]: as I said.

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:26.000
[Guest]: Fractify may actually have a particular use and connotation in a particular sentence.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.400
[Guest]: It is just a question of knowing when that is.

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:32.840
[Guest]: And knowing that those instances don't come by as often as you think they might.

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:37.000
[Amit Varma]: So you know, as you made this sort of shift towards, you know, longer writing, longer

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:41.320
[Amit Varma]: narrative nonfiction, and you in fact said that your comfort zone is in the seven to

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:46.200
[Amit Varma]: eight thousand word piece sort of what are the early memorable pieces that you remember

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:48.480
[Amit Varma]: and what are your learnings along the way there?

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:51.920
[Amit Varma]: You know, what would your process be like when you set out writing one of these?

00:36:51.920 --> 00:36:55.480
[Guest]: I mean, between my reading of these and my writing of these, I think there was like a

00:36:55.480 --> 00:36:59.600
[Guest]: good six year period, I mean, before I began to work on my first piece.

00:36:59.600 --> 00:37:04.560
[Guest]: But I remember the among the first ones, the first pieces I read, there were a lot of,

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:05.560
[Guest]: you know, A.J.

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:09.120
[Guest]: Liebling, who was a New Yorker writer who wrote a lot on boxing, on food and on the

00:37:09.120 --> 00:37:10.600
[Guest]: Second World War in France.

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:12.480
[Guest]: Again, eclectic range of subjects.

00:37:12.480 --> 00:37:16.840
[Guest]: I remember reading him and enjoying him thoroughly because I think he was, he was sort of funny

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:21.000
[Guest]: and irreverent when it came to two out of these three subjects, he was quite serious

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:22.000
[Guest]: about boxing.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:28.520
[Guest]: And, you know, he was, again, hugely inventive with the language in a way that has gone away

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:33.160
[Guest]: to a large extent in American journalism now, but was still back in the day in the 1930s

00:37:33.160 --> 00:37:35.560
[Guest]: and 40s was still a feature of the journalism.

00:37:35.560 --> 00:37:36.560
[Guest]: And I loved reading him.

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:41.960
[Guest]: And I remember buying a compendium of his book, of his articles and devouring that.

00:37:41.960 --> 00:37:45.600
[Guest]: I remember reading a lot of Calvin Trillin, who was a food writer.

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:48.760
[Guest]: I read a lot of Joan Didion, her essays from California.

00:37:48.760 --> 00:37:53.560
[Guest]: I mean, all of this stuff was introduced to me, again, in the early part of the 2000s,

00:37:53.560 --> 00:37:59.320
[Guest]: either by people who I had gone to college with or people who had read these in the U.S.

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:00.320
[Guest]: and pressed them onto me.

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:05.360
[Guest]: And in all of these, I mean, I was just, I would read them almost and this is, again,

00:38:05.360 --> 00:38:09.640
[Guest]: the sort of foundation of a particular kind of narrative journalism is that they should

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:11.000
[Guest]: read almost like fiction.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:12.520
[Guest]: And so this is how I would read these pieces.

00:38:12.520 --> 00:38:15.980
[Guest]: I mean, they were almost sort of fictive in their effect.

00:38:15.980 --> 00:38:20.400
[Guest]: You could read them and not realize that you were reading nonfiction at all.

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:21.960
[Guest]: And that appealed to me enormously.

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:26.040
[Guest]: And so when it came time to write sort of my first piece, I think the first piece I

00:38:26.040 --> 00:38:29.640
[Guest]: would have written in this vein was Profile of Lalit Modi for Caravan.

00:38:29.640 --> 00:38:34.120
[Guest]: I think that was, you know, the first long piece I actively set out to do.

00:38:34.120 --> 00:38:37.920
[Guest]: And, you know, so all of that, I mean, I was just like, wait, it was like an explosion

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:41.200
[Guest]: of desire to write these kind of pieces.

00:38:41.200 --> 00:38:45.360
[Guest]: And, you know, all of these ideas and things I've been thinking about for the last six

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:50.120
[Guest]: or seven or eight years, all sort of came out, I think, in that 8000 word piece on Lalit

00:38:50.120 --> 00:38:52.840
[Guest]: Modi, which came out in, I think, 2011.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:57.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of the things that is sort of notable about the Lalit Modi piece is,

00:38:57.760 --> 00:39:00.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, which sort of marked it out from the sort of stuff you would read in India

00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:05.560
[Amit Varma]: at that time, is the accretion of details, you know, in your very first para, you sort

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:09.920
[Amit Varma]: of quoted the Libchari and talking about how he's very fast with SMS, he has to think as

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:15.320
[Amit Varma]: fast as he types, which immediately, you know, gives you one little picture of the guy, then

00:39:15.320 --> 00:39:17.680
[Amit Varma]: you talk about how he smokes a cigarette.

00:39:17.680 --> 00:39:22.240
[Amit Varma]: So not just the tell of he would smoke ceaselessly, but even the show of he would begin a cigarette,

00:39:22.240 --> 00:39:26.580
[Amit Varma]: drag on it a couple of times, and then toss it away as if, you know, all of that.

00:39:26.580 --> 00:39:30.880
[Amit Varma]: So when you write a story, like if we talk about process now, and you begin work on a

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:36.640
[Amit Varma]: story, like I'm guessing there are two sort of distinct phases, and one is where you conceptualize

00:39:36.640 --> 00:39:39.560
[Amit Varma]: a story and you start getting the material together.

00:39:39.560 --> 00:39:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And the other would be when you actually sit down and write it.

00:39:42.440 --> 00:39:47.760
[Amit Varma]: So at the stage when you start getting the material together, you know, what is your

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:48.760
[Amit Varma]: process like?

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:53.940
[Amit Varma]: Because I'm guessing here, you see, it seems as if you have to be simultaneously mindful

00:39:53.940 --> 00:39:56.960
[Amit Varma]: of two different kinds of narrative elements.

00:39:56.960 --> 00:40:01.040
[Amit Varma]: One is the key narrative of what is happening and what people have done and all of that.

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:06.360
[Amit Varma]: And the other is you're also looking for these rich, vivid details, which can then make that

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:11.040
[Amit Varma]: work, you know, shine in a novelistic way, sort of to say, so how do you think about

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:12.040
[Amit Varma]: it?

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:13.040
[Amit Varma]: How do you go about it?

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:14.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, how do you take notes?

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:15.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm just very curious about that process.

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:19.440
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I feel like all of this has changed over time for me also.

00:40:19.440 --> 00:40:23.560
[Guest]: I mean, the way I do it now is essentially, there's three phases, actually, there's sort

00:40:23.560 --> 00:40:27.200
[Guest]: of the once the story has been pitched and accepted, we can get to pitching and accepting

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:29.080
[Guest]: later if that's like of interest to you.

00:40:29.080 --> 00:40:32.680
[Guest]: But once it's been accepted, I then set out to do a whole bunch of reading.

00:40:32.680 --> 00:40:35.560
[Guest]: That never used to happen before, I would just go out and start reporting immediately

00:40:35.560 --> 00:40:37.760
[Guest]: because I thought that's what journalists did.

00:40:37.760 --> 00:40:41.640
[Guest]: Now I think like I, you know, I buy a couple of books, I go online and read everything

00:40:41.640 --> 00:40:46.080
[Guest]: that has already been written, right, I'm midway through researching a profile now and

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:50.040
[Guest]: I had to read three books, two of them were memoirs written by this guy before I even

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.040
[Guest]: could start.

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:55.240
[Guest]: So it is important when you go into that world, to be as prepared as you can be, which is

00:40:55.240 --> 00:40:57.320
[Guest]: not something I thought much about earlier.

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:00.200
[Guest]: And then the second thing is, of course, this whole roster of interviews, the more the better

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:04.000
[Guest]: for Lalit Modi, I think I had like 30 or 40 interviews.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:09.280
[Guest]: And it is difficult, it is surprisingly difficult to get people to describe Amit.

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:12.100
[Guest]: I don't know what your experience has been with this.

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:17.520
[Guest]: But when I, you know, when you ask them to describe a room, when you ask them to describe

00:41:17.520 --> 00:41:22.480
[Guest]: a person's habits, when you ask them to describe what it is like to be around someone, or to

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:28.560
[Guest]: be in a particular place, I don't know whether it is, it's just that we have not learned

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:33.680
[Guest]: to do this as much as we should, or whether we don't pay attention to these details, or

00:41:33.680 --> 00:41:37.800
[Guest]: whether we think they are not important when they tell the story of somebody like Lalit

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:41.080
[Guest]: Modi, it's more important to focus on his achievements and on his character.

00:41:41.080 --> 00:41:44.960
[Guest]: So it was, you know, it's an enormous sort of challenge to draw this out of people.

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:49.380
[Guest]: I mean, there are some Americans, for some reason, tend to do this much better than anyone

00:41:49.380 --> 00:41:50.380
[Guest]: else in the world.

00:41:50.380 --> 00:41:54.600
[Guest]: I mean, they are immediately thinking in terms of almost cinematic terms, they will tell

00:41:54.600 --> 00:41:59.000
[Guest]: you sort of, even if you want them to talk about the theme and their work, they will

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:02.840
[Guest]: tell that to you, they will narrate that to you in a story like fashion.

00:42:02.840 --> 00:42:06.560
[Guest]: It's uncanny, almost uniformly, and no one else in the world, no other culture in the

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:08.440
[Guest]: world sort of managed to do that.

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:14.800
[Guest]: So in my opinion, what has usually worked is that you start off by allowing them to

00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:18.400
[Guest]: talk about what they want to talk about, which is sort of how Lalit Modi built the IPL.

00:42:18.400 --> 00:42:21.360
[Guest]: Well, first he did this, and then he did this, all of these details.

00:42:21.360 --> 00:42:25.320
[Guest]: And you allow them to get that out of their system, almost.

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:29.800
[Guest]: And then you keep asking again, and at that point, having run out of things to say about

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:35.840
[Guest]: his work, they will then automatically reach for other things, the kind of details, scenes

00:42:35.840 --> 00:42:40.400
[Guest]: that I want them to talk about, the personal tics and habits that make this guy go.

00:42:40.400 --> 00:42:41.840
[Amit Varma]: How do you get the cigarette detail though?

00:42:41.840 --> 00:42:42.840
[Amit Varma]: How he smokes?

00:42:42.840 --> 00:42:43.840
[Amit Varma]: How did you get those details?

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:47.600
[Guest]: I can't for the life of me remember, but I think, I mean, you know, I would just ask,

00:42:47.600 --> 00:42:51.800
[Guest]: I think that was part of a larger question when I asked about what he would do at the

00:42:51.800 --> 00:42:52.800
[Guest]: stadium.

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:54.120
[Guest]: You know, what was he like to be at the stadium?

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:57.640
[Guest]: And so I think that is where whoever, I can't remember who it was, but was telling me about

00:42:57.640 --> 00:43:00.880
[Guest]: how he would sort of constantly just be looking around him.

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:03.960
[Guest]: He would kind of be trying to direct all these operations at the same time, he would drop

00:43:03.960 --> 00:43:08.160
[Guest]: into the celeb boxes and talk to them over there and smoke a cigarette.

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:11.920
[Guest]: And so it sounded to me like he was just like really keyed up all the time.

00:43:11.920 --> 00:43:14.680
[Guest]: When I asked, I remarked on this.

00:43:14.680 --> 00:43:17.440
[Guest]: And at that point, I think this person said, yeah, you know, I mean, even these cigarettes

00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:19.040
[Guest]: that he kept smoking, he would never finish them.

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:22.000
[Guest]: He would just sort of toss them away after a couple of drags.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:23.560
[Guest]: That's how keyed up he was.

00:43:23.560 --> 00:43:27.120
[Guest]: So I mean, that is the kind of thing that you want ideally these people to say, and

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:29.160
[Guest]: it's very difficult to get them to say.

00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:33.120
[Guest]: I have realized, and this is interesting because I was thinking about this yesterday in the

00:43:33.120 --> 00:43:37.560
[Guest]: context of our upcoming interview, is that I have realized that very often people think

00:43:37.560 --> 00:43:43.400
[Guest]: that these details bore the journalist, because I was thinking for often, for example, when

00:43:43.400 --> 00:43:47.480
[Guest]: I was thinking yesterday, when I talked to Amit, what are the sort of things that he

00:43:47.480 --> 00:43:49.680
[Guest]: would even want to know about a journalist process?

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:53.720
[Guest]: I mean, it must sound immensely boring to the average listener, and possibly even to

00:43:53.720 --> 00:43:56.440
[Guest]: Amit, even though Amit is sort of a journalist himself in a sense.

00:43:56.440 --> 00:43:59.320
[Guest]: But like, why would he want to know about the process of writing long form?

00:43:59.320 --> 00:44:02.840
[Guest]: But then I realized this is exactly, maybe this is the kind of process that goes through

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:03.840
[Guest]: a person's mind.

00:44:03.840 --> 00:44:09.120
[Guest]: And maybe that's why they decide these details are not important or to tell or even to register.

00:44:09.120 --> 00:44:13.040
[Guest]: So you have to convince them that you are there, you have time for them.

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:19.800
[Guest]: And every time they let drop a morsel of detail, you bounce on it and show enthusiasm and say,

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:21.720
[Guest]: yes, yes, I want more like this.

00:44:21.720 --> 00:44:23.360
[Guest]: And slowly, then these things emerge.

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:27.040
[Guest]: So it's often very often, it's a question of just getting to spend enough time with

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:28.040
[Amit Varma]: that person.

00:44:28.040 --> 00:44:32.200
[Amit Varma]: What are your theories for why Indians are not so descriptive and Americans are, for

00:44:32.200 --> 00:44:33.200
[Guest]: example?

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:36.520
[Guest]: I mean, even English, I mean, as I find now, when I'm living in England, I mean, even people

00:44:36.520 --> 00:44:38.960
[Guest]: in England, it's very difficult to get them to describe.

00:44:38.960 --> 00:44:39.960
[Guest]: With Americans, I don't know.

00:44:39.960 --> 00:44:44.200
[Guest]: I mean, I have a number of theories, all of which are completely sort of speculative.

00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:48.160
[Guest]: One is that they have grown up listening to talk radio and, you know, things like NPR

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:53.160
[Guest]: and NPR does this kind of storytelling, oral storytelling and oral storytelling at such

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:57.360
[Guest]: length that you know that you have to, that this is the way to tell a story.

00:44:57.360 --> 00:45:00.960
[Guest]: Maybe it's the influence of Hollywood, where you think in sort of a cinematic way, right

00:45:00.960 --> 00:45:01.960
[Guest]: from your childhood.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:07.640
[Guest]: There is just a certain kind of discursiveness about that conversation, even on a day-to-day

00:45:07.640 --> 00:45:11.400
[Guest]: basis when you're not interviewing anyone that I have not found anywhere else.

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:12.400
[Guest]: It's quite remarkable.

00:45:12.400 --> 00:45:16.440
[Guest]: I would do, I was a co-host for a time of this podcast called The Intersection, which

00:45:16.440 --> 00:45:17.440
[Guest]: is a science podcast.

00:45:17.440 --> 00:45:22.720
[Guest]: And, you know, the idea was to get scientists to tell stories, not just to describe their

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:27.840
[Guest]: work and analyze their data for you on the podcast, but to also talk about how they set

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:32.200
[Guest]: about researching this and what kind of themes they're interested in and so on, and tell

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:33.880
[Guest]: stories about their own lives.

00:45:33.880 --> 00:45:39.320
[Guest]: And again, invariably, it was so difficult to get non-American scientists.

00:45:39.320 --> 00:45:44.200
[Guest]: It's definitely, there's an essay or at least a column in there somewhere for someone.

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:45.560
[Amit Varma]: And at some point, I hope you write it.

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:46.560
[Amit Varma]: That's really fascinating.

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:51.360
[Amit Varma]: So when you gather material, are you also forming the narrative in your head or is that

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:55.560
[Amit Varma]: a process that comes later, you know, Joan Didion once said, quote, I don't know what

00:45:55.560 --> 00:45:58.640
[Amit Varma]: I think until I write it down, stop quote.

00:45:58.640 --> 00:46:03.040
[Amit Varma]: And she would, I guess, perhaps have been speaking more in the context of personal essays

00:46:03.040 --> 00:46:08.040
[Amit Varma]: and so on, where you're sort of working out your thoughts as you kind of get into those.

00:46:08.040 --> 00:46:09.520
[Amit Varma]: So what's that process like?

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:14.920
[Amit Varma]: Like I imagine you get into a story fairly open, you have some notions of the angles

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:20.320
[Amit Varma]: you want to tackle, but you know, when does it start to fractify, if I may use that term?

00:46:20.320 --> 00:46:23.640
[Guest]: You may definitely use that term, it's completely appropriate.

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:28.200
[Guest]: It's, so you go into a story, not with, at least for one of these big stories, you go

00:46:28.200 --> 00:46:32.800
[Guest]: not so much with angles as with what one of my editors like to call themes, which is that

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:38.800
[Guest]: you have ostensibly one surface narrative, a surface story, but then you have three or

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:40.320
[Guest]: four layers below that.

00:46:40.320 --> 00:46:43.400
[Guest]: And obviously listeners can't see the thing I'm doing with my hands here, but I'm kind

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:47.640
[Guest]: of sandwiching them one below the other, but these layers that operate at a level below

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:52.600
[Guest]: the main plot or the main story, and those themes sort of weave in and out of the piece

00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:53.600
[Guest]: as you tell it.

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:58.000
[Guest]: And I think the craft, the only craft worth talking about in writing long form journalism

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:01.880
[Guest]: is how you weave the main plot and the themes in and out of each other.

00:47:01.880 --> 00:47:05.400
[Guest]: That is basically the only thing you have to do when you sit down to write.

00:47:05.400 --> 00:47:09.560
[Guest]: And so when I go into a story, most often I know the theme, sometimes I discover new

00:47:09.560 --> 00:47:14.240
[Guest]: themes as they're coming up and as I'm interviewing people, and so I will kind of replace one

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:18.840
[Guest]: with the other, but then I will essentially, and as the reporting goes on, and this is

00:47:18.840 --> 00:47:23.600
[Guest]: a matter of months in many cases, my reporting, my interviewing will get more and more pointed,

00:47:23.600 --> 00:47:25.400
[Guest]: my reading will get more and more pointed.

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:29.600
[Guest]: So I will stop seeking out some kind of sources because I think they possibly can't speak

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:33.800
[Guest]: to the themes that I want to pursue and I will look more for another kind.

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:39.560
[Guest]: My questions get more, revolve more and more around these themes until I feel there's one,

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:44.840
[Guest]: there's a great piece of advice in a book on journalism called the New New Journalism,

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:48.880
[Guest]: where somebody says, you keep reporting until you see yourself coming the other way, by

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:54.040
[Guest]: which I mean that the minute you know that you already have a more detailed answer in

00:47:54.040 --> 00:47:58.840
[Guest]: your mind to what this guy has just given you, you can kind of stop reporting at that

00:47:58.840 --> 00:48:02.800
[Guest]: point because you feel like maybe there is, maybe you keep it going to get some more anecdotes

00:48:02.800 --> 00:48:03.800
[Guest]: and color and so on.

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:06.880
[Guest]: But basically the information that you have is all mostly there.

00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:11.880
[Guest]: But that takes a long time, there's thousands and thousands of words of notes.

00:48:11.880 --> 00:48:17.840
[Guest]: I always these days tape record wherever I can so that I can take notes about other things,

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:21.400
[Guest]: you know, which includes follow up questions that have just stuck me or the scene that

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:24.680
[Guest]: we're setting in or whatever that might be or what this guy is like.

00:48:24.680 --> 00:48:29.400
[Guest]: And then I come back and at that point is when you kind of sit down and you put a structure

00:48:29.400 --> 00:48:33.680
[Guest]: down and you kind of, so I have right now next to me actually I have a legal pad on

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:37.280
[Guest]: which I have a structure for this profile I'm writing and in the top right hand corner

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:42.920
[Guest]: I have teams and I have a list of four teams, which is profile itself the guy who I'm profiling

00:48:42.920 --> 00:48:46.840
[Guest]: but then the second team is locked down over the last three or four months, third team

00:48:46.840 --> 00:48:50.920
[Guest]: is fast bowling because it's a profile of cricketer and the fourth team is longevity.

00:48:50.920 --> 00:48:55.440
[Guest]: So you know these kind of like things that I want to pursue as ideas in the piece that

00:48:55.440 --> 00:48:59.480
[Guest]: will go in and out of this story and then you structure it according to that and you

00:48:59.480 --> 00:49:04.120
[Guest]: kind of keep wondering how you can bring these things to the surface occasionally again.

00:49:04.120 --> 00:49:09.160
[Guest]: The thing with long-form journalism also is that it isn't always a question of just saying

00:49:09.160 --> 00:49:12.680
[Guest]: this happened and he said this then she said this and then this happened again it is also

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:18.000
[Guest]: sometimes a question of inserting in your own voice your own idea about what is happening

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:23.120
[Guest]: and so you need you know a definite take on some of these themes that you will then put

00:49:23.120 --> 00:49:27.560
[Guest]: in there at some point and that's kind of the joy of it it's an intensively subjective

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:29.000
[Guest]: form.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:33.040
[Guest]: It is never meant to be objective in fact objectivity in long-form journalism I think

00:49:33.040 --> 00:49:34.400
[Guest]: would be intensely boring.

00:49:34.400 --> 00:49:39.040
[Guest]: The whole point is to have a narrative and the whole point is to have it be subjective.

00:49:39.040 --> 00:49:40.280
[Amit Varma]: That's quite fascinating.

00:49:40.280 --> 00:49:44.240
[Amit Varma]: You know how is in the writing process like you've gathered all the material, the themes

00:49:44.240 --> 00:49:48.880
[Amit Varma]: have sort of fructified as we've gone along and actually how do you discipline yourself

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:50.560
[Amit Varma]: during the writing process?

00:49:50.560 --> 00:49:54.100
[Amit Varma]: I think the key problem most writers find is discipline and you've spoken about how

00:49:54.100 --> 00:49:57.880
[Amit Varma]: you know without a deadline you wouldn't get anything done so having said that you've written

00:49:57.880 --> 00:50:02.040
[Amit Varma]: a bunch of books so clearly you know those don't have such concrete deadlines usually

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:05.320
[Amit Varma]: so you've managed that but how do you kind of discipline yourself?

00:50:05.320 --> 00:50:07.160
[Amit Varma]: Do you write first thing in the morning?

00:50:07.160 --> 00:50:11.880
[Amit Varma]: You know what are the challenges you faced just in that process of getting things written?

00:50:11.880 --> 00:50:17.800
[Guest]: Yeah I mean I write very slowly you know if I write 500 words a day I consider it a job

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:18.800
[Guest]: well spent.

00:50:18.800 --> 00:50:21.720
[Guest]: I try as much as possible to write first thing in the morning.

00:50:21.720 --> 00:50:26.800
[Guest]: It doesn't always work out that way you know today for example we're doing our interview

00:50:26.800 --> 00:50:30.960
[Guest]: at 6.30 in the morning my time so I'll only get to writing maybe later in the afternoon

00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:35.160
[Guest]: but I try as much as possible when I'm working on something to do this 500 words a day thing

00:50:35.160 --> 00:50:37.040
[Guest]: you know if I do 600 it's a bonus.

00:50:37.040 --> 00:50:40.840
[Guest]: The thing that was really difficult was when I was doing long form I mean it's easy to

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:41.920
[Guest]: discipline yourself to that.

00:50:41.920 --> 00:50:46.200
[Guest]: I think that real difficulty came about when I was working on books in parallel with these

00:50:46.200 --> 00:50:47.200
[Guest]: pieces.

00:50:47.200 --> 00:50:50.000
[Guest]: I needed the pieces to make a living and I had to write the book because there was still

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:54.760
[Guest]: a deadline for it and I wanted to do it and so that would involve sort of writing 500

00:50:54.760 --> 00:50:58.880
[Guest]: words of the book in the morning and then setting that aside and doing another 500 words

00:50:58.880 --> 00:51:02.320
[Guest]: of whatever piece I was working on in the evening and that's quite exhausting.

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:05.240
[Guest]: I mean I think once you've done that for a year by the end of the year you are ready

00:51:05.240 --> 00:51:07.240
[Guest]: to take a few months off and not do anything.

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:08.240
[Guest]: So that was it.

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:11.880
[Guest]: I mean I think like I think with the journalism itself once the structure is down the structure

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:16.640
[Guest]: is key once you have the beginning and maybe the end cracked it sort of it tends to flow

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:21.520
[Guest]: I mean and then you just kind of obsess over things like what word to use in this sentence

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:25.880
[Guest]: and you know that kind of thing you are free to then devote yourself to the hearty part

00:51:25.880 --> 00:51:30.200
[Guest]: of the writing process which is just a selection of words and the rhythms of the sentence and

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:31.360
[Guest]: how they sound.

00:51:31.360 --> 00:51:35.120
[Amit Varma]: So you know a final question before we get off the writing process and actually get to

00:51:35.120 --> 00:51:39.640
[Amit Varma]: your wonderful new book is sort of you make a living doing long form journalism and doing

00:51:39.640 --> 00:51:43.320
[Amit Varma]: journalism and you write for The Guardian, The New Yorker and all of these people.

00:51:43.320 --> 00:51:45.880
[Amit Varma]: Now you know it's sort of a dual question.

00:51:45.880 --> 00:51:49.200
[Amit Varma]: One and both parts of the question really relate to voice.

00:51:49.200 --> 00:51:53.880
[Amit Varma]: One is that over time have you developed a particular journalistic voice or is it something

00:51:53.880 --> 00:51:58.600
[Amit Varma]: that shifts from piece to piece depending on your writing on I mean can someone pick

00:51:58.600 --> 00:52:03.400
[Amit Varma]: up a piece and say oh only someone could have written this or that this is so typically

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:07.640
[Amit Varma]: him or can you you know switch depending on the needs of the subject that's part one and

00:52:07.640 --> 00:52:12.960
[Amit Varma]: part two and something that struck me because a decade and a half back I used to write op-eds

00:52:12.960 --> 00:52:17.240
[Amit Varma]: for the Wall Street Journal and a couple of others and one of the things that struck me

00:52:17.240 --> 00:52:22.280
[Amit Varma]: about writing for foreign publications is that the cultural difference between you and

00:52:22.280 --> 00:52:26.240
[Amit Varma]: your editor also applies to how you look at your writing.

00:52:26.240 --> 00:52:30.640
[Amit Varma]: So one thing for example that you have to do for those guys is that you need to explain

00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:35.600
[Amit Varma]: things which the Indian reader would take for granted and therefore you need to simplify

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:40.160
[Amit Varma]: slash dumb it down and that really became an irritating process because if you're for

00:52:40.160 --> 00:52:45.020
[Amit Varma]: example talking about the BJP you don't always want to say comma the Hindu Nationalist Party

00:52:45.020 --> 00:52:47.080
[Guest]: which came to power in 2014.

00:52:47.080 --> 00:52:48.080
[Guest]: That's amazing.

00:52:48.080 --> 00:52:51.160
[Guest]: That's always the example that I use also when I'm talking about how frustrating it

00:52:51.160 --> 00:52:54.840
[Guest]: is and how I never want to write another piece about Modi again because you have to find

00:52:54.840 --> 00:52:58.360
[Guest]: some short brief but effective way of talking about 2002.

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:02.120
[Guest]: You know that is the most annoying thing you know so there are many reasons why 2002 should

00:53:02.120 --> 00:53:05.600
[Guest]: not have happened but one of the reasons is that you have to keep summarizing it in a

00:53:05.600 --> 00:53:07.880
[Amit Varma]: sentence before moving on to what he's doing now.

00:53:07.880 --> 00:53:12.720
[Amit Varma]: A very specific answer that it was also among the many other things that it did wrong it

00:53:12.720 --> 00:53:16.280
[Amit Varma]: was a bane for writers who occasionally write for foreign publications.

00:53:16.280 --> 00:53:19.720
[Amit Varma]: To complete the second part of the question then how does that affect your voice and can

00:53:19.720 --> 00:53:24.360
[Amit Varma]: that process get frustrating like do editors in these places or you know are they trying

00:53:24.360 --> 00:53:28.880
[Amit Varma]: to fit your piece into a particular kind of house style or their conception of how a good

00:53:28.880 --> 00:53:32.800
[Amit Varma]: piece should be or you know of course you're someone who's been writing for so many years

00:53:32.800 --> 00:53:37.160
[Amit Varma]: and you know you're a trusted and recognized writer do you get a certain amount of leeway

00:53:37.160 --> 00:53:39.000
[Guest]: with language and voice?

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:43.160
[Guest]: Okay the first part of your question was about voice across publications and so it does change

00:53:43.160 --> 00:53:47.760
[Guest]: a lot I mean you know the New Yorker has a very distinctive house style that very few

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:52.120
[Guest]: people who write for the magazine and the website are allowed to break on a regular

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:56.120
[Guest]: basis you know I mean first of all New Yorker geeks who are listening to this you know Anthony

00:53:56.120 --> 00:54:00.080
[Guest]: Lay in the movie clearly has a very distinctive style you know a writer like Nick Palmgarten

00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:04.680
[Guest]: who writes quite often has a very distinctive style but for many others you would only have

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:09.200
[Guest]: to you know if you blocked out the byline and you read the rest of the piece you would

00:54:09.200 --> 00:54:13.400
[Guest]: guess who wrote the piece only by what it deals with so if it's a law piece you know

00:54:13.400 --> 00:54:18.000
[Guest]: it is written by Jeffrey Toobin and if you know if it's like a deep state piece it's

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:21.960
[Guest]: a Jane Mayer piece and so on so and whereas and it's a cultural thing also in the sense

00:54:21.960 --> 00:54:27.160
[Guest]: that so from the New York Times magazine is a little bit more flexible Harper's as a magazine

00:54:27.160 --> 00:54:31.800
[Guest]: is still more flexible it's a cultural thing across the Atlantic that British publications

00:54:31.800 --> 00:54:37.160
[Guest]: allow you a lot more leeway and sort of playfulness with your language and your structure but

00:54:37.160 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: even in that the Guardian Longreads is a little bit more American than say 1843 which is the

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:47.400
[Guest]: features magazine of the Economist so it varies from publication to publication and you have

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:52.640
[Guest]: to also temper your voice to suit the subject you know a piece like quizzing piece which

00:54:52.640 --> 00:54:57.560
[Guest]: is partly a personal essay has it's a lot more flexible than a piece would be if it

00:54:57.560 --> 00:55:02.680
[Guest]: was about say I mean I wrote a piece on fair trade which is for the Guardian Longreads

00:55:02.680 --> 00:55:07.680
[Guest]: which is a very sort of intense quite detailed subject about a particular kind of niche in

00:55:07.680 --> 00:55:11.400
[Guest]: the industry and you have to there's very little flexibility over there you know but

00:55:11.400 --> 00:55:17.120
[Guest]: the personal essay is a lot more flexible and so so you do learn over time to tweak

00:55:17.120 --> 00:55:21.800
[Guest]: each article according to who's publishing it and how and what it addresses now having

00:55:21.800 --> 00:55:25.640
[Guest]: said that there is still I think underlying all of that there is still or there should

00:55:25.640 --> 00:55:30.200
[Guest]: be a voice which is particular to me and unique to me and I don't know whether it is a case

00:55:30.200 --> 00:55:34.240
[Guest]: that somebody will read a piece and know instinctively that it was written by me that is for readers

00:55:34.240 --> 00:55:38.920
[Guest]: to say in a sense but I think in my mind at least when I set out writing a sentence for

00:55:38.920 --> 00:55:42.640
[Guest]: the most part it is still the same kind of approach that I take to it and so I and the

00:55:42.640 --> 00:55:46.720
[Guest]: words that I use and the kind of structures that I use you know for example I use a lot

00:55:46.720 --> 00:55:52.080
[Guest]: of semicolons and em dashes you know that is just a linguistic kind of tick in my writing

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:56.760
[Guest]: that never goes away whatever I'm writing about I love things like interleaving dialogue

00:55:56.760 --> 00:56:02.320
[Guest]: between thick passages of text you know wherever that is possible I will do it and so there

00:56:02.320 --> 00:56:07.760
[Guest]: are these things that make up I love texture so texture of prose itself is such that you

00:56:07.760 --> 00:56:11.120
[Guest]: know it's almost like a visual thing on the page when you're looking at a page you don't

00:56:11.120 --> 00:56:16.220
[Guest]: necessarily just see you know three equally sized blocks of text you sometimes see big

00:56:16.220 --> 00:56:21.400
[Guest]: blocks small blocks just a standalone quote sometimes how much you use quotes and where

00:56:21.400 --> 00:56:25.400
[Guest]: you use quotes all of this stuff is tailored to what I like to read and how I like to read

00:56:25.400 --> 00:56:29.840
[Guest]: and so therefore I think it reflects in what you might call a voice we were talking earlier

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:33.760
[Guest]: I think we'd put it off for a later part of the podcast but this is probably a good time

00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:37.640
[Guest]: to bring it up which is that the whole philosophy behind this kind of journalism at least for

00:56:37.640 --> 00:56:42.040
[Guest]: me is you have a certain set of tools and you are like a handyman you can go out and

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:48.080
[Guest]: you can quote unquote fix or address practically any topic out there given time you know you

00:56:48.080 --> 00:56:52.720
[Guest]: have taught yourself how to read deeply and how to talk to people and know whom to interview

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:57.680
[Guest]: and then what kind of questions to ask them and what kind of detail you want to put into

00:56:57.680 --> 00:57:02.040
[Guest]: your story and then you have learned how to synthesize all of this and assimilate it in

00:57:02.040 --> 00:57:07.600
[Guest]: your own mind and then craft a story a narrative out of it this is a limited like Liam Neeson

00:57:07.600 --> 00:57:11.920
[Guest]: I have a small but limited set of tools but they are effective and the philosophy is that

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:17.200
[Guest]: you should be able to go out and apply these to any subject out there whether or not you

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:22.380
[Guest]: are a newcomer to that subject and this is why I enjoy doing this kind of work which

00:57:22.380 --> 00:57:28.640
[Guest]: ranges across subject matter both in my books and in journalism because every time I do

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:33.180
[Guest]: one more of these pieces it kind of strengthens my belief that really the set of tools is

00:57:33.180 --> 00:57:41.080
[Guest]: immensely useful and I love the I just adore the idea of being able to apply it to anything

00:57:41.080 --> 00:57:45.200
[Guest]: in my work I think that's sort of the thing that keeps me going on a day-to-day basis

00:57:45.200 --> 00:57:49.920
[Amit Varma]: why did you call it a limited set of tools why is it because the form itself obviously

00:57:49.920 --> 00:57:53.920
[Guest]: like every form this form also has certain limitations I mean you know for example I'm

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:59.100
[Guest]: not an imaginative person in the sense that a novelist is imaginative you know so I don't

00:57:59.100 --> 00:58:03.480
[Guest]: have you know a word building sense I have a world discovering sense you know so that

00:58:03.480 --> 00:58:07.840
[Guest]: and a lot of these set of tools is limited because they are quite functional tools also

00:58:07.840 --> 00:58:13.120
[Guest]: like how to structure a piece is like a very specific skill that you will use only in this

00:58:13.120 --> 00:58:16.960
[Guest]: field and nowhere else so that's why I called it small and limited but effective in this

00:58:16.960 --> 00:58:21.800
[Guest]: particular field as I said they are functional things that maybe people outside this field

00:58:21.800 --> 00:58:26.320
[Guest]: would not even care or have heard about but here it's sort of for some reason it finds

00:58:26.320 --> 00:58:31.440
[Amit Varma]: its own intense utility so you know when I teach my writing class I often sort of talk

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:36.440
[Amit Varma]: about the difference between strategy and tactics where strategy is sort of the approach

00:58:36.440 --> 00:58:41.360
[Amit Varma]: you bring to a particular piece of writing or it could be your overarching writing philosophy

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:46.640
[Amit Varma]: and tactics are of course all of these little tools of the language you know the paragraphs

00:58:46.640 --> 00:58:50.920
[Amit Varma]: and the punctuation and the ways in which you manipulate rhythm and the music of it

00:58:50.920 --> 00:58:55.880
[Amit Varma]: and all of that those are tactics so you know at a strategic level obviously part of your

00:58:55.880 --> 00:58:59.480
[Amit Varma]: strategy would be dictated by what you're trying to do in a specific piece who you're

00:58:59.480 --> 00:59:05.400
[Amit Varma]: writing it for and all of that but another part could be sort of an overarching writing

00:59:05.400 --> 00:59:09.680
[Amit Varma]: philosophy that you have set for yourself is there something like that which you used

00:59:09.680 --> 00:59:14.240
[Amit Varma]: to you know guide what kind of writing you are going to do I mean as far as possible

00:59:14.240 --> 00:59:20.600
[Guest]: I think this you know this I have still not lost my fascination with making a piece of

00:59:20.600 --> 00:59:25.520
[Guest]: writing as fictive as possible by which I mean it still has the effect of fiction it

00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:30.000
[Guest]: is as I said not always possible it's more possible with some pieces than with others

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:36.440
[Guest]: but insofar as it is possible I want to give the reader an easy and organic reading experience

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:43.080
[Guest]: you know in a lot of these long reads these long form pieces very often it is necessary

00:59:43.080 --> 00:59:49.880
[Guest]: to encapsulate a set of difficult ideas in prose that might be jargony you know because

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:53.600
[Guest]: the nature of the subject is such although you try to mitigate that as much as possible

00:59:53.600 --> 00:59:58.600
[Guest]: it is necessary to be abstract maybe even sort of talk about ideologies in this weird

00:59:58.600 --> 01:00:02.680
[Guest]: abstract vein a lot of people have no problem reading that but I know a lot of people do

01:00:02.680 --> 01:00:08.840
[Guest]: I for one do I mean I am always much better when I'm reading things that are set in the

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:14.640
[Guest]: concrete world that kind of have an underlying message or idea rather than having those ideas

01:00:14.640 --> 01:00:20.040
[Guest]: expressed as sentences you know abstraction set in words so but this is from one of the

01:00:20.040 --> 01:00:24.560
[Guest]: reasons why I find it really difficult to read lengthy political analysis that is completely

01:00:24.560 --> 01:00:28.560
[Guest]: diverse from what is actually happening in the real world you know I so in my mind what

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:33.720
[Guest]: I want to do is to avoid that as much as possible to give the reader an easy way into a lot

01:00:33.720 --> 01:00:38.960
[Guest]: of this material and that inevitably involves sort of doing things like presenting characters

01:00:38.960 --> 01:00:44.800
[Guest]: setting scenes having dialogue almost sort of it's sort of you know a spoonful of sugar

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:49.480
[Guest]: to make the rest of it go down more easily I think that is more than anything else the

01:00:49.480 --> 01:00:54.000
[Guest]: guiding philosophy for me and it's do again it's determined entirely by what I find easy

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:58.760
[Amit Varma]: to read and difficult yeah I want to explore the use of your word a fictive there like

01:00:58.760 --> 01:01:03.280
[Amit Varma]: I'm presuming you can mean a you know one of a couple of things one is that like you

01:01:03.280 --> 01:01:07.440
[Amit Varma]: just said you make it more vivid so you avoid the abstract and you go for the concrete so

01:01:07.440 --> 01:01:12.320
[Amit Varma]: you won't talk about say quote-unquote the great crisis of migrant labor having to walk

01:01:12.320 --> 01:01:16.560
[Amit Varma]: through highways instead you you know you look for an image like a woman pulling a suitcase

01:01:16.560 --> 01:01:20.680
[Amit Varma]: and her little three-year-old child is on that and you make that with it that is one

01:01:20.680 --> 01:01:24.360
[Amit Varma]: of the possible interpretations I'm drawing from it and the other one is that you have

01:01:24.360 --> 01:01:29.680
[Amit Varma]: deeper layers you build like in a novel you'd have sort of a universe of things and not

01:01:29.680 --> 01:01:34.360
[Amit Varma]: just one narrative not just one sort of linear narrative and I guess long form nonfiction

01:01:34.360 --> 01:01:38.680
[Amit Varma]: also gives you the scope to do that to have these different layers as you pointed out

01:01:38.680 --> 01:01:42.560
[Guest]: so are these two things what you mean by fictive they're both I mean they're both what I mean

01:01:42.560 --> 01:01:45.920
[Guest]: by fictive you're right I mean to present somebody the essence of what it's like to

01:01:45.920 --> 01:01:50.280
[Guest]: read fiction but to have it be fact which involves sort of creating a little mini universe

01:01:50.280 --> 01:01:55.720
[Guest]: for the reader populating with real people with real settings with real occurrences one

01:01:55.720 --> 01:01:59.640
[Guest]: of my editors has a nice phrase which is that over a long read you should somehow be able

01:01:59.640 --> 01:02:03.680
[Guest]: to convey the passage of time in some sense or the other and that is important I think

01:02:03.680 --> 01:02:09.160
[Guest]: because I think people move through time events happen over time and so to even have that

01:02:09.160 --> 01:02:15.880
[Guest]: happen is a novelistic thing I think and this populating with real people thing I think

01:02:15.880 --> 01:02:20.360
[Guest]: is something that is often underlooked I mean with one of my editors in particular we have

01:02:20.360 --> 01:02:25.120
[Guest]: intense and enjoyable differences of opinion on how much a real person should be focused

01:02:25.120 --> 01:02:31.840
[Guest]: on as a person rather than as just as a vehicle or a carrier for ideas and themes my own view

01:02:31.840 --> 01:02:36.520
[Guest]: always is that I think people read about people and they are interested in other people and

01:02:36.520 --> 01:02:40.760
[Guest]: through that they will then assimilate in a much more effective way the things that

01:02:40.760 --> 01:02:46.280
[Guest]: you're trying to convey whereas his view is that that you know you should just sort of

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:50.920
[Guest]: describe the person only in so far as it's necessary but then to actually beyond that

01:02:50.920 --> 01:02:55.480
[Guest]: just have him or her be a name that occurs in the rest of the piece as you are trying

01:02:55.480 --> 01:02:59.920
[Guest]: to explain certain things so it's you know these philosophies are quite enjoyable they

01:02:59.920 --> 01:03:03.920
[Guest]: differ from publication to publication editor to editor journalist to journalist and it's

01:03:03.920 --> 01:03:08.300
[Amit Varma]: nice to talk about these things and discuss them so you know we'll move into a commercial

01:03:08.300 --> 01:03:12.280
[Amit Varma]: break now and after that come back and talk about your book on JBS I'll then but before

01:03:12.280 --> 01:03:16.160
[Amit Varma]: we do that you know for people who are interested in writing for people who are interested in

01:03:16.160 --> 01:03:21.400
[Amit Varma]: long-form journalism you know one do you have any advice to share on maybe what you've learned

01:03:21.400 --> 01:03:25.360
[Amit Varma]: through your journey of all these years like if someone was to ask you that okay over the

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:29.480
[Amit Varma]: last 20 years what have you learned about writing what are the big lessons or even what

01:03:29.480 --> 01:03:33.840
[Amit Varma]: are the things you wish you knew 20 years ago and thought about I think I have only

01:03:33.840 --> 01:03:38.840
[Guest]: recently come to really appreciate the power of structure of an outline before you set

01:03:38.840 --> 01:03:42.600
[Guest]: out to write for a long time I did it without an outline or I would just sort of have section

01:03:42.600 --> 01:03:47.080
[Guest]: one is about X section two is about Y section three is about Z I would not actually break

01:03:47.080 --> 01:03:51.640
[Guest]: those sections down further for myself and I do it now to the extent that I know what

01:03:51.640 --> 01:03:56.960
[Guest]: each paragraph in each section will address that is obviously fluid as you're writing

01:03:56.960 --> 01:04:01.400
[Guest]: because sometimes what looks good on a structure and an outline does not look good on the page

01:04:01.400 --> 01:04:05.740
[Guest]: once you've started writing it so it's it's subject to change but I think that is something

01:04:05.740 --> 01:04:10.640
[Guest]: I think is is important I think the thing I've done a lot more off over the last few

01:04:10.640 --> 01:04:16.680
[Guest]: years is reread pieces four or five times and you know the first and second time maybe

01:04:16.680 --> 01:04:21.040
[Guest]: this is not my own pieces these are pieces that I admire and deeply appreciate the first

01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:25.240
[Guest]: and second time I will still be reading it almost as if I am a regular reader but in

01:04:25.240 --> 01:04:28.520
[Guest]: the third and fourth time I will actually take pen and paper and I will start breaking

01:04:28.520 --> 01:04:33.200
[Guest]: things down trying to understand for myself how these various things interlock with each

01:04:33.200 --> 01:04:39.040
[Guest]: other what this section is doing and why this particular writer started with an image like

01:04:39.040 --> 01:04:44.040
[Guest]: this which then moves on to a nut graph of this kind which is then exemplified by the

01:04:44.040 --> 01:04:48.040
[Guest]: scene that comes next you know all of these things you know why this character pops up

01:04:48.040 --> 01:04:53.160
[Guest]: here and not there these things I think I've started understanding in a deeper way only

01:04:53.160 --> 01:04:57.520
[Guest]: over the last five or six years as I've started doing this exercise of breaking these pieces

01:04:57.520 --> 01:05:01.440
[Guest]: down of reading them again and again and I think that is something that I think all writers

01:05:01.440 --> 01:05:07.080
[Amit Varma]: could stand to learn from and about and other pieces which are like you know models to you

01:05:07.080 --> 01:05:11.000
[Amit Varma]: of you know which you think you learned a lot from or you would present as a model of

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:15.840
[Guest]: what long form narrative nonfiction is capable of I mean there are models in each genre and

01:05:15.840 --> 01:05:19.400
[Guest]: field I guess so like to list them would be tough but I mean one of the things I use in

01:05:19.400 --> 01:05:26.840
[Guest]: my own writing workshops and and classes is a profile of the chef Mario Batali by the

01:05:26.840 --> 01:05:32.720
[Guest]: writer Bill Buford which is a long piece and eventually then went on to become the basis

01:05:32.720 --> 01:05:37.240
[Guest]: for a book a very fine book but it is a perfect example of what I'm talking about which is

01:05:37.240 --> 01:05:44.240
[Guest]: that you know Mario Batali is this intensely larger-than-life sensuously inclined kind

01:05:44.240 --> 01:05:50.760
[Guest]: of chef in New York an Italian chef and you know Bill Buford sort of tweaks his language

01:05:50.760 --> 01:05:56.960
[Guest]: to suit the subject and so the first paragraph is a long and deeply detailed scene of what

01:05:56.960 --> 01:06:01.840
[Guest]: happens when Mario Batali once came over to his house to cook for his guests and what

01:06:01.840 --> 01:06:06.840
[Guest]: that is like and the kind of excesses that Mario is prone to and you know it just it

01:06:06.840 --> 01:06:13.680
[Guest]: strikes me as a piece that gives you this deep insight into a person populates his world

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:19.600
[Guest]: describes what the kind of spaces are that he moves through why he is the way he is and

01:06:19.600 --> 01:06:24.160
[Guest]: what it is like to be in his presence I think there are very few pieces I think that convey

01:06:24.160 --> 01:06:28.960
[Guest]: better what a person is like if you were to meet him and that is something that I'm always

01:06:28.960 --> 01:06:32.800
[Guest]: trying to do with you know my profiles as well because that's the whole idea it has

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:38.120
[Guest]: this great sense of how to use detail how to accrete it and how to deploy it in the

01:06:38.120 --> 01:06:44.040
[Guest]: language is also in a sense slightly larger than life but in a good way because it suits

01:06:44.040 --> 01:06:47.840
[Guest]: the subject whereas if this was the same thing if you were writing about a much more sober

01:06:47.840 --> 01:06:51.480
[Guest]: restrained person maybe you wouldn't quite write the same way so it's it's something

