01:08:10.400 --> 01:08:13.560
[Amit Varma]: welcome back to the scene in the unseen I'm chatting with Saman Subramaniam about his

01:08:13.560 --> 01:08:20.200
[Amit Varma]: book a dominant character about JBS Haldane what what drove you to this interesting figure

01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:24.880
[Amit Varma]: because you know you've been a cricket writer you studied international relations at Columbia

01:08:24.880 --> 01:08:28.240
[Amit Varma]: there are so many things you could have and there are so many things you do write about

01:08:28.240 --> 01:08:33.080
[Amit Varma]: and your journalism has so many eclectic subjects why Haldane how did you arrive at him ironically

01:08:33.080 --> 01:08:36.600
[Guest]: I think perhaps for the first time I'd heard about him was in a quiz many years ago and

01:08:36.600 --> 01:08:41.920
[Guest]: then I kind of looked him up a little bit online and even his even if you read his basic

01:08:41.920 --> 01:08:46.400
[Guest]: Wikipedia bio so it's a very fascinating read I mean the kind of work that he did but also

01:08:46.400 --> 01:08:51.240
[Guest]: the kind of life that he led it was a really sort of larger than life so to speak and it

01:08:51.240 --> 01:08:55.280
[Guest]: seemed to straddle all of these worlds that I found myself interested in I mean he was

01:08:55.280 --> 01:08:59.080
[Guest]: a scientist and I have been interested in science for a long time but also he was intensely

01:08:59.080 --> 01:09:03.400
[Guest]: politically committed he lived an adventurous life in the sense that he fought in the trenches

01:09:03.400 --> 01:09:09.760
[Guest]: in the first world war he went to Spain during the civil war he did sort of research on himself

01:09:09.760 --> 01:09:13.520
[Guest]: for the British admiralty in the second world war and then he had this Indian connection

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:17.200
[Guest]: of course although it wasn't necessarily because of that that I latched on to him but I found

01:09:17.200 --> 01:09:22.080
[Guest]: it interesting that he came to India and lived the last seven odd years of his life and died

01:09:22.080 --> 01:09:26.640
[Guest]: here to the extent that he became an Indian citizen and that movement itself we are always

01:09:26.640 --> 01:09:30.760
[Guest]: familiar with movements in the reverse direction scientists leaving India to go overseas and

01:09:30.760 --> 01:09:36.120
[Guest]: so I thought it might be an interesting life through which to examine these intersections

01:09:36.120 --> 01:09:41.120
[Guest]: of science and politics science and society and also to examine his particular milieus

01:09:41.120 --> 01:09:45.040
[Guest]: in that time in the first half of the 20th century that is the explanation that I would

01:09:45.040 --> 01:09:49.240
[Guest]: give from the point of view of Haldane himself but then the second thing which is diverse

01:09:49.240 --> 01:09:52.840
[Guest]: of Haldane in a sense is that you know I had written a bunch of profiles by the time I

01:09:52.840 --> 01:09:57.000
[Guest]: started working on this book and I was intensely curious to see whether I could write a biography

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:01.680
[Guest]: so a form that has fascinated me and that I read a lot of and it seems to be an extension

01:10:01.680 --> 01:10:06.240
[Guest]: of the profile although as I realized isn't exactly and then all my journalism until now

01:10:06.240 --> 01:10:11.200
[Guest]: has been structured around places that I can go to and people who I can meet I depend on

01:10:11.200 --> 01:10:16.000
[Guest]: my being in a particular place to make things vivid for the reader which was definitely

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:20.800
[Guest]: the case with my first two books and I wanted to see almost as a kind of experiment of form

01:10:20.800 --> 01:10:25.280
[Guest]: how you would pursue and achieve that kind of vividness if you were not in a place if

01:10:25.280 --> 01:10:29.920
[Guest]: you were not able to talk to people if you had to rely purely on archival and documentary

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:34.520
[Guest]: material to present your scenes and your character so it was sort of mini challenge that I set

01:10:34.520 --> 01:10:40.520
[Guest]: up for myself and Haldane seemed to be sort of a good way to do that partly because he

01:10:40.520 --> 01:10:45.040
[Guest]: himself wrote a lot so there's a lot that you can glean from his own materials and writings

01:10:45.040 --> 01:10:50.040
[Guest]: but then secondarily he lived through such interesting and widely described times you

01:10:50.040 --> 01:10:53.840
[Guest]: know the first world war the second world war that there's a multiplicity of sources

01:10:53.840 --> 01:10:58.540
[Guest]: you can consult to then synthesize all of that and make a vivid scene out of it something

01:10:58.540 --> 01:11:02.520
[Guest]: that can hopefully come alive in the mind of the reader and these were the two reasons

01:11:02.520 --> 01:11:07.240
[Amit Varma]: I guess that I was drawn to Haldane as a subject so you know when I think of the biographies

01:11:07.240 --> 01:11:11.120
[Amit Varma]: I love and I loved your biography of Haldane you know one book which I spoke about on a

01:11:11.120 --> 01:11:15.480
[Amit Varma]: recent episode and I really loved was Robert Caro's A Power Broker and one of the main

01:11:15.480 --> 01:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: reasons I loved that was it works at so many different levels it is a life story of one

01:11:20.000 --> 01:11:26.480
[Amit Varma]: man yes but it is also in a sense a biography of New York City it's a study of how power

01:11:26.480 --> 01:11:32.360
[Amit Varma]: corrodes character it's a study of how political economies evolve over a period of time it's

01:11:32.360 --> 01:11:37.000
[Amit Varma]: a study of competing ideologies when you you know look at the battle between Moses and

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:42.720
[Amit Varma]: Jane Jacobs and similarly it seemed to me that what I really enjoyed about a dominant

01:11:42.720 --> 01:11:47.040
[Amit Varma]: character is not so much the biography of this one incredibly interesting man which

01:11:47.040 --> 01:11:52.580
[Amit Varma]: is you know fascinating in its own regard but also the larger themes that came up specifically

01:11:52.580 --> 01:11:56.720
[Amit Varma]: and of course we'll talk about it in much more detail about the intersection between

01:11:56.720 --> 01:12:02.040
[Amit Varma]: politics and science which is you know such a big theme in this so you know did you sort

01:12:02.040 --> 01:12:07.960
[Amit Varma]: of have these themes in mind when you actually entered the project or did they take shape

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:12.640
[Amit Varma]: I see I didn't say fructify or did they take shape as you were sort of moving through the

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:17.840
[Guest]: material I think the main theme of the which is the theme of the interplay between science

01:12:17.840 --> 01:12:21.520
[Guest]: and politics I think was something that is quite transparent to anyone who has even read

01:12:21.520 --> 01:12:24.840
[Guest]: a little bit about Haldane so I think even when I started when I sent the pitch out for

01:12:24.840 --> 01:12:28.700
[Guest]: this book that was definitely one of the themes that I wanted to explore there were other

01:12:28.700 --> 01:12:32.780
[Guest]: things that I thought were interesting that came up much later one of them for example

01:12:32.780 --> 01:12:39.720
[Guest]: was Haldane's view of what and what a utopian society was for him and that view itself changed

01:12:39.720 --> 01:12:45.120
[Guest]: over time as he got older and grew to be disillusioned with certain things and entranced by new other

01:12:45.120 --> 01:12:49.720
[Guest]: things and so those themes I guess like came up as I researched it but this question of

01:12:49.720 --> 01:12:53.560
[Guest]: the twinning of science and politics was something that I was fascinated by when I first started

01:12:53.560 --> 01:12:58.920
[Guest]: reading about Haldane and this was in I have to think back here it was in 2015 I think

01:12:58.920 --> 01:13:03.960
[Guest]: January 2015 is when I started really reading to research this book in some detail I could

01:13:03.960 --> 01:13:10.240
[Guest]: not have known at the time how intensely those themes would resonate five years later definitely

01:13:10.240 --> 01:13:15.920
[Guest]: there were you know I already had at the back of my mind you know some notion of how science

01:13:15.920 --> 01:13:20.220
[Guest]: and politics intersected in the realm of climate change you know my wife was for a long time

01:13:20.220 --> 01:13:23.880
[Guest]: a climate change journalist and of course anybody who's reasonably well read these days

01:13:23.880 --> 01:13:30.000
[Guest]: has read enough about how climate change science is itself shaped by political and economic

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:33.760
[Guest]: interests but I wanted to broaden that a little bit and kind of look at the history of that

01:13:33.760 --> 01:13:38.120
[Guest]: and look at how Haldane himself dealt with it indeed even acknowledged it and then built

01:13:38.120 --> 01:13:43.960
[Guest]: upon it but five years later here we are where a president is in power in the US who denies

01:13:43.960 --> 01:13:48.600
[Guest]: so much of science to the extent that science you know marches for science started three

01:13:48.600 --> 01:13:52.800
[Guest]: and a half years ago in America first and then spread to the rest of the world and you

01:13:52.800 --> 01:13:57.400
[Guest]: know even as that built we come to 2020 when a pandemic is in play all over the world when

01:13:57.400 --> 01:14:03.920
[Guest]: the science of vaccine research of disease of epidemiology of how data is interpreted

01:14:03.920 --> 01:14:08.760
[Guest]: and presented has become an intensely political idea because to lose control of this narrative

01:14:08.760 --> 01:14:14.160
[Guest]: would be to admit not only political failure but also to admit a certain lack of comprehension

01:14:14.160 --> 01:14:18.440
[Guest]: of science you know I'm living here in the UK where for example the government took a

01:14:18.440 --> 01:14:23.880
[Guest]: decision to go with one kind of you know model to control the epidemic before changing track

01:14:23.880 --> 01:14:28.080
[Guest]: after a couple of weeks they wanted to pursue the Swedish model of trying to build herd

01:14:28.080 --> 01:14:32.000
[Guest]: immunity before they realized that you know health services would get swamped and they

01:14:32.000 --> 01:14:36.680
[Guest]: had to just lock the whole country down so these even more than you know three years

01:14:36.680 --> 01:14:41.400
[Guest]: ago two years ago or even last year this is a moment in time when I think Paul Dane would

01:14:41.400 --> 01:14:47.920
[Guest]: have spoken most eloquently to what the government isn't doing how literate and numerate policymakers

01:14:47.920 --> 01:14:52.560
[Guest]: are and even how literate and numerate all of us are in terms of science because I think

01:14:52.560 --> 01:14:58.520
[Guest]: Paul Dane's overarching principle was that everybody should have a scientific mindset

01:14:58.520 --> 01:15:03.880
[Guest]: and ability to look at information and assess it based on evidence that is not just useful

01:15:03.880 --> 01:15:08.440
[Guest]: to people who work in labs and in biotech companies but people who go about their daily

01:15:08.440 --> 01:15:10.880
[Guest]: lives in a world that is dictated by science.

01:15:10.880 --> 01:15:15.280
[Amit Varma]: So I was sort of fascinated also by the bits that you have on Paul Dane's childhood one

01:15:15.280 --> 01:15:19.520
[Amit Varma]: of course because he was extremely prodigious like you write in his book quote the time

01:15:19.520 --> 01:15:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Paul Dane legend has it he looked intently at the blood trickling out of a cut on his

01:15:23.600 --> 01:15:29.240
[Amit Varma]: forehead and asked is it oxyhemoglobin or carboxyhemoglobin he was not yet four which

01:15:29.240 --> 01:15:34.320
[Amit Varma]: is you know obviously a crazy kind of prodigy but also a creature of circumstance in the

01:15:34.320 --> 01:15:39.640
[Amit Varma]: sense he was born to a certain kind of extreme privilege where his father was a great scientist

01:15:39.640 --> 01:15:44.160
[Amit Varma]: and more than that what possibly made him different from his peers was that his father

01:15:44.160 --> 01:15:48.720
[Amit Varma]: believed in actually going out into the field and practicing science like if he wanted to

01:15:48.720 --> 01:15:53.000
[Amit Varma]: figure out why miners were diving he would go down into the mines himself and spend time

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:57.480
[Amit Varma]: and experiment on himself with the whole you know notion of taking a cannery to the coal

01:15:57.480 --> 01:16:02.800
[Amit Varma]: mine came from him and the young JBS accompanied him on all these trips so he saw this sort

01:16:02.800 --> 01:16:08.520
[Amit Varma]: of this other side of English society which similarly privileged kids would not have you

01:16:08.520 --> 01:16:13.640
[Amit Varma]: know how much of for example when you look at say the British intellectuals of the 1910s

01:16:13.640 --> 01:16:18.480
[Amit Varma]: or 20s or 30s would it be fair to say that they were pretty much all born to extreme

01:16:18.480 --> 01:16:24.880
[Amit Varma]: privilege and that what kind of might have drawn Paul Dane apart was that he also had

01:16:24.880 --> 01:16:29.440
[Amit Varma]: a sensitivity to the other side which came both from accompanying his father to all of

01:16:29.440 --> 01:16:33.000
[Amit Varma]: these places and also the time he spent in the trenches in the first world war as you

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:37.760
[Guest]: point out yeah I think definitely among the you know the intellectuals in this field of

01:16:37.760 --> 01:16:42.800
[Guest]: biology and physiology whom I read about while writing this book you had to have done the

01:16:42.800 --> 01:16:46.760
[Guest]: whole public school which here is a book you know it's called public school elsewhere it's

01:16:46.760 --> 01:16:50.720
[Guest]: private school so a public school education followed by a stint at Oxford or Cambridge

01:16:50.720 --> 01:16:55.200
[Guest]: at the very least maybe two stints you know and Hardin did follow that model in some detail

01:16:55.200 --> 01:16:59.720
[Guest]: he went to Eton as a King scholar he followed that up by going to Oxford for his undergraduate

01:16:59.720 --> 01:17:06.360
[Guest]: degree so you know all of that seems to fit the CV of many other intellectuals in the

01:17:06.360 --> 01:17:09.800
[Guest]: physiological sciences at the time but you're completely right in that what set him apart

01:17:09.800 --> 01:17:14.300
[Guest]: and what set his childhood apart was this exposure to parts of British society that

01:17:14.300 --> 01:17:18.640
[Guest]: none of the others would ever have had or very few would have had and I think you know

01:17:18.640 --> 01:17:23.440
[Guest]: this taught him a few things one is that it taught him the defects of science has real

01:17:23.440 --> 01:17:28.800
[Guest]: world effects and it has real world problems that can be addressed and as his father believed

01:17:28.800 --> 01:17:32.960
[Guest]: it didn't just all have to be done within the confines of a lab on our pen and paper

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:37.080
[Guest]: this is ironic because Hardin himself would for the most part use pen and paper and very

01:17:37.080 --> 01:17:42.920
[Guest]: little else in his own work but he was always aware of the link between what he was doing

01:17:42.920 --> 01:17:48.440
[Guest]: and what the real world needed or required or had a deficit of so there was the fact

01:17:48.440 --> 01:17:52.400
[Guest]: that he got to meet people like this all the time but the second thing that was quite egalitarian

01:17:52.400 --> 01:17:56.280
[Guest]: about what his father did was that he used himself as a guinea pig this is something

01:17:56.280 --> 01:18:01.400
[Guest]: that would have been quite unthinkable at a time when you could pay a poor person to

01:18:01.400 --> 01:18:05.560
[Guest]: serve as a guinea pig for you you know there are distinctions in class in race all of these

01:18:05.560 --> 01:18:10.280
[Guest]: things were so vast that you didn't have to use yourself it was a very egalitarian move

01:18:10.280 --> 01:18:15.720
[Guest]: on the part of Hardin senior to subject himself to the kind of pressures quite literally I

01:18:15.720 --> 01:18:21.160
[Guest]: mean air pressure temperatures you know humidity lack of oxygen all of these factors are going

01:18:21.160 --> 01:18:27.880
[Guest]: to play for sailors and submarines or for miners very deep down in a coal mine he would

01:18:27.880 --> 01:18:31.120
[Guest]: put himself through those same conditions and examine what the effects were like on

01:18:31.120 --> 01:18:36.560
[Guest]: him Hardin senior's logic in this was how would you ever know the precise physiological

01:18:36.560 --> 01:18:40.280
[Guest]: effects unless you underwent them yourself and maybe that was a scientific way of looking

01:18:40.280 --> 01:18:45.160
[Guest]: at it and he didn't quite think about the egalitarian nest that was implicit in this

01:18:45.160 --> 01:18:48.720
[Guest]: and I think that taught young JBS a lesson that he would remember all his life which

01:18:48.720 --> 01:18:53.040
[Guest]: is basically that everyone is essentially physiologically created equal and that they

01:18:53.040 --> 01:18:57.840
[Guest]: should therefore then be equal in the eyes of the law and of society and I want to read

01:18:57.840 --> 01:19:01.680
[Amit Varma]: out a bit from an essay that Holden wrote much later but I want to bring it to bear

01:19:01.680 --> 01:19:05.280
[Amit Varma]: on a question about his upbringing in fact where you know towards the end of his life

01:19:05.280 --> 01:19:10.600
[Amit Varma]: he wrote an essay called what ails Indian science and in that he wrote quote I noticed

01:19:10.600 --> 01:19:15.360
[Amit Varma]: that in India a new caste system is developing before the old one has disappeared the new

01:19:15.360 --> 01:19:19.680
[Amit Varma]: system is based on academic degrees one cannot teach Bengali chemistry history or what you

01:19:19.680 --> 01:19:24.000
[Amit Varma]: will without a degree in that subject and a higher degree given for research is almost

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:29.200
[Amit Varma]: obligatory if one hopes for a professional chair it is only a matter of time before I

01:19:29.200 --> 01:19:33.480
[Amit Varma]: am debarred from teaching science or statistics since I have no degree of any kind in these

01:19:33.480 --> 01:19:37.740
[Amit Varma]: subjects but in terms of the new caste system I'm qualified to teach the classics since

01:19:37.740 --> 01:19:43.860
[Amit Varma]: I secured a somewhat marginal first class in literary human yours vulgarly called greats

01:19:43.860 --> 01:19:49.880
[Amit Varma]: at Oxford stop good and and my question sort of here goes you know also to the term which

01:19:49.880 --> 01:19:54.400
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned in the context of quizzing which is bricolage which is holding was born in

01:19:54.400 --> 01:20:00.200
[Amit Varma]: the 19th century in November 1892 seems to be that classic maybe in that last generation

01:20:00.200 --> 01:20:05.200
[Amit Varma]: of 19th century intellectuals who have studied a variety of different subjects they haven't

01:20:05.200 --> 01:20:10.800
[Amit Varma]: specialized in one thing and you know which shows even in a scientific work I think one

01:20:10.800 --> 01:20:15.680
[Amit Varma]: of your chapters is called synthesis where you know he's bringing this broader outlook

01:20:15.680 --> 01:20:20.360
[Amit Varma]: this ability to step back and solving that debate between say the Mendelians and the

01:20:20.360 --> 01:20:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Darwinists because he can take that step back because he has all that training in other

01:20:24.480 --> 01:20:30.720
[Amit Varma]: things and he can quote Plato and Aristotle and Lucretius and all of those guys and how

01:20:30.720 --> 01:20:37.240
[Amit Varma]: important do you think that is to break through thinking in any field and is it a loss for

01:20:37.240 --> 01:20:41.960
[Amit Varma]: how knowledge develops that we don't seem to have much of that anymore yeah I mean it's

01:20:41.960 --> 01:20:47.040
[Guest]: interesting I think Haldane would have been among the last generations in science who

01:20:47.040 --> 01:20:51.080
[Guest]: could come to science without a degree in it I doubt and as a part of research for this

01:20:51.080 --> 01:20:54.360
[Guest]: book I would I mean obviously I didn't have anybody to interview and quote but what I

01:20:54.360 --> 01:20:58.160
[Guest]: would do is talk to other scientists just about his work but also about some of these

01:20:58.160 --> 01:21:02.920
[Guest]: themes and one of the themes that came up quite often is this question of specialization

01:21:02.920 --> 01:21:06.680
[Guest]: and how Haldane would have been among the last of the serious scientists who would have

01:21:06.680 --> 01:21:12.400
[Guest]: not specialized in at the undergraduate level in part it is a nature of how science develops

01:21:12.400 --> 01:21:17.600
[Guest]: is that it has gotten over the 20th century genetics let's take an example like genetics

01:21:17.600 --> 01:21:22.620
[Guest]: and got so specialized that you had to start specializing quite early to be able to then

01:21:22.620 --> 01:21:26.840
[Guest]: fine-tune your research to an even deeper point by the time you reach a postdoctorate

01:21:26.840 --> 01:21:32.000
[Guest]: level you couldn't start off or very rarely could you start off studying English and then

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:36.440
[Guest]: switching broadly to biology in at your master's and then going further in that I mean it didn't

01:21:36.440 --> 01:21:40.560
[Guest]: happen you had to you know this is also the structure of higher education itself today

01:21:40.560 --> 01:21:45.200
[Guest]: is that by the time you finish your undergraduate degree you're expected to have completed two

01:21:45.200 --> 01:21:48.960
[Guest]: internships and spent time in a lab in the university somewhere and you know it's a very

01:21:48.960 --> 01:21:55.120
[Guest]: intense and intensely specialized feeling and a lot of that is inevitable a lot of it

01:21:55.120 --> 01:21:59.080
[Guest]: has benefits because obviously if you start thinking about specific problems from the

01:21:59.080 --> 01:22:03.080
[Guest]: time you're 21 by the time you're 30 you've actually sort of made great headway in that

01:22:03.080 --> 01:22:08.240
[Guest]: particular problem but a number of scientists told me that there is a loss in it as well

01:22:08.240 --> 01:22:12.000
[Guest]: as you said so this you know what Haldane said about the Indian caste system about the

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:17.440
[Guest]: specialization of knowledge has permeated every field everywhere by now and it particularly

01:22:17.440 --> 01:22:22.080
[Guest]: includes the sciences and I think a number of scientists felt that loss felt the loss

01:22:22.080 --> 01:22:27.080
[Guest]: of the generalist not the journalist the generalist coming to science and seeing bigger problems

01:22:27.080 --> 01:22:31.960
[Guest]: and being able to knit various aspects together from a multidisciplinary point of view and

01:22:31.960 --> 01:22:38.840
[Guest]: this catchphrase multidisciplinary I think is only now slowly starting to re-emerge in

01:22:38.840 --> 01:22:43.920
[Guest]: academia somewhat in the sciences I think but in other fields as well I think the advantage

01:22:43.920 --> 01:22:49.240
[Guest]: of what people like Haldane brought to this table is being starting to be recognized again

01:22:49.240 --> 01:22:55.240
[Guest]: because precisely because scientists have not over the last half century say have stopped

01:22:55.240 --> 01:22:59.520
[Guest]: thinking too deeply or too intensely about the political effects of their work if you

01:22:59.520 --> 01:23:05.000
[Guest]: are in one silo you rarely see the effects of that silo on other silos or upon the general

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:08.800
[Guest]: world or upon the world outside and I think that is starting to be realized more and more

01:23:08.800 --> 01:23:12.840
[Guest]: as everybody becomes a little bit more politically aware I think that is starting to be realized

01:23:12.840 --> 01:23:17.580
[Guest]: more and more I hope I mean and again the last three years have seen a complete efflorescence

01:23:17.580 --> 01:23:22.880
[Guest]: of political thinking on the part of scientists aided in no small part by the kind of political

01:23:22.880 --> 01:23:27.320
[Guest]: regimes in power all over the world I think more and more we will start to see the benefits

01:23:27.320 --> 01:23:32.360
[Amit Varma]: of that in scientific research itself and what was also sort of apparent in the biography

01:23:32.360 --> 01:23:36.880
[Amit Varma]: and I want to you know discuss three different aspects of Haldane first as a scientist and

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:41.800
[Amit Varma]: as a writer slash public intellectual and then finally his politics but it struck me

01:23:41.800 --> 01:23:47.160
[Amit Varma]: while reading about his scientific career that in a sense he went wherever his intellectual

01:23:47.160 --> 01:23:51.880
[Amit Varma]: curiosity took him and it also strikes me and I don't know if you'd have a view on it

01:23:51.880 --> 01:23:56.120
[Amit Varma]: that a modern day scientist so people training to be scientists are subject to different

01:23:56.120 --> 01:24:01.000
[Amit Varma]: sets of incentives whereas you know this is your tenure track and this is your publication

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:05.280
[Amit Varma]: track and if you want to get funding these are the kind of projects which are you know

01:24:05.280 --> 01:24:10.640
[Amit Varma]: quote-unquote sexy and all of these incentives will then shape their entire careers and their

01:24:10.640 --> 01:24:15.040
[Amit Varma]: entire bodies of work is that broadly true is that something you've heard about from

01:24:15.040 --> 01:24:19.680
[Amit Varma]: the scientific communities is that something that you know people kind of have thought

01:24:19.680 --> 01:24:23.640
[Guest]: about and written about is it a problem absolutely I mean a number of scientists told me for

01:24:23.640 --> 01:24:28.240
[Guest]: example the fact that many scientists for a long time chose to not have too much of

01:24:28.240 --> 01:24:32.960
[Guest]: a political voice you know in part it's because this ivory tower phenomenon has built up more

01:24:32.960 --> 01:24:39.600
[Guest]: and more over the 20th century academics feel that they're insulated to to an unreasonable

01:24:39.600 --> 01:24:43.200
[Guest]: extent from the real world because they don't often experience its problems especially once

01:24:43.200 --> 01:24:46.560
[Guest]: you have tenure so all of that is there but there's definitely people who told me that

01:24:46.560 --> 01:24:51.280
[Guest]: having a political voice meant often speaking out against a government that is in power

01:24:51.280 --> 01:24:55.240
[Guest]: when it is that government that decides what grants institutions decide what grants you

01:24:55.240 --> 01:25:00.280
[Guest]: get and so therefore you try not to piss them off sometimes entire research programs are

01:25:00.280 --> 01:25:04.920
[Guest]: funded by corporations that eventually want to monetize technologies or processes for

01:25:04.920 --> 01:25:09.340
[Guest]: themselves speaking out against those corporations is not a wise thing to do if you're depending

01:25:09.340 --> 01:25:13.920
[Guest]: on them for your research money and so a lot of these constricted scientists ability to

01:25:13.920 --> 01:25:19.360
[Guest]: have a voice now this is also again a natural byproduct of just how science evolves if you

01:25:19.360 --> 01:25:24.000
[Guest]: look at what the field of genetics was like when Haldane was born Mendel had not been

01:25:24.000 --> 01:25:30.680
[Guest]: rediscovered there were big problems out there that you could access sort of from a generalist

01:25:30.680 --> 01:25:35.260
[Guest]: point of view with very little equipment certainly and whatever equipment you needed wasn't sort

01:25:35.260 --> 01:25:39.760
[Guest]: of very expensive in Haldane's case has always turned out to be it was pen and paper and

01:25:39.760 --> 01:25:44.160
[Guest]: you could apply yourself to these things without having to depend on large grants and so on

01:25:44.160 --> 01:25:48.680
[Guest]: and even Haldane despite all of that did feel the pinch of you know the lack of finances

01:25:48.680 --> 01:25:54.680
[Guest]: at various points in his career now the situation is you know has progressed to the point where

01:25:54.680 --> 01:25:59.640
[Guest]: you need a plethora of expensive equipment your big problems have been addressed for

01:25:59.640 --> 01:26:03.880
[Guest]: the large part and you have to drill down into small problems and as a result of all

01:26:03.880 --> 01:26:08.760
[Guest]: of this you know you don't want to jeopardize perhaps quite rightly and understandably you

01:26:08.760 --> 01:26:12.920
[Guest]: don't want to jeopardize your ability to get these big grants to then work on these quite

01:26:12.920 --> 01:26:17.080
[Guest]: specific problems I think it's an inevitable nature of the march of science you know that

01:26:17.080 --> 01:26:21.280
[Guest]: from when the 20th century started and when the 21st century started science is unrecognizable

01:26:21.280 --> 01:26:25.480
[Guest]: whereas you couldn't always say that of say the 16th and the 17th centuries or 17th and

01:26:25.480 --> 01:26:29.360
[Guest]: 18th centuries you know I mean the paradigm shift has been immense and I think it's a

01:26:29.360 --> 01:26:34.040
[Guest]: consequence of that scientists feel that a lot of their freedoms and a lot of what they

01:26:34.040 --> 01:26:38.520
[Guest]: would otherwise want to say and do is dictated quite heavily by the nature of their work

01:26:38.520 --> 01:26:43.480
[Amit Varma]: and the way their work is funded so you know let's talk about Haldane as a scientist now

01:26:43.480 --> 01:26:49.160
[Amit Varma]: obviously his major contributions are in the field of genetics but he also dabbled widely

01:26:49.160 --> 01:26:52.520
[Amit Varma]: elsewhere for example I was not aware it's something that I learned in your book that

01:26:52.520 --> 01:26:57.080
[Amit Varma]: our notion of the primordial soup so to say comes from Haldane that he simultaneously

01:26:57.080 --> 01:27:02.000
[Amit Varma]: and independently with the Russian scientists you know conceived of the origins of life

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:06.600
[Amit Varma]: lying in some kind of chemical soup where the Sun interacted and with chemicals and

01:27:06.600 --> 01:27:12.000
[Amit Varma]: created amino acids and so on which I wasn't aware of but broadly he is remembered for

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:16.440
[Amit Varma]: his contributions in genetics so tell me a little bit about that and when I say broadly

01:27:16.440 --> 01:27:21.280
[Amit Varma]: he has remembered as you point out that he's not even remembered that much because much

01:27:21.280 --> 01:27:25.840
[Amit Varma]: of his work was so foundational and essential that we cannot just take it for granted which

01:27:25.840 --> 01:27:29.880
[Guest]: is something he always thought was the best fate ever for a scientist by the way he thought

01:27:29.880 --> 01:27:33.640
[Guest]: that the best compliment you could pay to a scientist work is to not even think about

01:27:33.640 --> 01:27:37.920
[Guest]: how it's done that you just think that they are natural laws and axioms that we found

01:27:37.920 --> 01:27:43.880
[Guest]: out there are then attributed to one person so I mean Haldane's biggest scientific contribution

01:27:43.880 --> 01:27:48.920
[Guest]: was in a subfield of what we might call modern synthesis so to take us back to the early

01:27:48.920 --> 01:27:53.880
[Guest]: 20th century what had happened was that Darwin had set out the theory of evolution by natural

01:27:53.880 --> 01:27:58.640
[Guest]: selection and it had found a lot of traction but for some reason nobody could quite understand

01:27:58.640 --> 01:28:05.480
[Guest]: how natural selection would work at this cellular level and when I say that the reason is that

01:28:05.480 --> 01:28:09.920
[Guest]: Mendel who had published his papers also in the 19th century his work had been sort of

01:28:09.920 --> 01:28:15.040
[Guest]: largely forgotten or not quite recognized for its significance in the way that it should

01:28:15.040 --> 01:28:20.480
[Guest]: have been nobody had tied Mendel to Darwin nobody had seen that Mendel had set out these

01:28:20.480 --> 01:28:26.280
[Guest]: units of hereditary information called genes and the big riddle left by Darwin's theory

01:28:26.280 --> 01:28:31.320
[Guest]: which is how actually natural selection works at that level at the cellular level that could

01:28:31.320 --> 01:28:38.600
[Guest]: have been answered by uniting Mendel and Darwin and that rediscovery happened in 1900 and

01:28:38.600 --> 01:28:42.760
[Guest]: a few years thereafter about eight years after Haldane was born so that was a state the science

01:28:42.760 --> 01:28:48.360
[Guest]: was in when Haldane went into university and broadly people who worked in this new field

01:28:48.360 --> 01:28:52.440
[Guest]: of genetics and evolution split themselves into two camps one was the Darwinians and

01:28:52.440 --> 01:28:57.480
[Guest]: one was the Mendelians and the Mendelians believed that these units called genes existed

01:28:57.480 --> 01:29:03.720
[Guest]: and they produced big discrete changes in organisms because they were going by Mendel's

01:29:03.720 --> 01:29:09.400
[Guest]: work so they believed that as Mendel had discovered there was a gene for determining whether a

01:29:09.400 --> 01:29:14.600
[Guest]: pea had a smooth surface or whether it had a textured and wrinkly surface there were

01:29:14.600 --> 01:29:19.040
[Guest]: two types of genes and whichever one was dominant would dictate what the pea's texture was like

01:29:19.040 --> 01:29:24.160
[Guest]: the Mendelians assumed that this is how genes work big discrete changes the Darwinians believe

01:29:24.160 --> 01:29:28.680
[Guest]: because Darwin had also postulated this that what was actually happening in a population

01:29:28.680 --> 01:29:33.920
[Guest]: was that there were a number of very small variations that would eventually accumulate

01:29:33.920 --> 01:29:39.200
[Guest]: over time to produce enough variation to then distinguish a species from another one so

01:29:39.200 --> 01:29:44.680
[Guest]: the Darwinians would criticize Mendelians for saying look you can say that a pea is

01:29:44.680 --> 01:29:49.480
[Guest]: textured or smooth but you can't explain a variation of heights in a population for example

01:29:49.480 --> 01:29:53.560
[Guest]: because it's not just people are either tall or short there is every single height on the

01:29:53.560 --> 01:29:57.880
[Guest]: spectrum is to be found and you have a smooth bell curve where there is an average kind

01:29:57.880 --> 01:30:01.960
[Guest]: of height and the Darwinians believe that that was explained only by their own theory

01:30:01.960 --> 01:30:06.400
[Guest]: of small variations in a population but they couldn't explain how these small variations

01:30:06.400 --> 01:30:12.240
[Guest]: would have the kind of huge effects that would then create a new species altogether or to

01:30:12.240 --> 01:30:16.600
[Guest]: create a completely different feature altogether and so this was a big inherent tussle that

01:30:16.600 --> 01:30:21.720
[Guest]: nobody could quite explain and Haldane along with a couple of other scientists explained

01:30:21.720 --> 01:30:26.440
[Guest]: this essentially united these or synthesized these two views of genetics and evolution

01:30:26.440 --> 01:30:30.600
[Guest]: with what we call the modern synthesis which is intensely mathematically based but what

01:30:30.600 --> 01:30:35.560
[Guest]: he and a couple of others did was to show through math that the small variations that

01:30:35.560 --> 01:30:40.680
[Guest]: Haldane that Darwin postulated those small variations could with the power of natural

01:30:40.680 --> 01:30:44.920
[Guest]: selection and he would build models out to explain how this would be possible could have

01:30:44.920 --> 01:30:49.880
[Guest]: enough of a selective advantage to actually create new species or to create big changes

01:30:49.880 --> 01:30:54.960
[Guest]: in a species so the power of natural selection and at a time when people thought natural

01:30:54.960 --> 01:31:00.160
[Guest]: selection was almost dead because it couldn't explain speciation as powerfully as that at

01:31:00.160 --> 01:31:04.560
[Guest]: time when it was almost dead Haldane and these two other scientists Ronald Fisher and Seymour

01:31:04.560 --> 01:31:10.140
[Guest]: Wright they managed to explain through mathematics how this was possible they essentially brought

01:31:10.140 --> 01:31:14.680
[Guest]: natural selection from the 19th century into the 20th century and pushed it forward towards

01:31:14.680 --> 01:31:15.680
[Amit Varma]: the 21st.

01:31:15.680 --> 01:31:21.240
[Amit Varma]: I also found it fascinating how big and you know how passionate he was about maths and

01:31:21.240 --> 01:31:25.120
[Amit Varma]: how big that was a part of his arsenal like you've described on you know how he'd be on

01:31:25.120 --> 01:31:29.000
[Amit Varma]: a bus and he'd always have a briefcase with him and it was very common for him just to

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:33.080
[Amit Varma]: take out paper from there and start doing algebra on the bus and you know he was kind

01:31:33.080 --> 01:31:39.040
[Amit Varma]: of scribbling all the time and you also illustrated how using math alone he showed that natural

01:31:39.040 --> 01:31:44.640
[Amit Varma]: selection was responsible for a certain kind of moth population instead of having mainly

01:31:44.640 --> 01:31:49.600
[Amit Varma]: I think silverish wings going to you know black wings which I found you know so fascinating

01:31:49.600 --> 01:31:55.200
[Amit Varma]: and so illustrative and so amazing that someone can just you know essentially get to that

01:31:55.200 --> 01:31:58.320
[Amit Varma]: proof by just taking pen and paper and kind of getting it done.

01:31:58.320 --> 01:32:01.600
[Amit Varma]: You want to talk a little bit about this because I just found it really fascinating and yeah

01:32:01.600 --> 01:32:06.360
[Guest]: absolutely yeah one of his favorite phrases was an ounce of algebra is worth a ton of

01:32:06.360 --> 01:32:10.560
[Guest]: verbal argument which is I think like a fascinating way to describe it.

01:32:10.560 --> 01:32:14.040
[Guest]: So Haldane was you know consummately the pen and paper guy to the extent that he would

01:32:14.040 --> 01:32:17.280
[Guest]: not even go out and collect his own field data you know field data was often collected

01:32:17.280 --> 01:32:20.480
[Guest]: by other people and he would just sort of get those data sets and he would look at it.

01:32:20.480 --> 01:32:25.680
[Guest]: So one of the things that he worked on was the data set of moth populations in and around

01:32:25.680 --> 01:32:32.560
[Guest]: Manchester in the 19th century and what had happened, what lepidopterists had observed

01:32:32.560 --> 01:32:37.520
[Guest]: was that there used to be you know a moth with silver gray wings called Biston betularia.

01:32:37.520 --> 01:32:42.200
[Guest]: A surprisingly short period of time these silvery moths disappeared to be replaced by

01:32:42.200 --> 01:32:46.800
[Guest]: moths with almost entirely black wings and it happened so fast that people couldn't quite

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:48.480
[Guest]: figure out how this was possible.

01:32:48.480 --> 01:32:52.440
[Guest]: For a long time one of the theories was that the soot from the factories of the Industrial

01:32:52.440 --> 01:32:55.720
[Guest]: Revolution was darkening the wings of the moths.

01:32:55.720 --> 01:32:59.440
[Guest]: It was actually as a layer, it was a black soot layer on top of the wings.

01:32:59.440 --> 01:33:03.240
[Guest]: There was another theory that said that there were a lot of chemicals in the air that caused

01:33:03.240 --> 01:33:08.320
[Guest]: these moths to mutate very fast so a silvery moth itself became a black moth in its own

01:33:08.320 --> 01:33:09.320
[Guest]: lifetime.

01:33:09.320 --> 01:33:12.240
[Guest]: You know these were the kind of theories that were floating around at the time and then

01:33:12.240 --> 01:33:16.800
[Guest]: eventually of course people did realize that the moths that had black wings were getting

01:33:16.800 --> 01:33:22.840
[Guest]: some kind of selective advantage because the trees in that area where these moths used

01:33:22.840 --> 01:33:27.840
[Guest]: to perch, their bark was gradually getting blackened by soot, the trees and the branches

01:33:27.840 --> 01:33:29.440
[Guest]: of the tree.

01:33:29.440 --> 01:33:33.160
[Guest]: And so these moths, these black winged moths would sit on these trees and they would be

01:33:33.160 --> 01:33:36.760
[Guest]: camouflaged because they couldn't be seen by the birds that hunted them, they were black

01:33:36.760 --> 01:33:37.760
[Amit Varma]: on black.

01:33:37.760 --> 01:33:40.640
[Guest]: Earlier it was silvery bark so earlier it helped them anodize.

01:33:40.640 --> 01:33:45.000
[Guest]: And as the black darkened or blackened the silvery moths would stand out, they would

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:48.880
[Guest]: be easy prey for birds whereas the black moths wouldn't and so they would survive.

01:33:48.880 --> 01:33:52.880
[Guest]: But even then you know it wasn't sort of an established, nobody had confirmed this and

01:33:52.880 --> 01:33:58.600
[Guest]: the only way to confirm this was to prove in that short span of time natural selection

01:33:58.600 --> 01:34:05.080
[Guest]: could work on giving the silver moths a disadvantage and the black moths an advantage to the extent

01:34:05.080 --> 01:34:08.100
[Guest]: that they could almost completely replace the silver moth population.

01:34:08.100 --> 01:34:11.560
[Guest]: And this is what Haldane did, he took this data that was published over the years and

01:34:11.560 --> 01:34:16.200
[Guest]: he set up an equation by which he could figure out what coefficient of selective advantage

01:34:16.200 --> 01:34:18.920
[Guest]: was for black winged moths.

01:34:18.920 --> 01:34:22.640
[Guest]: And he proved that, you know, with these data sets he proved that this kind of selective

01:34:22.640 --> 01:34:27.220
[Guest]: advantage was indeed possible, natural selection could act in a short span of time so as to

01:34:27.220 --> 01:34:29.400
[Guest]: completely replace one population with another.

01:34:29.400 --> 01:34:33.960
[Guest]: And it was the first time anyone had done that kind of rigorous analysis of data on

01:34:33.960 --> 01:34:37.880
[Guest]: this moth population or indeed on any other biological population.

01:34:37.880 --> 01:34:42.520
[Guest]: And it was the first of a series of 10 papers that he would publish over the next 10 years

01:34:42.520 --> 01:34:47.360
[Guest]: in which he constantly refined and tweaked this model of selective advantage in various

01:34:47.360 --> 01:34:48.360
[Guest]: kind of settings.

01:34:48.360 --> 01:34:52.520
[Guest]: You know, he would examine what would happen if a population migrated elsewhere, what would

01:34:52.520 --> 01:34:57.160
[Guest]: happen if a plague struck a population, you know, all these kind of various permutations

01:34:57.160 --> 01:34:59.280
[Guest]: and combinations of situations.

01:34:59.280 --> 01:35:02.440
[Guest]: And he would figure out selective advantages in each of those and through an accretion

01:35:02.440 --> 01:35:07.080
[Guest]: of all of this he built up I think body of evidence to conclusively demonstrate the power

01:35:07.080 --> 01:35:08.560
[Guest]: of natural selection.

01:35:08.560 --> 01:35:12.760
[Guest]: And the fact that Darwin was right that Darwinism was not dead after all.

01:35:12.760 --> 01:35:16.720
[Amit Varma]: It's also such a great example of the seen in the unseen that you have chemical effluents

01:35:16.720 --> 01:35:21.960
[Amit Varma]: from a factory making the bark of trees dark and then within two or three human generations

01:35:21.960 --> 01:35:24.680
[Amit Varma]: all the moths change from silver wings to black wings.

01:35:24.680 --> 01:35:28.560
[Amit Varma]: It's fascinating and also so beautiful the way the whole sort of process works.

01:35:28.560 --> 01:35:32.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, Douglas Adams once said that he stopped believing in God when he understood

01:35:32.240 --> 01:35:36.660
[Amit Varma]: natural selection because the beauty and the awe that he felt when he really understood

01:35:36.660 --> 01:35:39.280
[Amit Varma]: it was, you know, God could not compare with that.

01:35:39.280 --> 01:35:44.840
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of, you know, all his scientific work is enormously kind of amusing, but then

01:35:44.840 --> 01:35:50.120
[Amit Varma]: we also, amazing rather, but then we also sort of come to where, you know, they shade

01:35:50.120 --> 01:35:56.520
[Amit Varma]: over into his political beliefs, how his political beliefs are almost shaped by his scientific

01:35:56.520 --> 01:35:57.520
[Amit Varma]: beliefs.

01:35:57.520 --> 01:36:02.140
[Amit Varma]: Can you talk a little bit about that and would you say it was kind of inevitable that attraction

01:36:02.140 --> 01:36:09.320
[Amit Varma]: to Marxism would happen given the dual propensity of him being that sort of man of science as

01:36:09.320 --> 01:36:14.720
[Amit Varma]: it were obsessed with how systems work and therefore, as Marx was being therefore drawn

01:36:14.720 --> 01:36:19.520
[Amit Varma]: to Darwin's theory for that reason, and also the sympathy that he would have felt for the

01:36:19.520 --> 01:36:24.600
[Amit Varma]: underclasses given that, you know, he had far more interactions with people from other

01:36:24.600 --> 01:36:27.040
[Amit Varma]: classes and others like him did.

01:36:27.040 --> 01:36:30.520
[Guest]: I think it's interesting how the art of biography works, which I've realized through this.

01:36:30.520 --> 01:36:35.480
[Guest]: I mean, in the sense that you look at another person looking at Haldane's life story might

01:36:35.480 --> 01:36:38.760
[Guest]: pick up completely different reasons for why he eventually became a socialist and then

01:36:38.760 --> 01:36:39.760
[Guest]: a communist.

01:36:39.760 --> 01:36:40.760
[Guest]: And I think it depends.

01:36:40.760 --> 01:36:45.880
[Guest]: This is where the subjectivity of the biographer comes in, which is, I, in my own life, I tend

01:36:45.880 --> 01:36:50.680
[Guest]: to place a lot of emphasis on what my childhood was like in order to explain who I am today.

01:36:50.680 --> 01:36:54.460
[Guest]: And it's just something that I have done, you know, everybody constructs their own origin

01:36:54.460 --> 01:36:57.400
[Guest]: stories for themselves, and this is possibly mine.

01:36:57.400 --> 01:37:01.240
[Guest]: And so therefore, when I came to Haldane's life, I sort of yielded to my proclivity and

01:37:01.240 --> 01:37:04.960
[Guest]: I just sort of also explained a lot of it, although not all of it, a lot of what he became

01:37:04.960 --> 01:37:06.580
[Guest]: later to his childhood.

01:37:06.580 --> 01:37:11.100
[Guest]: And so I explained it to the model that his father set up, which is the model of a scientist

01:37:11.100 --> 01:37:14.360
[Guest]: who believed that science had to be done for the benefit of the masses, a man who believed

01:37:14.360 --> 01:37:16.460
[Guest]: in a certain kind of equality in society.

01:37:16.460 --> 01:37:21.760
[Guest]: And so all that exposure that Haldane had at some point, in my view, helped a lot towards

01:37:21.760 --> 01:37:22.760
[Guest]: making him a socialist.

01:37:22.760 --> 01:37:26.400
[Guest]: Definitely, he was never a conservative of any kind, even though his uncle was a conservative

01:37:26.400 --> 01:37:27.400
[Guest]: politician.

01:37:27.400 --> 01:37:31.680
[Guest]: His own family and his father and himself never went into that side of the political

01:37:31.680 --> 01:37:32.680
[Guest]: spectrum at all.

01:37:32.680 --> 01:37:36.160
[Guest]: But then as he grew up, and as he continued to work in science, even though his own science

01:37:36.160 --> 01:37:41.480
[Guest]: was not in any way directly related to, you know, the practical matters of society in

01:37:41.480 --> 01:37:47.840
[Guest]: many aspects, you know, he always had in his mind, this link between science and society,

01:37:47.840 --> 01:37:51.520
[Guest]: the fact that science had to work for the upliftment of society more than anything else.

01:37:51.520 --> 01:37:53.440
[Guest]: That was the noblest thing science could do.

01:37:53.440 --> 01:37:57.520
[Guest]: And so when the Russian Revolution happened in a couple of decades thereafter, as the

01:37:57.520 --> 01:38:02.280
[Guest]: Soviet Union paid, at first, real attention to science, and then after that, lip service,

01:38:02.280 --> 01:38:03.960
[Guest]: obviously, and not anything else.

01:38:03.960 --> 01:38:09.960
[Guest]: But as they continued to champion this model of a scientifically built egalitarian society,

01:38:09.960 --> 01:38:13.800
[Guest]: it was inevitable that he would, you know, fall for the attraction of that.

01:38:13.800 --> 01:38:18.240
[Guest]: He went to the Soviet Union once with his wife in 1928.

01:38:18.240 --> 01:38:22.840
[Guest]: And while his wife came away with decidedly mixed views about how well the Soviet Union

01:38:22.840 --> 01:38:25.640
[Guest]: was succeeding, he came away completely captivated.

01:38:25.640 --> 01:38:31.680
[Guest]: He genuinely saw, you know, or thought he saw an enormous amount of funding and attention

01:38:31.680 --> 01:38:36.360
[Guest]: being paid by the government to science and scientists and scientific institutions.

01:38:36.360 --> 01:38:40.980
[Guest]: It was something that was always sort of a quibble for him in England itself.

01:38:40.980 --> 01:38:45.560
[Guest]: He thought capitalist societies were inevitably organized around what corporations want and

01:38:45.560 --> 01:38:47.260
[Guest]: not what the people want.

01:38:47.260 --> 01:38:51.760
[Guest]: And so therefore, governments would do what interests wanted them to do.

01:38:51.760 --> 01:38:53.720
[Guest]: This was a view that his father also held.

01:38:53.720 --> 01:38:58.120
[Guest]: And he, you know, again, multiple times through the course of his early career, he had seen

01:38:58.120 --> 01:39:03.920
[Guest]: that politicians in England frequently disregarded the advice of scientists, much to the, and

01:39:03.920 --> 01:39:05.960
[Guest]: they never bore the brunt of that ignorance.

01:39:05.960 --> 01:39:08.760
[Guest]: In fact, the people who bore the brunt of that ignorance were the regular people.

01:39:08.760 --> 01:39:13.520
[Guest]: So for example, if his father designed a particular kind of gas mask to protect against chlorine

01:39:13.520 --> 01:39:18.380
[Guest]: gas attacks in the First World War, the government and its civil servants would substitute one

01:39:18.380 --> 01:39:22.160
[Guest]: ingredient for another, make the mask less effective than it should have been.

01:39:22.160 --> 01:39:26.720
[Guest]: And, you know, the people who bore the brunt of that were the soldiers in the trenches,

01:39:26.720 --> 01:39:31.080
[Guest]: working class men quite often, who would be saddled with these non-functional masks and

01:39:31.080 --> 01:39:32.080
[Guest]: would die as a result.

01:39:32.080 --> 01:39:33.800
[Guest]: And he saw this time and time again.

01:39:33.800 --> 01:39:38.120
[Guest]: I mean, he would see politicians be rewarded for scientific advances that had been made

01:39:38.120 --> 01:39:39.120
[Guest]: by scientists.

01:39:39.120 --> 01:39:43.200
[Guest]: And I think all of this disillusioned him quite a bit about the way that Western capitalist

01:39:43.200 --> 01:39:48.640
[Guest]: societies were set up at the time and drove him more and more to the left of the political

01:39:48.640 --> 01:39:49.640
[Amit Varma]: spectrum.

01:39:49.640 --> 01:39:56.000
[Amit Varma]: I was always found it curious that, you know, Marxists saw Darwinism as a validation of

01:39:56.000 --> 01:40:01.600
[Amit Varma]: or a natural sort of extension of what they believed in, because, you know, I did an episode

01:40:01.600 --> 01:40:05.360
[Amit Varma]: with Matt Ridley a couple of years back called the evolution of everything, you know, based

01:40:05.360 --> 01:40:11.640
[Amit Varma]: on a book he had written, where he pointed out that common force between a natural selection

01:40:11.640 --> 01:40:15.960
[Amit Varma]: itself and the way languages develop and the way markets work is basically that it is a

01:40:15.960 --> 01:40:21.860
[Amit Varma]: kind of emergent order, that there isn't a grand planner, there isn't a grand designer,

01:40:21.860 --> 01:40:25.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, I mean, the whole intelligent design argument, which came from William Paley was

01:40:25.760 --> 01:40:29.040
[Amit Varma]: that, look, this is so complex and beautiful, someone must have designed it.

01:40:29.040 --> 01:40:33.280
[Amit Varma]: And the genius of Darwin and those who followed him like Haldane was to point out that no,

01:40:33.280 --> 01:40:38.720
[Amit Varma]: you don't need a designer, this stuff happens on its own, which is so counterintuitive.

01:40:38.720 --> 01:40:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and that would lead you not to therefore, believe in things like central

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:46.880
[Amit Varma]: planning or that you can design a society.

01:40:46.880 --> 01:40:50.760
[Amit Varma]: And I think, you know, when I read about Haldane, I thought he kind of fit the description of

01:40:50.760 --> 01:40:52.840
[Amit Varma]: what Adam Smith would have called the man of system.

01:40:52.840 --> 01:40:58.080
[Amit Varma]: I'll just sort of read out what Smith's, how Smith defined that, where writing in the theory

01:40:58.080 --> 01:41:03.240
[Amit Varma]: of moral sentiments, Smith wrote, quote, the man of system is apt to be very wise in his

01:41:03.240 --> 01:41:08.320
[Amit Varma]: own conceit, and is often so enamored with the supposed beauty of his ideal plan of government

01:41:08.320 --> 01:41:11.440
[Amit Varma]: that he cannot suffer the smallest deviation from any part of it.

01:41:11.440 --> 01:41:15.120
[Amit Varma]: He goes on to establish it completely and in all its parts without any regard either

01:41:15.120 --> 01:41:18.960
[Amit Varma]: to the great interests or to the strong prejudices which may oppose it.

01:41:18.960 --> 01:41:23.840
[Amit Varma]: He seems to imagine that he can arrange the different members of a great society with

01:41:23.840 --> 01:41:28.460
[Amit Varma]: as much ease as a hand arranges the different pieces upon a chessboard.

01:41:28.460 --> 01:41:31.960
[Amit Varma]: He does not consider that the pieces upon the chessboard have no other principle of

01:41:31.960 --> 01:41:37.000
[Amit Varma]: motion besides that which the hand impresses upon them, but that in the great chessboard

01:41:37.000 --> 01:41:41.760
[Amit Varma]: of human society, every single piece has a principle of motion of its own, altogether

01:41:41.760 --> 01:41:46.400
[Amit Varma]: different from that which the legislature might choose to impress upon it, stop quote.

01:41:46.400 --> 01:41:51.880
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that one in this sense that Haldane and so many others in that era, you

01:41:51.880 --> 01:41:56.760
[Amit Varma]: know, we've also spoken about how eugenics held so much sway over both the left and the

01:41:56.760 --> 01:41:59.960
[Amit Varma]: right and was almost common wisdom in a sense.

01:41:59.960 --> 01:42:04.520
[Amit Varma]: And how so much of that seems to come from the belief that, you know, when scientists

01:42:04.520 --> 01:42:08.880
[Amit Varma]: realize the power of their tools and there is no denying that they're incredibly powerful,

01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:13.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, the things that Haldane could prove with algebra and sort of the advances in knowledge

01:42:13.040 --> 01:42:18.040
[Amit Varma]: he could make, it's easy to get carried away with that sense of power and then be arrogant

01:42:18.040 --> 01:42:22.200
[Amit Varma]: enough to assume that it applies to society.

01:42:22.200 --> 01:42:26.200
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you know, a classic illustration of that which you've given in that excellent

01:42:26.200 --> 01:42:30.360
[Amit Varma]: first chapter in your book was, of course, the Soviet scientist Lysenko, you know, got

01:42:30.360 --> 01:42:31.360
[Amit Varma]: carried away by this.

01:42:31.360 --> 01:42:35.480
[Amit Varma]: And Lysenko, of course, was a shitty scientist, Haldane was a great scientist.

01:42:35.480 --> 01:42:41.800
[Amit Varma]: But what it seems to me is that he is applying a certain kind of rigor to his science, but

01:42:41.800 --> 01:42:47.480
[Amit Varma]: not a similar rigor to his politics, which we again see later in his defense of Lysenko,

01:42:47.480 --> 01:42:48.560
[Amit Varma]: for example.

01:42:48.560 --> 01:42:50.760
[Amit Varma]: What is sort of your sense of all this?

01:42:50.760 --> 01:42:56.240
[Amit Varma]: And is that a danger that, say, men of system, scientists or people who are, you know, very

01:42:56.240 --> 01:43:00.440
[Amit Varma]: accomplished that, you know, it could be science, it could be managerial work, like there is

01:43:00.440 --> 01:43:05.400
[Amit Varma]: this notion that if you're the CEO of a company, you can run a country as well, which is another

01:43:05.400 --> 01:43:09.880
[Amit Varma]: mistaken notion people seem to have, as if there is any remote comparison between the

01:43:09.880 --> 01:43:10.880
[Amit Varma]: complexities involved.

01:43:10.880 --> 01:43:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Do you think that this was sort of Haldane's kind of fatal mistake?

01:43:16.120 --> 01:43:20.840
[Amit Varma]: And not just his, but I think a lot of Marxists embraced Darwinism, right?

01:43:20.840 --> 01:43:22.560
[Guest]: Because as you point out in your book.

01:43:22.560 --> 01:43:23.560
[Guest]: Yeah, okay.

01:43:23.560 --> 01:43:24.560
[Guest]: Well, there's so many layers to this.

01:43:24.560 --> 01:43:26.200
[Guest]: So let me like, let me unpack some of them.

01:43:26.200 --> 01:43:30.520
[Guest]: I mean, a couple of things that I thought about while you were talking about this mystery

01:43:30.520 --> 01:43:35.720
[Guest]: as to why Marxists and Darwinists at the time seem to find common cause.

01:43:35.720 --> 01:43:40.240
[Guest]: One is, I think that in the 19th century, these were both challenges to the established

01:43:40.240 --> 01:43:41.240
[Guest]: order.

01:43:41.240 --> 01:43:44.200
[Guest]: I think Marxism was obviously a challenge to the way that markets were structured.

01:43:44.200 --> 01:43:46.680
[Guest]: And Darwinism was a challenge to the church.

01:43:46.680 --> 01:43:52.480
[Guest]: It was sort of a refutation of any principle of God or the Godhead in any way.

01:43:52.480 --> 01:43:57.680
[Guest]: And I think as many, as to happen quite often, differences were papered over just because

01:43:57.680 --> 01:44:01.800
[Guest]: these two were allied at the time, sort of quite radical causes.

01:44:01.800 --> 01:44:07.480
[Guest]: The second also was, I think both, I mean, Marxists and Darwinists, both, I think might

01:44:07.480 --> 01:44:11.680
[Guest]: have been seen to believe in what might be called the theory of bottom-up change.

01:44:11.680 --> 01:44:16.320
[Guest]: That basically that you, that organizing happens from the bottom, you know, animals change,

01:44:16.320 --> 01:44:22.960
[Guest]: well, species evolve because first there was one unit or one individual mutant or variant

01:44:22.960 --> 01:44:26.760
[Guest]: that emerged that then proved to be more, you know, so there are these broader principles

01:44:26.760 --> 01:44:29.200
[Guest]: that operate, but the change happens at the bottom.

01:44:29.200 --> 01:44:33.600
[Guest]: And I think the idea of Marxism as a kind of revolution that begins from the bottom

01:44:33.600 --> 01:44:37.560
[Guest]: through the agglomeration of people and how to change their material well-being in order

01:44:37.560 --> 01:44:41.320
[Guest]: to then change society, I think, again, there's a similarity over there.

01:44:41.320 --> 01:44:45.960
[Guest]: But the interesting thing, and maybe the point where maybe we can choose to part ways here

01:44:45.960 --> 01:44:53.080
[Guest]: is that I think everybody who approaches politics underplays the emotional reasons or the irrational

01:44:53.080 --> 01:44:59.960
[Guest]: reasons for which they are drawn to a particular political ideology and overplays the rational

01:44:59.960 --> 01:45:01.760
[Guest]: reasons that they are drawn to it.

01:45:01.760 --> 01:45:05.960
[Guest]: Certainly Haldane and other Marxists of his time, examples, you know, Haldane, as I point

01:45:05.960 --> 01:45:09.480
[Guest]: out in my book, I mean, a lot of the reason that he was driven to the left was because

01:45:09.480 --> 01:45:13.260
[Guest]: of the circumstances in which he grew up, the kind of things that he saw that left an

01:45:13.260 --> 01:45:18.200
[Guest]: impression on him and that directed both his work and his political ideology.

01:45:18.200 --> 01:45:23.760
[Guest]: But equally, I think, are people who tend to believe that economics is an exact science

01:45:23.760 --> 01:45:27.600
[Guest]: and that they have figured out that there is an exactitude, there's a precise way in

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:32.400
[Guest]: which a market can work for the best benefit of society and approach it from there and

01:45:32.400 --> 01:45:36.040
[Guest]: insist that they are being rational when they're doing it, that there is no tug of emotion

01:45:36.040 --> 01:45:41.920
[Guest]: or sentiment or irrationality or even sometimes blind belief in the way in which this works.

01:45:41.920 --> 01:45:46.400
[Guest]: I think you could say it for people on every part of the political spectrum and not just

01:45:46.400 --> 01:45:48.600
[Guest]: for Marxists alone.

01:45:48.600 --> 01:45:52.760
[Guest]: Of course, there is a completely valid argument to be made about how Haldane and other Marxists

01:45:52.760 --> 01:45:57.760
[Guest]: and communists should not have been blind to the perversions of science that were happening

01:45:57.760 --> 01:45:58.760
[Guest]: in the Soviet Union at the time.

01:45:58.760 --> 01:46:04.240
[Guest]: In fact, this is a point I make in the opening chapter and certainly Haldane's insistence

01:46:04.240 --> 01:46:10.040
[Guest]: on defending Stalin even into the 1950s when the extent of his show trials and his purges

01:46:10.040 --> 01:46:13.560
[Guest]: were starting to become quite well known, I mean that was completely mystifying and

01:46:13.560 --> 01:46:20.240
[Guest]: I can only ascribe that to Haldane's stubbornness which is demonstrated in many other forms.

01:46:20.240 --> 01:46:25.800
[Guest]: So you're completely right, he didn't bring to his politics the nimbleness and flexibility

01:46:25.800 --> 01:46:29.920
[Guest]: and willingness to change his mind that marked his scientific work.

01:46:29.920 --> 01:46:36.000
[Guest]: But I think that is the nature of most people who approach politics in any part of the political

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:37.000
[Amit Varma]: spectrum.

01:46:37.000 --> 01:46:42.220
[Amit Varma]: A bunch of things to unpack here, one that's a great insight that you shared that we often

01:46:42.220 --> 01:46:47.280
[Amit Varma]: underplay the emotional reasons and overplay the rational reasons and I would completely

01:46:47.280 --> 01:46:51.960
[Amit Varma]: agree with Haldane and I think that there was, that society was broken, that government

01:46:51.960 --> 01:46:57.040
[Amit Varma]: was in the sway of private interests which kind of remains the case today so one can

01:46:57.040 --> 01:46:59.120
[Amit Varma]: sort of understand that attraction.

01:46:59.120 --> 01:47:03.320
[Amit Varma]: That said, I think, and he could not have known that at this time, but while in terms

01:47:03.320 --> 01:47:07.960
[Amit Varma]: of science, his rigor was spot on and he was obviously one of the great geniuses of the

01:47:07.960 --> 01:47:08.960
[Amit Varma]: time.

01:47:08.960 --> 01:47:12.560
[Amit Varma]: He didn't understand the principles of economics, for example, like you've referred to, I'll

01:47:12.560 --> 01:47:17.840
[Amit Varma]: quote from your book, in 1932 he released a science fiction story, The Goldmakers, an

01:47:17.840 --> 01:47:22.720
[Amit Varma]: approximation of a Wellsian yarn in which a new technique to distill gold out of seawater

01:47:22.720 --> 01:47:25.400
[Amit Varma]: threatens to disrupt the world's mining concerns.

01:47:25.400 --> 01:47:30.200
[Amit Varma]: The inventor plans to use his profits to start endowing science as it should be endowed,

01:47:30.200 --> 01:47:34.400
[Amit Varma]: a pet cause for Haldane, although in the tale he doesn't recognize how these profits will

01:47:34.400 --> 01:47:39.160
[Amit Varma]: plummet if the markets are suddenly flooded with fresh gold, stop quote.

01:47:39.160 --> 01:47:43.000
[Amit Varma]: But leaving that aside, the other thing that I'd kind of taken issue with is that yeah,

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:47.000
[Amit Varma]: in Marxism, in theory, they might talk of it being bottom up, but in practice, it can

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:49.320
[Amit Varma]: only be achieved through top-down coercion.

01:47:49.320 --> 01:47:54.960
[Amit Varma]: And that is something that, you know, Haldane also seemed to have turned a blind eye to,

01:47:54.960 --> 01:47:59.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, the moral question of do the means justify the end, for example, in 1928, when

01:47:59.720 --> 01:48:04.040
[Amit Varma]: he met one of the scientists who hosted him and showed him great hospitality was Nikolai

01:48:04.040 --> 01:48:06.160
[Amit Varma]: Vavilov, I think his name was.

01:48:06.160 --> 01:48:10.800
[Amit Varma]: And then later Vavilov was arrested because, you know, Lysenko didn't like him.

01:48:10.800 --> 01:48:15.800
[Amit Varma]: And he was murdered in 1942, essentially, he was imprisoned and then he died in prison.

01:48:15.800 --> 01:48:19.800
[Amit Varma]: And that is something that, you know, Haldane completely shaded over when he was asked to

01:48:19.800 --> 01:48:23.720
[Amit Varma]: comment on, for example, you know, the many political prisoners and many scientists, you

01:48:23.720 --> 01:48:28.280
[Amit Varma]: point out in the book about how at one point in an essay or a piece that he's writing,

01:48:28.280 --> 01:48:31.880
[Amit Varma]: he mentions that a couple of scientists were no longer in their positions.

01:48:31.880 --> 01:48:36.240
[Amit Varma]: But then later on, he sort of says, oh, they didn't do any important work anyway.

01:48:36.240 --> 01:48:40.700
[Amit Varma]: And you see these sort of this kind of finessing happening, where, you know, again, it seems

01:48:40.700 --> 01:48:48.340
[Amit Varma]: to me to be, in that sense, a wonderful study of how his character also is corroded by this

01:48:48.340 --> 01:48:53.100
[Amit Varma]: political affiliation and this ideology to the extent that where there is a clear choice

01:48:53.100 --> 01:48:58.080
[Amit Varma]: to be made between his science and his politics, that is when Lysenko basically says there

01:48:58.080 --> 01:49:03.160
[Amit Varma]: is no such thing as a gene and, you know, goes into that Lamarckianism that, you know,

01:49:03.160 --> 01:49:06.040
[Amit Varma]: that qualities we acquire during a lifetime can be inherited.

01:49:06.040 --> 01:49:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, when it is completely clear that the science is on one side, and these

01:49:09.380 --> 01:49:13.100
[Amit Varma]: guys are on the other side, he sticks with these guys, because he's a card carrying member

01:49:13.100 --> 01:49:18.200
[Amit Varma]: of the Communist Party, and he feels that for the larger cause, he must.

01:49:18.200 --> 01:49:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And this was incredibly fascinating to me.

01:49:20.600 --> 01:49:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And you've pointed out in an interview somewhere that you sort of see this as the exception,

01:49:25.560 --> 01:49:30.880
[Amit Varma]: the one weak moment, the defense of Lysenko, but to my eyes, and just judging from I haven't

01:49:30.880 --> 01:49:34.800
[Amit Varma]: read anything else on him except your remarkable book, and there are enough details on that.

01:49:34.800 --> 01:49:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And my sense from that was that this was sort of a pattern, like even in 1928, when he went,

01:49:39.880 --> 01:49:44.640
[Amit Varma]: the squalor was there, it's just that he fell for the confirmation bias and chose to completely

01:49:44.640 --> 01:49:47.880
[Amit Varma]: ignore it while his wife, you know, noticed some of it.

01:49:47.880 --> 01:49:52.840
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me, and it's almost a very tragic human story in that sense, where he

01:49:52.840 --> 01:49:57.320
[Amit Varma]: is letting his politics, and this brings me to sort of, or I'll ask you to, I'll get to

01:49:57.320 --> 01:50:00.120
[Amit Varma]: my question later, I'll ask you to, you know, comment on this.

01:50:00.120 --> 01:50:04.040
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, his one fatal mistake, I think was, as you quite rightly point out, was the

01:50:04.040 --> 01:50:08.680
[Guest]: defense of Lysenko, and by extension, the defense of the Soviet Union at a time when

01:50:08.680 --> 01:50:13.280
[Guest]: many of its policies could not bear defending, and the fact that he did this in itself sort

01:50:13.280 --> 01:50:14.620
[Guest]: of instructive.

01:50:14.620 --> 01:50:16.040
[Guest]: But let me point out a couple of things.

01:50:16.040 --> 01:50:21.880
[Guest]: First is that as a scientist, to be a scientist in the 1910s and the 1920s, and to look to

01:50:21.880 --> 01:50:28.400
[Guest]: a regime which promised to bring the benefits of science to the masses, to promise a whole

01:50:28.400 --> 01:50:34.040
[Guest]: new political system, I mean, we have to look at this from the point of view, not of people

01:50:34.040 --> 01:50:38.320
[Guest]: who are living in the 21st century, and you've seen what happened in the 1980s and 90s, with

01:50:38.320 --> 01:50:42.120
[Guest]: the collapse of communism, but as people living in the 1910s and 20s, who are seeing a whole

01:50:42.120 --> 01:50:47.080
[Guest]: new alternative system of government and society spring up somewhere in one of the great nations

01:50:47.080 --> 01:50:52.800
[Guest]: of the world, and the promise that science will be used to equalize people, and all investment

01:50:52.800 --> 01:50:58.640
[Guest]: in science will be used to improve livelihoods, to improve agricultural practices, for example,

01:50:58.640 --> 01:51:03.640
[Guest]: I mean, this must have been an immense lure, to the extent that it fooled somebody like

01:51:03.640 --> 01:51:05.680
[Guest]: Haldane who went there in 1928.

01:51:05.680 --> 01:51:10.400
[Guest]: And even in 1928, you know, as we know from the chronology of events, the show trials

01:51:10.400 --> 01:51:15.080
[Guest]: had only just about begun, they were, you know, often inaccessible to people who didn't

01:51:15.080 --> 01:51:16.660
[Guest]: probably speak Russian.

01:51:16.660 --> 01:51:20.280
[Guest]: So to see squalor around you is one thing, and you'd think that maybe it is only the

01:51:20.280 --> 01:51:24.320
[Guest]: effect of the new Soviet regime not having been in power long enough, and that eventually

01:51:24.320 --> 01:51:25.880
[Guest]: the squalor will disappear.

01:51:25.880 --> 01:51:30.200
[Guest]: But to gauge perversions of power that was starting to happen at that time already was

01:51:30.200 --> 01:51:34.320
[Guest]: another thing altogether that I think would have been invisible to Haldane quite naturally

01:51:34.320 --> 01:51:39.000
[Guest]: as somebody who didn't speak Russian, whose entire visit was possibly curated by Vavilov

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:40.560
[Guest]: and other people from the Soviet state.

01:51:40.560 --> 01:51:45.520
[Guest]: I won't accuse him of blindness at that point, so much as just an inability to access a lot

01:51:45.520 --> 01:51:47.080
[Guest]: of what was happening around him.

01:51:47.080 --> 01:51:51.840
[Guest]: As things progressed, I think in the 1930s, this is very much a human factor, as you rightly

01:51:51.840 --> 01:51:56.160
[Guest]: point out, a human frailty, which is that as you wed yourself more and more to a political

01:51:56.160 --> 01:51:58.920
[Guest]: cause, you dig yourself in more and more.

01:51:58.920 --> 01:52:02.560
[Guest]: You are unwilling to make radical changes in your political judgment.

01:52:02.560 --> 01:52:04.480
[Guest]: And this is something we see all the time today.

01:52:04.480 --> 01:52:07.640
[Guest]: And so it's particularly instructive to read of Haldane's experience with this.

01:52:07.640 --> 01:52:13.760
[Guest]: My big curiosity about the Lysenko affair was whether he genuinely believed either that

01:52:13.760 --> 01:52:17.040
[Guest]: what Lysenko was doing, was saying was accurate.

01:52:17.040 --> 01:52:22.280
[Guest]: It couldn't have been, because then that meant he was negating his own decades worth of work.

01:52:22.280 --> 01:52:26.480
[Guest]: So then did he believe that this was all sort of permissible, that a few lives lost and

01:52:26.480 --> 01:52:31.040
[Guest]: a few scientists imprisoned was permissible for the larger cause?

01:52:31.040 --> 01:52:35.160
[Guest]: And the third thing I wonder is, did he ever stand up within the Communist Party itself

01:52:35.160 --> 01:52:37.440
[Guest]: for some of the principles that he believed in?

01:52:37.440 --> 01:52:40.640
[Guest]: It was the third thing that intrigued me the most, because nobody had written about this.

01:52:40.640 --> 01:52:44.640
[Guest]: Either nobody had analyzed his papers and his documents deeply enough or hadn't read

01:52:44.640 --> 01:52:45.640
[Guest]: them.

01:52:45.640 --> 01:52:48.840
[Guest]: It felt to me to kind of look through his correspondences with other members of the

01:52:48.840 --> 01:52:53.200
[Guest]: British Communist Party at the time, the memoranda he circulated within the party.

01:52:53.200 --> 01:52:58.560
[Guest]: And the thing I found that is he criticized the Soviet Union and Lysenko and Soviet science

01:52:58.560 --> 01:53:00.520
[Guest]: extensively within the party itself.

01:53:00.520 --> 01:53:05.040
[Guest]: So what he clearly thought was that he was best serving the cause of both science and

01:53:05.040 --> 01:53:09.360
[Guest]: society if he restricted his criticisms to that close group.

01:53:09.360 --> 01:53:14.120
[Guest]: If he tried to effect the change from within, rather than seeming to abandon the party in

01:53:14.120 --> 01:53:15.120
[Guest]: the public eye.

01:53:15.120 --> 01:53:19.640
[Guest]: And I think this is a choice that many of us very often are called upon to make even

01:53:19.640 --> 01:53:20.640
[Guest]: today.

01:53:20.640 --> 01:53:23.640
[Guest]: You know, we all have entrenched political beliefs in one way or another.

01:53:23.640 --> 01:53:27.280
[Guest]: We are all painfully aware, at least those of us who think about this seriously, we are

01:53:27.280 --> 01:53:33.120
[Guest]: all painfully aware that these political positions are limiting in and of themselves.

01:53:33.120 --> 01:53:38.440
[Guest]: Very often they are tied to the fortunes of one party and every party is fickle and flawed

01:53:38.440 --> 01:53:43.440
[Guest]: and we have to stand up for that party or that cause even while ignoring its hypocrisies

01:53:43.440 --> 01:53:44.920
[Guest]: or its flaws.

01:53:44.920 --> 01:53:48.320
[Guest]: It is particularly true in a two-party system like the US.

01:53:48.320 --> 01:53:51.600
[Guest]: It is even true in a multi-party system like India.

01:53:51.600 --> 01:53:56.920
[Guest]: And my point and the reason I wanted to explain this Haldane episode in depth, this Lysenko

01:53:56.920 --> 01:54:02.400
[Guest]: episode in depth, was to illustrate that this happened even to people who purported to approach

01:54:02.400 --> 01:54:03.800
[Amit Varma]: all of this with a scientific point.

01:54:03.800 --> 01:54:07.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I found it very interesting and relatable.

01:54:07.240 --> 01:54:11.400
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and it's another theme that you sort of pick upon is you talk about how

01:54:11.400 --> 01:54:15.720
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, Haldane, of course, was a prolific public intellectual, wrote a lot

01:54:15.720 --> 01:54:16.720
[Amit Varma]: which we'll talk about.

01:54:16.720 --> 01:54:22.560
[Amit Varma]: But one of the themes that you pick upon is how there was that sort of space where scientists

01:54:22.560 --> 01:54:24.720
[Amit Varma]: were speaking out in politics.

01:54:24.720 --> 01:54:27.840
[Amit Varma]: You refer to the book, The Visible College, and you've spoken about the, you know, the

01:54:27.840 --> 01:54:32.920
[Amit Varma]: five guys at Cambridge who were, you know, prominent scientists and people who were speaking

01:54:32.920 --> 01:54:33.920
[Amit Varma]: out politically.

01:54:33.920 --> 01:54:38.520
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, one of them, Banal, wrote a book called The Social Function of Science.

01:54:38.520 --> 01:54:43.120
[Amit Varma]: And then you lament that it went off over the decades as scientists got into an ivory

01:54:43.120 --> 01:54:44.680
[Amit Varma]: tower and so on.

01:54:44.680 --> 01:54:49.040
[Amit Varma]: And then in the end, in a hopeful note, you said that, okay, they are now gradually coming

01:54:49.040 --> 01:54:50.040
[Amit Varma]: back.

01:54:50.040 --> 01:54:54.520
[Amit Varma]: And I had sort of two opposite reactions to this.

01:54:54.520 --> 01:54:59.680
[Amit Varma]: One reaction was that we need more of the scientific viewpoint in politics, because

01:54:59.680 --> 01:55:04.800
[Amit Varma]: otherwise politics, you know, they build their own narratives, which need to be countered

01:55:04.800 --> 01:55:05.800
[Amit Varma]: with good science.

01:55:05.800 --> 01:55:08.080
[Amit Varma]: So there, I completely agree with you.

01:55:08.080 --> 01:55:11.680
[Amit Varma]: But the point that I'm conflicted about is that while I would like to see more science

01:55:11.680 --> 01:55:16.520
[Amit Varma]: in politics, I'm not sure I would like to see more politics in science.

01:55:16.520 --> 01:55:20.880
[Amit Varma]: Because what happens today, and this is something that is, you know, I think a crisis on both

01:55:20.880 --> 01:55:26.880
[Amit Varma]: the right and the left, is that politics impinges upon science in a way that in some particular

01:55:26.880 --> 01:55:31.600
[Amit Varma]: context, there is a chilling effect upon scientists, for example, there was a recent debate on,

01:55:31.600 --> 01:55:35.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, involving JK Rowling about whether biological sex is real or not.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:39.240
[Amit Varma]: My point is not to take a stance on that, but my point is to say that this is something

01:55:39.240 --> 01:55:42.280
[Amit Varma]: that scientists should be able to debate and discuss.

01:55:42.280 --> 01:55:46.640
[Amit Varma]: But it seems to me that today, it's just one of those subjects which has been put out of

01:55:46.640 --> 01:55:47.640
[Amit Varma]: bounds.

01:55:47.640 --> 01:55:49.880
[Amit Varma]: You cannot debate and discuss it anymore.

01:55:49.880 --> 01:55:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you take a particular position on it, you could lose your job or you could, you

01:55:54.000 --> 01:55:57.360
[Amit Varma]: know, not get hired by the university you were applying to.

01:55:57.360 --> 01:55:58.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is just one example.

01:55:58.360 --> 01:56:01.400
[Amit Varma]: And again, I'm not taking a position on this one way or the other.

01:56:01.400 --> 01:56:04.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there's even been a similar chilling effect, for example, when you talk

01:56:04.600 --> 01:56:07.320
[Amit Varma]: about something like inheritable differences.

01:56:07.320 --> 01:56:12.960
[Amit Varma]: And there again, you see sort of perhaps an overreaction to an earlier politics, where

01:56:12.960 --> 01:56:17.920
[Amit Varma]: a particular kind of science, the science of inherited differences was used to justify

01:56:17.920 --> 01:56:22.640
[Amit Varma]: horribly coercive state action in eugenics, which we've seen, which is one of the big

01:56:22.640 --> 01:56:24.080
[Amit Varma]: lessons we've learned.

01:56:24.080 --> 01:56:28.120
[Amit Varma]: But regardless of that, you know, when it is prescriptive and is used in a particular

01:56:28.120 --> 01:56:30.400
[Amit Varma]: kind of politics, yes, it's a problem.

01:56:30.400 --> 01:56:34.600
[Amit Varma]: But when it's descriptive, and you just have scientists exploring different subjects, why

01:56:34.600 --> 01:56:36.440
[Amit Varma]: should you stop studying it?

01:56:36.440 --> 01:56:40.640
[Amit Varma]: So my point here is, again, not to take a stand on any of these issues, but say, but

01:56:40.640 --> 01:56:44.880
[Amit Varma]: just point out that the scientific temperament, as I think even Haldane would have agreed,

01:56:44.880 --> 01:56:50.100
[Amit Varma]: is that you study all sides, and you let that openness remain where anybody is free to study

01:56:50.100 --> 01:56:51.100
[Amit Varma]: anything.

01:56:51.100 --> 01:56:56.880
[Amit Varma]: And yet today, we have politics impinging upon science, where some areas of potential

01:56:56.880 --> 01:57:00.360
[Amit Varma]: study are just out of bounds because of political reasons.

01:57:00.360 --> 01:57:01.360
[Amit Varma]: What's your reaction?

01:57:01.360 --> 01:57:07.520
[Guest]: I mean, what Haldane's argument and what his experience was, is that politics has never

01:57:07.520 --> 01:57:13.440
[Guest]: ever stopped being a part of science, and it is sort of a fool's errand to believe otherwise.

01:57:13.440 --> 01:57:17.520
[Guest]: And it's exemplified so beautifully during the course of Haldane's own life, which is

01:57:17.520 --> 01:57:24.960
[Guest]: that as soon as genetics became a thing, as soon as a very first decade of the 20th century,

01:57:24.960 --> 01:57:27.800
[Guest]: as soon as people thought about evolution and the fact that there were genes and there

01:57:27.800 --> 01:57:32.920
[Guest]: is such a thing as fitness, immediately they started to apply it to races, to the extent

01:57:32.920 --> 01:57:37.600
[Guest]: that the British government, which had suffered terribly in the Boer War in the late 1800s

01:57:37.600 --> 01:57:41.880
[Guest]: and 1900s, they started to think about the fitness of their population.

01:57:41.880 --> 01:57:46.800
[Guest]: I write extensively in this book about this campaign of sterilization in the US to weed

01:57:46.800 --> 01:57:51.720
[Guest]: the fit people out of society, of sort of sequestering people here in the UK to make

01:57:51.720 --> 01:57:56.680
[Guest]: sure they don't breed and produce further quote-unquote unfit people.

01:57:56.680 --> 01:58:00.840
[Guest]: So this has been a part of science since time immemorial.

01:58:00.840 --> 01:58:04.400
[Guest]: The things that we talked about here that you mentioned, which are enormously interesting,

01:58:04.400 --> 01:58:09.560
[Guest]: which is somebody like JK Rowling sort of talking about biological sex, for example,

01:58:09.560 --> 01:58:14.920
[Guest]: Haldane wouldn't quite characterize that as, I guess, a scientist's ability or inability

01:58:14.920 --> 01:58:17.200
[Guest]: to work on the intricacies of biological sex.

01:58:17.200 --> 01:58:21.000
[Guest]: I don't actually know, I haven't looked into this in any detail, whether funding has been

01:58:21.000 --> 01:58:26.600
[Guest]: granted, not granted, publication status has been granted, not granted, to papers based

01:58:26.600 --> 01:58:30.880
[Guest]: on political views, but certainly the pressures are immense and the pressures have always

01:58:30.880 --> 01:58:31.880
[Guest]: been there.

01:58:31.880 --> 01:58:36.040
[Guest]: One of the things, you know, we talked earlier about how the Lysenko episode was this regrettable

01:58:36.040 --> 01:58:40.520
[Guest]: one-off in Haldane's career and what I meant to add on to that is also relevant here, which

01:58:40.520 --> 01:58:46.280
[Guest]: is that Haldane's scientific approach to things in so many other cases led him into exactly

01:58:46.280 --> 01:58:47.280
[Guest]: the right direction.

01:58:47.280 --> 01:58:51.920
[Guest]: You know, Haldane grew up as a child of the 19th century, early 20th century, and he was

01:58:51.920 --> 01:58:57.800
[Guest]: saddled initially with a lot of the racist biases that belong to Englishmen of his generation.

01:58:57.800 --> 01:59:02.440
[Guest]: He grew to outgrew that because he did more and more science, understood more and more

01:59:02.440 --> 01:59:05.500
[Guest]: about how human populations and genes work.

01:59:05.500 --> 01:59:10.440
[Guest]: It led him to take an extremely vociferous stance against fascist notions of what science

01:59:10.440 --> 01:59:15.240
[Guest]: and racial purity were, to the extent that he put himself in harm's way when he went

01:59:15.240 --> 01:59:20.640
[Guest]: to Spain during the Civil War to help in whatever way he could on the front to fight the fascists.

01:59:20.640 --> 01:59:23.960
[Guest]: I mean, he was that committed to an anti-fascist stance.

01:59:23.960 --> 01:59:28.680
[Guest]: So you know, in many of these cases, scientists speaking up and having the weight of scientific

01:59:28.680 --> 01:59:34.600
[Guest]: experience behind them, I think has inevitably enriched public debate and it has definitely

01:59:34.600 --> 01:59:40.480
[Guest]: very often stood up against distortions of science that are propagated by politicians

01:59:40.480 --> 01:59:43.080
[Guest]: or people on the left or people on the right.

01:59:43.080 --> 01:59:47.080
[Guest]: I think the Lysenko episode is remarkable precisely because it was the only time where

01:59:47.080 --> 01:59:50.400
[Guest]: he allowed his political beliefs to override his scientific beliefs.

01:59:50.400 --> 01:59:55.200
[Guest]: If he had acted in character in that episode, as in every other episode, he would have stood

01:59:55.200 --> 02:00:00.000
[Guest]: up against the Soviet Union, perhaps quit the party, and said that this was a clear

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:03.200
[Guest]: violation of scientific knowledge and rigor.

02:00:03.200 --> 02:00:04.640
[Amit Varma]: He didn't do that.

02:00:04.640 --> 02:00:06.720
[Amit Varma]: He did praise Stalin after he died as well.

02:00:06.720 --> 02:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: So it's, you know, so I have a question for you.

02:00:09.880 --> 02:00:13.560
[Amit Varma]: But before that, sort of, I want to move on to Haldane's writing now.

02:00:13.560 --> 02:00:18.480
[Amit Varma]: And you had cited this excellent article he wrote, which was almost meta because he was

02:00:18.480 --> 02:00:21.880
[Amit Varma]: extremely prolific in terms of writing and even giving talks.

02:00:21.880 --> 02:00:24.880
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned there was a year where he gave 100 talks.

02:00:24.880 --> 02:00:30.040
[Amit Varma]: And he then got meta and wrote this piece called how to write a popular scientific article.

02:00:30.040 --> 02:00:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And you're right, his first piece of stern advice, know a great deal more about your

02:00:33.600 --> 02:00:38.280
[Amit Varma]: subject than you put on paper, then look for a familiar analogy or pull it out of the facts

02:00:38.280 --> 02:00:40.440
[Amit Varma]: of everyday experience.

02:00:40.440 --> 02:00:44.440
[Amit Varma]: And now you quote Haldane, compare the production of hot gas in the bomb to that of steam in

02:00:44.440 --> 02:00:49.080
[Amit Varma]: a kettle, the changes which occur in the bird each year to those which take place in men

02:00:49.080 --> 02:00:55.160
[Amit Varma]: once in a lifetime at puberty, the precipitation of casein by calcium salts to the formation

02:00:55.160 --> 02:00:56.320
[Amit Varma]: of soap suds.

02:00:56.320 --> 02:01:00.720
[Amit Varma]: If you know enough, you will be able to proceed to your goal in a series of hops, rather than

02:01:00.720 --> 02:01:03.280
[Amit Varma]: a single long jump, stop good.

02:01:03.280 --> 02:01:08.680
[Amit Varma]: And you also sort of talk about his philosophy towards his craft, which, you know, I think

02:01:08.680 --> 02:01:12.360
[Amit Varma]: Hemingway who he hung out with during the Spanish Civil War, I mean, he seems to have

02:01:12.360 --> 02:01:13.360
[Amit Varma]: been like Forrest Gump.

02:01:13.360 --> 02:01:14.360
[Amit Varma]: He was everywhere.

02:01:14.360 --> 02:01:15.360
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

02:01:15.360 --> 02:01:17.880
[Guest]: He was very much a kind of Kilroy was your type of guy.

02:01:17.880 --> 02:01:18.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:01:18.880 --> 02:01:22.380
[Amit Varma]: So you know, the picture that one gets of him as a writer about sciences of a person

02:01:22.380 --> 02:01:25.380
[Amit Varma]: of remarkable craft and knowledge and bringing it to bear.

02:01:25.380 --> 02:01:29.840
[Amit Varma]: In another part of the book, you write about sort of political writing about communism,

02:01:29.840 --> 02:01:33.920
[Amit Varma]: which is, again, though you didn't use those words, I'm kind of just thinking aloud, but

02:01:33.920 --> 02:01:38.800
[Amit Varma]: were more woolly would have tended to be more abstract than concrete, unlike in these, you

02:01:38.800 --> 02:01:41.320
[Amit Varma]: know, amazing scientific examples that we used.

02:01:41.320 --> 02:01:45.480
[Amit Varma]: So while you were going through the archives, is that a difference that you noticed?

02:01:45.480 --> 02:01:49.400
[Amit Varma]: Did it feel like you know, the Haldane who was writing about science and about things

02:01:49.400 --> 02:01:53.720
[Amit Varma]: of which he had deep knowledge was, you know, was the writing different?

02:01:53.720 --> 02:01:55.640
[Guest]: I think the purpose was different.

02:01:55.640 --> 02:02:00.600
[Guest]: I think when he was writing about science for the lay public, I think his effort was

02:02:00.600 --> 02:02:06.600
[Guest]: to get to explain and to get people to understand, but more importantly, to get people to understand

02:02:06.600 --> 02:02:10.920
[Guest]: how scientists think, you know, the kind of series of logical steps in the weighing of

02:02:10.920 --> 02:02:12.440
[Guest]: evidence that scientists often do.

02:02:12.440 --> 02:02:15.640
[Guest]: I think when he spoke about when he wrote about politics or spoke about politics, his

02:02:15.640 --> 02:02:20.080
[Guest]: purpose was to convince, to persuade, to bring people to his point of view.

02:02:20.080 --> 02:02:26.160
[Guest]: And I think necessarily for that reason, he often allowed himself to slip into what might

02:02:26.160 --> 02:02:28.080
[Guest]: sometimes be called propaganda.

02:02:28.080 --> 02:02:31.920
[Guest]: Not always and not with every political article, for example, a lot of the political pieces

02:02:31.920 --> 02:02:35.000
[Guest]: he wrote about Nazi science, about racial science.

02:02:35.000 --> 02:02:37.240
[Guest]: He was very clear about and he was quite over there.

02:02:37.240 --> 02:02:41.480
[Guest]: He was sharp and clear and unambiguous and scientific even.

02:02:41.480 --> 02:02:47.480
[Guest]: But I think every time he tried to refer to the Soviet Union and to communism as an ideology

02:02:47.480 --> 02:02:54.200
[Guest]: to be admired, he let himself slip into propagandistic mode, which was, I mean, and the distinction

02:02:54.200 --> 02:02:55.200
[Guest]: is quite clear.

02:02:55.200 --> 02:02:58.840
[Guest]: You read a lot of his essays and the essay for essays, for the most part, will stick

02:02:58.840 --> 02:03:03.080
[Guest]: with science and they'll be clear and precise and little gems of explication.

02:03:03.080 --> 02:03:06.800
[Guest]: And then towards the end, he'll want to draw a political moral out of it just to buttress

02:03:06.800 --> 02:03:08.680
[Guest]: his own political philosophy.

02:03:08.680 --> 02:03:13.480
[Guest]: And at that particular instance, he will slip into a kind of nebulousness in his language

02:03:13.480 --> 02:03:14.800
[Guest]: that he would otherwise have deployed.

02:03:14.800 --> 02:03:19.120
[Amit Varma]: While you finish the book, and we're kind of getting to the later stage of his life.

02:03:19.120 --> 02:03:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And while you finish the book, did you sort of get a sense of the evolution of his character,

02:03:25.400 --> 02:03:28.720
[Amit Varma]: like quite apart from the things that he's doing in, say, the scientific domain or the

02:03:28.720 --> 02:03:30.120
[Amit Varma]: political domain?

02:03:30.120 --> 02:03:34.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, you've spoken about how is the transition between his marriages and all of that.

02:03:34.200 --> 02:03:37.960
[Amit Varma]: But do you get a sense of him as a person, for example, one thing you pointed out is

02:03:37.960 --> 02:03:44.040
[Amit Varma]: that many people would wonder about why he chose to come to India of all places in 1957.

02:03:44.040 --> 02:03:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And one reason that you point out, which you discovered when you went through his bank

02:03:48.120 --> 02:03:53.600
[Amit Varma]: statements and, you know, all of those papers, which are, you know, otherwise inaccessible,

02:03:53.600 --> 02:03:55.440
[Amit Varma]: is that he was actually very short of money.

02:03:55.440 --> 02:04:00.040
[Amit Varma]: You describe how, you know, partly because he had alimony payments going out to his first

02:04:00.040 --> 02:04:01.040
[Amit Varma]: wife and all of that.

02:04:01.040 --> 02:04:05.760
[Amit Varma]: And you describe at one point about how an American journalist wrote to him with a bunch

02:04:05.760 --> 02:04:06.960
[Amit Varma]: of questions.

02:04:06.960 --> 02:04:10.480
[Amit Varma]: And he said that, listen, it would take me hours to answer these personal questions.

02:04:10.480 --> 02:04:14.160
[Amit Varma]: Are you willing to, you know, kind of pay for it, which reminded me of an experience I had

02:04:14.160 --> 02:04:15.160
[Amit Varma]: in Cricken 4.

02:04:15.160 --> 02:04:19.560
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if you ever had a similar experience or rather at Wizarding, when I called up one

02:04:19.560 --> 02:04:23.480
[Amit Varma]: of the famous spin quartet for quotes.

02:04:23.480 --> 02:04:26.360
[Amit Varma]: And he said, tell me about vitamin M. Wow.

02:04:26.360 --> 02:04:28.080
[Amit Varma]: And I said, what?

02:04:28.080 --> 02:04:32.760
[Amit Varma]: And then I realized and I felt so sad, I felt like crying because yeah, a legend of the

02:04:32.760 --> 02:04:33.760
[Amit Varma]: game.

02:04:33.760 --> 02:04:34.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:04:34.760 --> 02:04:39.560
[Amit Varma]: And so it kind of strikes me that after this immense career, where he's been a hugely successful

02:04:39.560 --> 02:04:44.000
[Amit Varma]: public intellectual, and all of that has happened, and he stood up against fascism and fascism

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:45.040
[Amit Varma]: has lost.

02:04:45.040 --> 02:04:49.040
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, communism is crumbling, and he's not crumbling, but has revealed his

02:04:49.040 --> 02:04:50.040
[Amit Varma]: true face.

02:04:50.040 --> 02:04:52.040
[Amit Varma]: And he's sort of in denial about that.

02:04:52.040 --> 02:04:57.160
[Amit Varma]: Does one get a sense of sort of the human side of this great man, like one of the quotes

02:04:57.160 --> 02:05:01.820
[Amit Varma]: I most loved in your book was when he talks about going to India.

02:05:01.820 --> 02:05:06.880
[Amit Varma]: And he says, one of my reasons for settling in India was to avoid wearing socks, 60 years

02:05:06.880 --> 02:05:09.240
[Amit Varma]: and socks is enough, stop quote.

02:05:09.240 --> 02:05:10.240
[Amit Varma]: And I love that quote.

02:05:10.240 --> 02:05:12.000
[Guest]: It gives such a great sense of the guy.

02:05:12.000 --> 02:05:13.760
[Guest]: I mean, it's absolutely right.

02:05:13.760 --> 02:05:17.560
[Guest]: The context, the broader context for his brokenness itself also should be explained, I feel, which

02:05:17.560 --> 02:05:20.480
[Guest]: is, of course, the alimony is one part of it.

02:05:20.480 --> 02:05:24.040
[Guest]: But all the money he made, he gave to his own university, the university that was supposed

02:05:24.040 --> 02:05:29.520
[Guest]: to be paying him, he was giving money to the university to make sure that labs could remain

02:05:29.520 --> 02:05:30.520
[Guest]: funded.

02:05:30.520 --> 02:05:34.760
[Guest]: He once gave, he bought a set of teaspoons for 10 shillings for the men's staff room,

02:05:34.760 --> 02:05:38.600
[Guest]: the men's teacher staff room in the university, because they had no teaspoons in the university.

02:05:38.600 --> 02:05:43.080
[Guest]: This was a post-war period, University College London had been heavily bombed, you know,

02:05:43.080 --> 02:05:47.040
[Guest]: the nearest tennis court, as I said, was 14 miles away, it was, it was just a complete

02:05:47.040 --> 02:05:49.800
[Guest]: shell of itself and rebuilding was going on.

02:05:49.800 --> 02:05:54.040
[Guest]: At this time, funds for doing science were quite limited.

02:05:54.040 --> 02:05:58.560
[Guest]: And so he would, you know, he once gave 300, which was an eighth of his annual salary,

02:05:58.560 --> 02:06:02.780
[Guest]: he gave back to the university to make sure his department could continue doing research.

02:06:02.780 --> 02:06:06.960
[Guest]: So a lot of this money, the aspects of money that I talk about in the book are not for

02:06:06.960 --> 02:06:12.560
[Guest]: personal enrichment, because he was a bizarrely low maintenance guy in that sense, you know,

02:06:12.560 --> 02:06:16.400
[Guest]: all through his life, not just in India, where he was definitely sort of living a very simple

02:06:16.400 --> 02:06:17.920
[Guest]: life, but even before that.

02:06:17.920 --> 02:06:22.720
[Guest]: But I think he felt that there wasn't enough money for, to do the science that he wanted

02:06:22.720 --> 02:06:23.800
[Guest]: to do.

02:06:23.800 --> 02:06:28.320
[Guest]: And all of the money that he would get from writing articles, he would make over to some

02:06:28.320 --> 02:06:32.320
[Guest]: grad student of his or to some lab, there are letters to that effect saying, listen,

02:06:32.320 --> 02:06:35.360
[Guest]: I know you owe me this much money, can you make it over to University College London?

02:06:35.360 --> 02:06:39.080
[Guest]: And similarly, for these, you know, this money that he asked for when he did interviews,

02:06:39.080 --> 02:06:42.520
[Guest]: the money, the money was not for his own bank account, it was actually, so in that sense,

02:06:42.520 --> 02:06:48.240
[Guest]: he was a remarkably uniform character throughout his life, he never cared, he was never fastidious

02:06:48.240 --> 02:06:49.240
[Guest]: about himself.

02:06:49.240 --> 02:06:55.520
[Guest]: He drove old beaten up cars, lived in almost slovenly mess, and continued to do that well

02:06:55.520 --> 02:06:56.520
[Guest]: into India.

02:06:56.520 --> 02:07:01.040
[Guest]: In fact, the thing that attracted him to India was, you know, you mentioned this line about

02:07:01.040 --> 02:07:05.320
[Guest]: socks, which is a beautiful sort of bon mot, you just kind of tossed it away.

02:07:05.320 --> 02:07:09.440
[Guest]: The thing that is inherent in it is that a certain simplicity of lifestyle is what attracted

02:07:09.440 --> 02:07:12.760
[Guest]: him to the fact that, for example, you didn't need winter clothing, you could just sort

02:07:12.760 --> 02:07:16.920
[Guest]: of go all year round in cottons and maybe one jacket or whatever it was when he was

02:07:16.920 --> 02:07:17.920
[Guest]: living in Calcutta.

02:07:17.920 --> 02:07:22.760
[Guest]: You didn't have to have expensive furniture, you didn't have in a relatively poor country,

02:07:22.760 --> 02:07:27.720
[Guest]: he could live the sort of relatively poor lifestyle that he had always lived.

02:07:27.720 --> 02:07:31.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, and it also struck me and this is a complete aside that one of the letters you've

02:07:31.560 --> 02:07:35.400
[Amit Varma]: quoted from him is where he's writing to Mahalonubis and he's saying that please forgive me for

02:07:35.400 --> 02:07:36.400
[Amit Varma]: not being more productive.

02:07:36.400 --> 02:07:39.320
[Amit Varma]: It's just too freaking hot, not in those words.

02:07:39.320 --> 02:07:44.320
[Amit Varma]: But I just thought that my God, I think another thing that is unseen by most people is a massive

02:07:44.320 --> 02:07:49.520
[Amit Varma]: difference that the invention of air conditioning has just made to humanity in general.

02:07:49.520 --> 02:07:53.400
[Guest]: As Lee Kuan Yew said, it is the greatest invention of the 20th century, at least from the point

02:07:53.400 --> 02:07:58.480
[Guest]: of view of Singapore and other Asian nations, because it transitioned them from being sort

02:07:58.480 --> 02:08:02.880
[Guest]: of an economy that had to do work outside or not at all to be able to work indoors.

02:08:02.880 --> 02:08:06.200
[Guest]: I mean, it's an entire lifestyle and professional change.

02:08:06.200 --> 02:08:07.200
[Amit Varma]: It's just magnificent.

02:08:07.200 --> 02:08:10.000
[Amit Varma]: My two great inventions are the AC and the jet spray.

02:08:10.000 --> 02:08:15.000
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, so here's the thing, I read your book and in fact, I read it yesterday because

02:08:15.000 --> 02:08:16.000
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to save it.

02:08:16.000 --> 02:08:20.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, I bought it months ago when it came out, but I wanted to read it just before our

02:08:20.280 --> 02:08:24.720
[Amit Varma]: conversation so it would be sharp in my memory and I absolutely loved it.

02:08:24.720 --> 02:08:27.840
[Amit Varma]: It's so beautifully written and so many insights and I learned a lot from it.

02:08:27.840 --> 02:08:33.320
[Amit Varma]: But my question to you to throw that back to you is in the process of writing it, A,

02:08:33.320 --> 02:08:37.960
[Amit Varma]: how did your thinking about the world and society and perhaps science expand?

02:08:37.960 --> 02:08:41.520
[Amit Varma]: And B, just about the craft of writing, I mean, you've written two excellent books before

02:08:41.520 --> 02:08:43.760
[Amit Varma]: this mind you, which we didn't even mention.

02:08:43.760 --> 02:08:48.440
[Amit Varma]: But in the sense that this was just such a different project also, how did your sense

02:08:48.440 --> 02:08:53.600
[Amit Varma]: of you know, your own writing and the craft of writing in general, how did those end of

02:08:53.600 --> 02:08:54.600
[Guest]: evolve?

02:08:54.600 --> 02:08:59.040
[Guest]: Well, to answer the second question first, I mean, the writing was, as I mentioned earlier

02:08:59.040 --> 02:09:03.000
[Guest]: on the podcast, it was an extremely interesting process because I had to depend on what I

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:07.400
[Guest]: read to make things vivid for the reader to bring this character to life who I'd never

02:09:07.400 --> 02:09:12.560
[Guest]: met to get an insight into him and to write about him that word again, in an almost fictive

02:09:12.560 --> 02:09:16.120
[Guest]: sense and convey him as a character and a person.

02:09:16.120 --> 02:09:17.960
[Guest]: So you know, a lot of this was quite challenging.

02:09:17.960 --> 02:09:21.400
[Guest]: When I was doing it for the first time, I would read extensively from other books that

02:09:21.400 --> 02:09:23.680
[Guest]: I thought had done this well.

02:09:23.680 --> 02:09:28.360
[Guest]: And you know, it took much longer to write as a book than either of my previous two books.

02:09:28.360 --> 02:09:31.960
[Guest]: And partly that was down to the writing, partly also it was a material, I'm not a scientist,

02:09:31.960 --> 02:09:34.880
[Guest]: you know, I haven't been trained as a biologist, certainly.

02:09:34.880 --> 02:09:39.320
[Guest]: And so to understand a lot of the subjects that he worked on in the papers that he wrote,

02:09:39.320 --> 02:09:45.200
[Guest]: I had to train myself, I mean, obviously not to the level of a scientist, but to the level

02:09:45.200 --> 02:09:48.480
[Guest]: of somebody who could at least understand the science and simplify it.

02:09:48.480 --> 02:09:51.880
[Guest]: And that involved very often talking to other scientists to get them to explain it to me

02:09:51.880 --> 02:09:56.200
[Guest]: as if I was a first year college student, to read papers again and again, and to kind

02:09:56.200 --> 02:10:01.240
[Guest]: of enough scientists, friends who I could call at a moment's notice to ask them, you

02:10:01.240 --> 02:10:03.520
[Guest]: know, doubts about one thing or the other.

02:10:03.520 --> 02:10:07.280
[Guest]: All of this was very different from my previous two books.

02:10:07.280 --> 02:10:11.520
[Guest]: And then the act of boiling that science down itself is something else altogether.

02:10:11.520 --> 02:10:15.160
[Guest]: I mean, it's something that I've never done before, because it's inherently more complex

02:10:15.160 --> 02:10:18.480
[Guest]: and technical than the Sri Lankan civil war, for example.

02:10:18.480 --> 02:10:23.040
[Guest]: So to constantly find real world examples, very much as Haldane did, in fact, to find

02:10:23.040 --> 02:10:28.480
[Guest]: real world examples in his papers, or to find real world examples that his papers retrospectively

02:10:28.480 --> 02:10:32.760
[Guest]: applied to, or went on to apply to, I mean, all of these things were challenges that I

02:10:32.760 --> 02:10:36.680
[Guest]: set myself precisely for this purpose, because I felt that I'd never done this before.

02:10:36.680 --> 02:10:42.960
[Guest]: And I wanted to see what the limits of my language and my prose and my writing were.

02:10:42.960 --> 02:10:44.600
[Guest]: So that was really difficult.

02:10:44.600 --> 02:10:48.360
[Guest]: And I think in terms of how I myself changed over the course of researching this book is,

02:10:48.360 --> 02:10:52.600
[Guest]: well, I mean, we talked about this earlier, I mean, a lot of these thoughts and ideas

02:10:52.600 --> 02:10:58.200
[Guest]: about the frailty of our political stances, and how contingent they are just on what we

02:10:58.200 --> 02:11:03.240
[Guest]: are wedded to, you know, I've been thinking about that perhaps superficially even before.

02:11:03.240 --> 02:11:08.400
[Guest]: And certainly events since 2014, have helped me clarify some of these a lot more, be the

02:11:08.400 --> 02:11:11.160
[Guest]: events in India or in the UK or in the US.

02:11:11.160 --> 02:11:15.240
[Guest]: But writing through this book helped me understand it from the point of view of something that

02:11:15.240 --> 02:11:17.440
[Guest]: happened within one person's lifetime.

02:11:17.440 --> 02:11:20.880
[Guest]: And kind of, you can look back on your life, but it's still only a limited life, you haven't

02:11:20.880 --> 02:11:23.440
[Guest]: seen the full extent of your own life.

02:11:23.440 --> 02:11:26.840
[Guest]: Whereas writing through someone like Haldane's life enabled me to see the whole thing in

02:11:26.840 --> 02:11:28.280
[Guest]: its entirety.

02:11:28.280 --> 02:11:31.480
[Guest]: And I grew immensely fond of him.

02:11:31.480 --> 02:11:36.720
[Guest]: I mean, I can't say something, this is the most unusual thing, the most unexpected thing

02:11:36.720 --> 02:11:38.520
[Guest]: that came out of this process.

02:11:38.520 --> 02:11:41.360
[Guest]: You know, of course, everybody says, if you write a biography of somebody, you should

02:11:41.360 --> 02:11:44.280
[Guest]: be fond of the person, it doesn't apply to people like Hitler.

02:11:44.280 --> 02:11:49.400
[Guest]: But obviously, to spend that much time inside one person's mind, you are fond of them, I

02:11:49.400 --> 02:11:50.400
[Guest]: agree.

02:11:50.400 --> 02:11:55.080
[Guest]: But I told Ram Guha this, I said, like, you know, Ram, you never told me how sad a biographer

02:11:55.080 --> 02:12:01.040
[Guest]: feels when he or she reaches the end of the subject's life.

02:12:01.040 --> 02:12:04.920
[Guest]: It felt like somebody very close to me had died, and I was somehow witness to it and

02:12:04.920 --> 02:12:05.920
[Guest]: not.

02:12:05.920 --> 02:12:09.280
[Guest]: I wrote a small piece about this somewhere else about Haldane's handwriting, and so just

02:12:09.280 --> 02:12:11.560
[Guest]: how I grew to adore it.

02:12:11.560 --> 02:12:16.960
[Guest]: And how, you know, describing the end of his life felt to me, and this is a terrible example.

02:12:16.960 --> 02:12:21.520
[Guest]: So I apologize in advance for anyone who has ever lost a child.

02:12:21.520 --> 02:12:24.600
[Guest]: This is in no way comparing the scale of the two things.

02:12:24.600 --> 02:12:31.160
[Guest]: But only in these two instances, do you see the entirety of a person's life from birth

02:12:31.160 --> 02:12:34.800
[Guest]: to death, and be there to observe the death itself.

02:12:34.800 --> 02:12:39.400
[Guest]: Of course, mine is in a much more sort of superficial case of the same, but I, you know,

02:12:39.400 --> 02:12:45.760
[Guest]: you see the person being born, I saw JBS's sort of childhood letters, I saw the mistakes

02:12:45.760 --> 02:12:50.240
[Guest]: he made when he was a kid, I saw how he was bullied when he was at Eton, I saw the person

02:12:50.240 --> 02:12:55.000
[Guest]: he went on to become, I saw the mistakes he made in his personal and professional life.

02:12:55.000 --> 02:12:56.520
[Guest]: And I saw the way he died.

02:12:56.520 --> 02:12:59.280
[Guest]: When else do you ever get to experience this?

02:12:59.280 --> 02:13:03.480
[Guest]: So there was a real sense of acute loss, I felt when I was writing that last scene when

02:13:03.480 --> 02:13:08.480
[Guest]: he died, you know, and that again, sort of, there's so much about the biographical graph

02:13:08.480 --> 02:13:12.080
[Guest]: that we can discuss, although you should probably talk to people who've written more than one

02:13:12.080 --> 02:13:16.800
[Guest]: biography, but that I think, a real emotional charge to it that I didn't expect.

02:13:16.800 --> 02:13:21.240
[Amit Varma]: That's quite moving. And I'll also, in the show notes, I'll link to this talk you gave

02:13:21.240 --> 02:13:25.080
[Amit Varma]: on the book, which is on YouTube, where you have this fascinating slide, which has three

02:13:25.080 --> 02:13:29.320
[Amit Varma]: handwritten letters by him at different points in time, it actually gets neater as it goes

02:13:29.320 --> 02:13:32.720
[Amit Varma]: along. And I thought it'd be like a bell curve where the, you know, the middle one when he's

02:13:32.720 --> 02:13:37.920
[Amit Varma]: this thing will be the best, but it's extremely lucid and readable at the end.

02:13:37.920 --> 02:13:42.120
[Amit Varma]: And you know, maybe this is a reason Robert Caro hasn't yet finished his biography of

02:13:42.120 --> 02:13:44.360
[Amit Varma]: Lyndon Johnson, he doesn't want to say goodbye to the guy.

02:13:44.360 --> 02:13:48.000
[Guest]: Well, Robert Caro, I mean, I once had the extreme good fortune to sit next to him at

02:13:48.000 --> 02:13:52.920
[Guest]: a dinner. And he told me about, you know, he was he was talking about the first book

02:13:52.920 --> 02:13:56.880
[Guest]: and he said about how he didn't understand LBJ's background at all, sort of Texas and

02:13:56.880 --> 02:14:01.160
[Guest]: small town Texas that he came out of. And he said, Well, so I only saw one solution

02:14:01.160 --> 02:14:04.800
[Guest]: to this. And I said, What was that? He said, Well, I moved there. So what I moved there

02:14:04.800 --> 02:14:09.800
[Guest]: for three years, he lived in a small town in Texas for three years, just to understand

02:14:09.800 --> 02:14:15.200
[Guest]: that Texan background that LBJ would grow up in. So I mean, that kind of commitment

02:14:15.200 --> 02:14:17.760
[Guest]: to the biographical craft is something else entirely.

02:14:17.760 --> 02:14:18.760
[Guest]: Could you do that?

02:14:18.760 --> 02:14:21.600
[Guest]: Oh, man, I mean, you know, look, if publishers are willing to pay me enough, I will go anywhere

02:14:21.600 --> 02:14:26.400
[Guest]: to, you know, he was not being paid at that time, I have to point out, I mean, he was

02:14:26.400 --> 02:14:30.720
[Guest]: still sort of, but this was just what he wanted to do. This is he had also been a journalist

02:14:30.720 --> 02:14:34.880
[Guest]: for a while. And he decided he just wanted to get into the nuts and bolts of a person's

02:14:34.880 --> 02:14:38.200
[Guest]: life to that level. It's really admirable.

